Definition: To jostle by riding against one.
Having two significations equally applicable; capable of double interpretation; of doubtful meaning; ambiguous; uncertain.
A back with a hunch or hump; also a hunchbacked person.
A backward slope in the face of a wall or of a bank; receding slope.
A bag or sac in animals which serves as the receptacle of some fluid.
A bag or sack for carrying about the person as a bag for carrying the necessaries for a journey; a knapsack; a beggar's receptacle for charity; a peddler's pack.
A bag; a pouch.
A ball filled with powder or other combustibles intended to be thrown among enemies and to injure by explosion; also to set fire to their works and light them up so that movements may be seen.
A ball or globe forming part of the regalia of an emperor or other sovereign. It is encircled with bands enriched with precious stones and surmounted with a cross; -- called also globe.
A ball payer who stands out in the field to catch or stop balls.
A band of singers and dancers.
A band or strap which encircles the body; especially one by which a saddle is fastened upon the back of a horse.
A band used to prevent a stocking from slipping down on the leg.
A bank of drifted snow.
A bar of iron sharpened at one end and used as a lever.
A bar or frame of wood by which two oxen are joined at the heads or necks for working together.
A bark; a yelp.
A barkeeper.
A baron's wife; also a lady who holds the baronial title in her own right.
A barrier made of a rail or of rails.
A basket made of rushes used chiefly for containing figs and raisins.
A basket used in offices libraries etc. as a receptacle for waste paper.
A bay recess or inlet of the sea or the mouth of a river which affords anchorage and shelter for shipping; a harbor; a port.
A beam or ray of the sun.
A beat or strong pulsation as of the heart and arteries; a violent beating; a papitation:
A beat of drum or sound of a trumpet or bugle at night giving notice to soldiers to retreat or to repair to their quarters in garrison or to their tents in camp.
A beating or throbbing especially of the heart or of an artery or in an inflamed part; a beat of the pulse.
A bed and its furniture; the materials of a bed whether for man or beast; bedclothes; litter.
A bed of earth heated by fermenting manure or other substances and covered with glass intended for raising early plants or for nourishing exotics.
A bed of oysters or mussels.
A bed of roses or place where roses grow.
A bed or cot for a baby oscillating on rockers or swinging on pivots; hence the place of origin or in which anything is nurtured or protected in the earlier period of existence.
A bedquilt; a counterpane; a coverlet.
A being subject to death; a human being; man.
A bench on which work is performed as in a carpenter's shop.
A bend turn or curve; curvature; flexure.
A bending or sinking between the ends of a thing in consequence of its own or an imposed weight; an arching downward in the middle as of a ship after straining. Cf. Hogging.

A bent portion of an axle or shaft or an arm keyed at right angles to the end of a shaft by which motion is imparted to or received from it; also used to change circular into reciprocating motion or reciprocating into circular motion.
A bereaved child; one who has lost father or mother.
A beverage consisting of lemon juice mixed with water and sweetened.
A biennial plant of the genus Beta which produces an edible root the first year and seed the second year.
A binary compound of chlorine with another element or radical.
A binary compound of fluorine with another element or radical.
A binary compound of oxygen with an atom or radical or a compound which is regarded as binary.
A binocular glass whether opera glass telescope or microscope.
A biography written by the subject of it; memoirs of one's life written by one's self.
A bird belonging to Cuculus Coccyzus and several allied genera of many species.
A bird of prey of the Hawk family belonging to the genus Buteo and related genera.
A bird of the genus Emberiza or of an allied genus related to the finches and sparrows (family Fringillidae).

A bird of the Parrot family of the subfamily Cacatuinae having a short strong and much curved beak and the head ornamented with a crest which can be raised or depressed at will. There are several genera and many species.
A bird.
A bitter white crystalline alkaloid found in opium possessing strong narcotic properties and much used as an anodyne; -- called also morphia and morphina.

A bitter white crystalline substance obtained from the saccharinates and regarded as the lactone of saccharinic acid; -- so called because formerly supposed to be isomeric with cane sugar (saccharose).
A bivalve mollusk of many kinds especially those that are edible.
A black granular explosive substance consisting of an intimate mechanical mixture of niter charcoal and sulphur. It is used in gunnery and blasting.

A black substance formed by combustion or disengaged from fuel in the process of combustion which rises in fine particles and adheres to the sides of the chimney or pipe conveying the smoke; strictly the fine powder consisting chiefly of carbon which colors smoke and which is the result of imperfect combustion.
A blacksmith's fuller or chisel having a square shank for insertion into a square hole in an anvil called the hardy hole.
A blank book in which extracts cut from books and papers may be pasted and kept.
A blank window or panel.
A blast; destruction by a blast or by some pernicious cause.
A bleeding at the nose.
A blood feud; private revenge for the murder of a kinsman.

A blood-sucking dipterous fly of the genus Culex undergoing a metamorphosis in water. The females have a proboscis armed with needlelike organs for penetrating the skin of animals. These are wanting in the males. In America they are generally called mosquitoes.

A blood-sucking ghost; a soul of a dead person superstitiously believed to come from the grave and wander about by night sucking the blood of persons asleep thus causing their death. This superstition is now prevalent in parts of Eastern Europe and was especially current in Hungary about the year 1730.
A blossom; the flower of a plant; an expanded bud; flowers collectively.
A blot or spot as of color or of ink; especially a large or irregular spot. Also Fig..
A blow as with a club; a heavy blow.
A blow on the face.
A blow with the open hand; a slap.
A blow; a stroke.
A blow; esp. a blow with the open hand; a box; a slap.
A blustering demonstration or great effort; a great display.
A board placed on the fore part of a carriage sleigh or other vehicle to intercept water mud or snow thrown up by the heels of the horses; -- in England commonly called splashboard.
A board which supports the back wen one is sitting;
A boast or boasting; bragging; ostentatious pretense or self glorification.
A boaster.
A boat designed to be propelled by oars instead of sails.
A boat or vessel propelled by steam power; -- generally used of river or coasting craft as distinguished from ocean steamers.
A boat propelled by a sail or sails.
A boat used by rude nations formed of trunk of a tree excavated by cutting of burning into a suitable shape. It is propelled by a paddle or paddles or sometimes by sail and has no rudder.
A body of about five or six hundred soldiers; the tenth part of a legion.
A body of children.
A body of foot soldiers and cavalry consisting of different numbers at different periods -- from about four thousand to about six thousand men -- the cavalry being about one tenth.
A body of troops whether cavalry artillery infantry or mixed consisting of two or more regiments under the command of a brigadier general.
A body of troops; esp. a body of troops or an army in battle array.
A body or figure in the shape of an egg or popularly of an ellipse.
A body or order of cavaliers or knights serving on horseback; illustrious warriors collectively; cavalry.
A body projected or impelled forward by force; especially a missile adapted to be shot from a firearm.
A body so suspended from a fixed point as to swing freely to and fro by the alternate action of gravity and momentum. It is used to regulate the movements of clockwork and other machinery.
A boiling spring which throws forth at frequent intervals jets of water mud etc. driven up by the expansive power of steam.
A bomb.
A bonbon cake or the like; -- usually in the pl.
A bone in the base of the lower jaw of many birds reptiles and fishes.
A book containing laws and usages or customs.
A book containing stories or short narratives either true or false.
A book containing the names and descriptions of plants.

A book in which a summary of accounts is laid up or preserved; the final book of record in business transactions in which all debits and credits from the journal etc. are placed under appropriate heads.
A book of directions and information for travelers tourists etc.
A book of directions and receipts for cooking; a cookery book.
A book of reference to be carried in the hand; a manual; a guidebook.
A book of sketches or for sketches.

A book or table containing a calendar of days and months to which astronomical data and various statistics are often added such as the times of the rising and setting of the sun and moon eclipses hours of full tide stated festivals of churches terms of courts etc.
A book published yearly; any annual report or summary of the statistics or facts of a year designed to be used as a reference book.
A book; a manuscript.
A bottomless or unfathomed depth gulf or chasm; hence any deep immeasurable and specifically hell or the bottomless pit.
A bounding with juice; succulent.

A bow or arch exhibiting in concentric bands the several colors of the spectrum and formed in the part of the hemisphere opposite to the sun by the refraction and reflection of the sun's rays in drops of falling rain.
A bowman one skilled in the use of the bow and arrow.
A box basket or other structure for the reception and habitation of a swarm of honeybees.
A box or inclosure wholly or partly of openwork in wood or metal used for confining birds or other animals.
A boy belonging to or attending a school.
A boy or young man; a waiter; a servant; especially a man or boy who has charge of horses or the stable.
A boy who distributes or sells newspaper.
A branching perennial plant (Cichorium Intybus) with bright blue flowers growing wild in Europe Asia and America; also cultivated for its roots and as a salad plant; succory; wild endive.
A breaker or destroyer of images or idols; a determined enemy of idol worship.
A breaking or bursting forth; a violent rush or flood of waters which breaks down opposing barriers and hurls forward and disperses blocks of stone and other debris.
A breathing place or hole; a nostril as of a bird.
A breed of dogs having curly hair and often showing remarkable intelligence in the performance of tricks.

A breed of large and powerful dogs with long smooth and pendulous ears and remarkable for acuteness of smell. It is employed to recover game or prey which has escaped wounded from a hunter and for tracking criminals. Formerly it was used for pursuing runaway slaves. Other varieties of dog are often used for the same purpose and go by the same name. The Cuban bloodhound is said to be a variety of the mastiff.
A breed of large dogs noted for strength and courage. There are various strains differing in form and color and characteristic of different countries.
A breed or an animal produced from parents of different breeds; a new variety as of plants combining the qualities of two parent varieties or stocks.
A brewer's cooling vat; a keelfat.
A brewhouse; the building and apparatus where brewing is carried on.

A bridge of which either the whole or a part is made to be raised up let down or drawn or turned aside to admit or hinder communication at pleasure as before the gate of a town or castle or over a navigable river or canal.
A bridge.
A brief poetical sentiment; hence any brief sentiment motto or legend; especially one inscribed on a ring.
A brief statement of facts respecting some passing event as military operations or the health of some distinguished personage issued by authority for the information of the public.
A brief writing of any kind esp. a declaration bill certificate request supplication etc.
A bright dazzling light; splendor that dazzles the eyes; a confusing and bewildering light.
A bright sparkling light; brilliant and showy luster; brilliancy.

A bright silver-white metallic element. It is of the iron group and is hard malleable and ductile. It occurs combined with sulphur in millerite with arsenic in the mineral niccolite and with arsenic and sulphur in nickel glance. Symbol Ni. Atomic weight 58.6.
A brine or pickle containing wine and spices for enriching the flavor of meat and fish.

A bringer of the glad tidings of Church and his doctrines. Specially: (a) A missionary preacher sent forth to prepare the way for a resident pastor; an itinerant missionary preacher. (b) A writer of one of the four Gospels (With the definite article).
A broad shallow basket.
A broad board painted black or any black surface on which writing drawing or the working of mathematical problems can be done with chalk or crayons. It is much used in schools.
A broad flat limb used for swimming as those of seals sea turtles whales etc.
A broad piece of defensive armor carried on the arm -- formerly in general use in war for the protection of the body.
A broad piece of sawed timber differing from a board only in being thicker.
A broker who deals in stocks.
A brooch clasp or buckle.
A brothel; a bawdyhouse; a house devoted to prostitution.

A brother or member of any religious order but especially of one of the four mendicant orders viz: (a) Minors Gray Friars or Franciscans. (b) Augustines. (c) Dominicans or Black Friars. (d) White Friars or Carmelites.
A brush for cleaning the teeth.
A brush for cleansing and smoothing the hair.
A bubble.
A bud.
A buffoon dressed in party-colored clothes who plays tricks often without speaking to divert the bystanders or an audience; a merry-andrew; originally a droll rogue of Italian comedy.
A buffoon or merry-andrew; one that practices odd gesticulations; the Fool of the old play.
A buffoon; a merry-andrew; a court fool.
A building for keeping goods of any kind especially provisions; a magazine; a repository; a warehouse.
A building for soldiers especially when in garrison. Commonly in the pl. originally meaning temporary huts but now usually applied to a permanent structure or set of buildings.
A building separate from and subordinate to the main house; an outhouse.
A building used for dramatic exhibitions; a theater.
A building where meat or fish is cured by subjecting it to a dense smoke.
A building which is occupied by the guard and in which soldiers are confined for misconduct; hence a lock-up.
A building; a house; an edifice; -- used chiefly in poetry.
A building; a structure; an architectural fabric; -- chiefly applied to elegant houses and other large buildings.
A bulbous iridaceous plant (Crocus sativus) having blue flowers with large yellow stigmas.
A bulbous plant (Galanthus nivalis) bearing white flowers which often appear while the snow is on the ground. It is cultivated in gardens for its beauty.
A bulbous plant of the genus Hyacinthus bearing beautiful spikes of fragrant flowers. H. orientalis is a common variety.
A bumper in honor of a toast or health.
A bundle of grain; a handful of grain laid down by the reaper as it is cut.
A bundle or package of goods in a cloth cover and corded for storage or transportation; also a bundle of straw / hay etc. put up compactly for transportation.
A burlesque translation or imitation of a work.
A burn or injury to the skin or flesh by some hot liquid or by steam.
A burning of the surface; a slight burn.
A burning; esp. the act or practice of cremating the dead.
A burnt sacrifice; an offering the whole of which was consumed by fire among the Jews and some pagan nations.
A burst of sunlight.
A bursting forth.
A burstion inwards as of a vessel from which the air has been exhausted; -- contrasted with explosion.
A buzzing or whizzing sound produced by rapid or whirling motion.
A cake sweetmeat or confection made with almonds or other nuts.
A call or demand (as by continued applause) for a repetition.
A call; a summons; a citation; especially a designation or appointment to a particular state business or profession.
A candlestick lamp stand gas fixture or the like having several branches; esp. one hanging from the ceiling.
A canine tooth.
A canoe or boat dug out from a large log.
A cap which fits the head closely; also formerly a headpiece of iron sewed inside of a cap for protection.
A cap worn in bed to protect the head or in undress.
A captain leader or commander; a chief; the head of a troop army or clan.

A carbonate in which but half the hydrogen of the acid is replaced by a positive element or radical thus making the proportion of the acid to the positive or basic portion twice what it is in the normal carbonates; an acid carbonate; -- sometimes called supercarbonate.
A carbuncle.
A careful looking or watching for any object or event.
A carnivorous animal (Canis latrans) allied to the dog found in the western part of North America; -- called also prairie wolf. Its voice is a snapping bark followed by a prolonged shrill howl.

A carnivorous animal of the genus Vulpes family Canidae of many species. The European fox (V. vulgaris or V. vulpes) the American red fox (V. fulvus) the American gray fox (V. Virginianus) and the arctic white or blue fox (V. lagopus) are well-known species.
A carnivorous animal of the Weasel family (Mustela zibellina) native of the northern latitudes of Europe Asia and America -- noted for its fine soft and valuable fur.

A carnivorous mammal of the genus Putorius allied to the weasel. The European mink is Putorius lutreola. The common American mink (P. vison) varies from yellowish brown to black. Its fur is highly valued. Called also minx nurik and vison.
A carouse; a drinking.
A cart drawn or pushed by hand.
A Carthusian monastery; esp. La Grande Chartreuse mother house of the order in the mountains near Grenoble France.
A carving in relief esp. one on a small scale used as a jewel for personal adornment or like.
A case box or receptacle especially one in which are deposited sacred relics as the bones of a saint.
A case for the reception of a sword hunting knife or other long and slender instrument; a scabbard.
A case of canvas or leather for carrying on the back a soldier's necessaries or the clothing etc. of a traveler.
A case or bag stuffed with some soft and elastic material and used to sit or recline upon; a soft pillow or pad.
A case with shelves for holding books esp. one with glazed doors.
A casket chest or trunk; especially one used for keeping money or other valuables.
A cast from the hand; a throw; also a flounce; a kick.
A caste of priests philosophers and magicians among the ancient Persians; hence any holy men or sages of the East.
A cat; -- a fondling appellation.
A catch; anything that holds as a hook; an impediment; an obstacle; an entanglement.
A cattle herder; a drover; specifically one of an adventurous class of herders and drovers on the plains of the Western and Southwestern United States.
A causal word or form of speech.
A cause of uneasiness and complaint; a wrong done and suffered; that which gives ground for remonstrance or resistance as arising from injustice tyranny etc.; injury.
A cave grotto or subterraneous place of large extent used for the burial of the dead; -- commonly in the plural.
A caviling; a sophism.

A cavity or one of the cavities of an organ as of the larynx or the brain; specifically the posterior chamber or one of the two posterior chambers of the heart which receives the blood from the auricle and forces it out from the heart.
A celebrated fairy the merry wanderer of the night; -- called also Robin Goodfellow Friar Rush Pug etc.
A celebrated whirlpool on the coast of Norway.
A centrifugal machine.

A cephalopod of the genus Sepia having an internal shell large eyes and ten arms furnished with denticulated suckers by means of which it secures its prey. The name is sometimes applied to dibranchiate cephalopods generally.
A ceremony formerly used in conferring knighthood consisting am embrace and a slight blow on the shoulders with the flat blade of a sword.

A certain rate of money corn cattle or other thing anciently paid in the north of England and south of Scotland to certain men who were allied to robbers or moss troopers to be by them protected from pillage.

A certificate of interest due printed at the bottom of transferable bonds (state railroad etc.) given for a term of years designed to be cut off and presented for payment when the interest is due; an interest warrant.
A cetacean or a sirenian.
A cetacean of the genus Delphinus and allied genera (esp. D. delphis); the true dolphin.
A chain or range of rocks lying at or near the surface of the water.
A chair of state commonly a royal seat but sometimes the seat of a prince bishop or other high dignitary.
A chair with arms to support the elbows or forearms.
A change in food produced by the organs of nutrition; digestion.
A channel at the eaves of a roof for conveying away the rain; an eaves channel; an eaves trough.
A character [0] which standing by itself expresses nothing but when placed at the right hand of a whole number increases its value tenfold.

A character or cipher composed of two or more letters interwoven or combined so as to represent a name or a part of it (usually the initials). Monograms are often used on seals ornamental pins rings buttons and by painters engravers etc. to distinguish their works.
A character or point [ ] marking the smallest divisions of a sentence written or printed.
A character or symbol used to represent a sound esp. one used in phonography.
A character used in cursive writing.
A character used in musical notation to determine the position and pitch of the scale as represented on the staff.
A cheating or cheat; trick; fraud.
A check in growth; also that which has been checked in growth; a stunted animal or thing.

A chemical vessel consisting of two portions unequally exposed to the heat of the fire and with connecting pipes or passages through which the fluid rises from the overheated portion and descends from the relatively colder maintaining a circulation.
A chest box coffer bin coop or the like in which things may be stored or animals kept.
A chest or coffer.
A chicken just breaking the shell; a young bird.
A chicken.
A chief angel; one high in the celestial hierarchy.

A chief bishop; a church dignitary of the first class (often called a metropolitan or primate) who superintends the conduct of the suffragan bishops in his province and also exercises episcopal authority in his own diocese.
A child bereaved of both father and mother; sometimes also a child who has but one parent living.
A child's game in which a player hopping on one foot drives a stone from one compartment to another of a figure traced or scotched on the ground; -- called also hoppers.
A child's puppet; a toy baby for a little girl.
A child's word for father.
A chimney; esp. a pipe serving as a chimney as the pipe which carries off the smoke of a locomotive the funnel of a steam vessel etc.
A Chinese and Japanese liquid sauce for fish etc. made by subjecting boiled beans (esp. soja beans) or beans and meal to long fermentation and then long digestion in salt and water.
A Chinese public officer or nobleman; a civil or military official in China and Annam.
A Chinese weight of 2/ pounds.
A Chinook Indian.
A chip; a piece separated by a cutting or graving instrument; a fragment.
A chisel with a hollow or semicylindrical blade for scooping or cutting holes channels or grooves in wood stone etc.; a similar instrument with curved edge for turning wood.
A churl; a common man; a person male or female of low birth.
A cipher writing. Same as Cryptograph.
A circle not having the same center as another contained in some measure within the first.
A circular hole formed in the rocky beds of rivers by the grinding action of stones or gravel whirled round by the water in what was at first a natural depression of the rock.
A circular tread; a gait by which a horse going sideways round a center makes two concentric tracks.
A cistern in the course or the termination of a drain to collect sedimentary or superfluous matter; a privy vault; any receptacle of filth.
A city of Italy which has given its name to various objects.

A class of objects divided into several subordinate species; a class more extensive than a species; a precisely defined and exactly divided class; one of the five predicable conceptions or sorts of terms.
A class or kind described by any definite marks; hence condition; particular situation or state; especially an unfortunate or trying position or condition.
A cleft crack or chink as in the surface of the earth or in the skin.
A cleft; a gap; a ravine; -- rarely used except as part of a proper name.
A clerk a clergyman.
A clock watch or other chronometer; a timepiece.
A clock watch or other instrument to measure or show the progress of time; a chronometer.
A close dark prison common/ under ground as if the lower apartments of the donjon or keep of a castle these being used as prisons.
A close compression as with the ends of the fingers or with an instrument; a nip.
A close embrace or clasping with the arms as in affection or in wrestling.
A close embrace.
A close-fitting covering for the foot and leg usually knit or woven.
A closing or opening or a quick motion of the eye; a wink or sparkle of the eye.
A cloth for covering a table especially one with which a table is covered before the dishes etc. are set on for meals.
A cloth or stuff made of matted fibers of wool or wool and fur fulled or wrought into a compact substance by rolling and pressure with lees or size without spinning or weaving.
A clumsy awkward workman; one who bungles.
A clumsy or awkward performance; a botch; a gross blunder.
A clumsy vessel that works its way from one anchorage to another by means of the tides.
A coach that runs regularly from one stage station or place to another for the conveyance of passengers.
A coal broker.
A coarse cotton drilling used for overalls etc.
A coarse fabric made of jute or hemp used for bagging; also a finer variety of similar material used for curtains etc.
A coarse file on which the cutting prominences are distinct points raised by the oblique stroke of a sharp punch instead of lines raised by a chisel as on the true file.
A coarse leaden shot larger than swan shot used in hunting deer and large game.
A coarsely granular substance obtained by heating and thus partly changing the moistened starch obtained from the roots of the cassava. It is much used in puddings and as a thickening for soups.
A coat or covering; a layer of any substance as a cover or protection.
A coat worn over the other clothing; a greatcoat; a topcoat.
A coat worn under another; a light coat as distinguished from an overcoat or a greatcoat.
A coating or covering resembling ice as of sugar and milk or white of egg; frosting.
A cockroach.
A collar or neck chain usually twisted especially as worn by ancient barbaric nations as the Gauls Germans and Britons.
A collateral relative.
A collection made by gleaning.
A collection of breeding horses and mares or the place where they are kept; also a number of horses kept for a racing riding etc.
A collection of cattle driven or cattle collected for driving; a number of animals as oxen sheep or swine driven in a body.

A collection of glosses or explanations of words and passages of a work or author; a partial dictionary of a work an author a dialect art or science explaining archaic technical or other uncommon words.
A collection of logs boards pieces of timber or the like fastened together either for their own collective conveyance on the water or to serve as a support in conveying other things; a float.
A collection of pus or purulent matter in any tissue or organ of the body the result of a morbid process.
A collection of shrubs.
A collection of small flexible or soft things in a knot or bunch; a waving or bending and spreading cluster.
A collection or combination of three of a kind; three united.
A colloquial abbreviation of Sister.
A color of a delicate purple violet or lilac.
A colorless volatile liquid H2CO resembling acetic or ethyl aldehyde and chemically intermediate between methyl alcohol and formic acid.

A colorless gaseous substance (O/) obtained (as by the silent discharge of electricity in oxygen) as an allotropic form of oxygen containing three atoms in the molecule. It is a streng oxidizer and probably exists in the air though by he ordinary tests it is liable to be confused with certain other substances as hydrogen dioxide or certain oxides of nitrogen. It derives its name from its peculiar odor which resembles that of weak chlorine.

A colorless nonmetallic element tasteless and odorless comprising four fifths of the atmosphere by volume. It is chemically very inert in the free state and as such is incapable of supporting life (hence the name azote still used by French chemists); but it forms many important compounds as ammonia nitric acid the cyanides etc and is a constituent of all organized living tissues animal or vegetable. Symbol N. Atomic weight 14. It was formerly regarded as a permanent noncondensible gas but was liquefied in 1877 by Cailletet of Paris and Pictet of Geneva.
A colorless stone of high luster made of paste. It is much used as an inexpensive ornament.

A colorless volatile liquid CHCl3 having an ethereal odor and a sweetish taste formed by treating alcohol with chlorine and an alkali. It is a powerful solvent of wax resin etc. and is extensively used to produce anaesthesia in surgical operations; also externally to alleviate pain.
A combat between two persons fought with deadly weapons by agreement. It usually arises from an injury done or an affront given by one to the other.
A combination of kindred to avenge injuries or affronts done or offered to any of their blood on the offender and all his race.
A coming together; a meeting.
A commander; the commanding officer of a place or of a body of men.

A commingling; intimate connection or dealings between persons or nations as in common affairs and civilities in correspondence or trade; communication; commerce; especially interchange of thought and feeling.
A common appellation for a North American Indian; -- so called from the color of the skin.
A common baptismal name for a man. The name of one of the apostles

A common metallic element of the alkali group in nature always occuring combined as in common salt in albite etc. It is isolated as a soft waxy white unstable metal so readily oxidized that it combines violently with water and to be preserved must be kept under petroleum or some similar liquid. Sodium is used combined in many salts in the free state as a reducer and as a means of obtaining other metals (as magnesium and aluminium) is an important commercial product. Symbol Na (Natrium). Atomic weight 23. Specific gravity 0.97.
A common name for various kinds of vehicles as a Scythian dwelling on wheels or a chariot.
A common name of many species of the genus Solanum given esp. to the Solanum nigrum or black nightshade a low branching weed with small white flowers and black berries reputed to be poisonous.

A communistic building erected by certain Indian tribes of Arizona and New Mexico. It is often of large size and several stories high and is usually built either of stone or adobe. The term is also applied to any Indian village in the same region.
A compact variety or sulphate of lime or gypsum of fine texture and usually white and translucent but sometimes yellow red or gray. It is carved into vases mantel ornaments etc.
A companion in diversions; a playfellow.

A company of travelers pilgrims or merchants organized and equipped for a long journey or marching or traveling together esp. through deserts and countries infested by robbers or hostile tribes as in Asia or Africa.
A company or collection of living creatures; -- especially applied to sheep and birds rarely to persons or (except in the plural) to cattle and other large animals.
A company or troop especially the company pf performers in a play or an opera.

A comparatively rare element occurring most abundantly in the mineral chromite. Atomic weight 52.5. Symbol Cr. When isolated it is a hard brittle grayish white metal fusible with difficulty. Its chief commercial importance is for its compounds as potassium chromate lead chromate etc. which are brilliantly colored and are used dyeing and calico printing. Called also chrome.

A comparatively rare element related to zinc and occurring in some zinc ores. It is a white metal both ductile and malleable. Symbol Cd. Atomic weight 111.8. It was discovered by Stromeyer in 1817 who named it from its association with zinc or zinc ore.
A comparison; a similitude; specifically a short fictitious narrative of something which might really occur in life or nature by means of which a moral is drawn.
A compendious and rapid method or writing by substituting characters abbreviations or symbols for letters words etc.; short writing; stenography.
A compendium containing the heads of a discourse and the like; an abstract.

A complete assortment of printing type of one size including a due proportion of all the letters in the alphabet large and small points accents and whatever else is necessary for printing with that variety of types; a fount.
A complete charge for a firearm contained in or held together by a case capsule or shell of metal pasteboard or other material.
A complete entity; a whole number in contradistinction to a fraction or a mixed number.
A complete view in every direction.

A composite plant (Artemisia Absinthium) having a bitter and slightly aromatic taste formerly used as a tonic and a vermifuge and to protect woolen garments from moths. It gives the peculiar flavor to the cordial called absinthe. The volatile oil is a narcotic poison. The term is often extended to other species of the same genus.

A composite plant of the genus Lactuca (L. sativa) the leaves of which are used as salad. Plants of this genus yield a milky juice from which lactucarium is obtained. The commonest wild lettuce of the United States is L. Canadensis.
A composition generally poetical holding up vice or folly to reprobation; a keen or severe exposure of what in public or private morals deserves rebuke; an invective poem.

A composition (usually in symphonic form with three movements) in which one instrument (or two or three) stands out in bold relief against the orchestra or accompaniment so as to display its qualities or the performer's skill.
A composition for blacking shoes boots etc.; also one for taking impressions of engraved work.
A composition for two performers whether vocal or instrumental.
A composition of different materials.
A composition of inflammable materials which kindled is very hard to quench; Greek fire.
A composition of sugar and beaten egg used to cover or ornament cake pudding etc.
A compound containing only hydrogen and carbon as methane benzene etc.; also by extension any of their derivatives.
A compound formed by the union of cyanogen with an element or radical.
A compound formed by the union of water with some other substance generally forming a neutral body as certain crystallized salts.
A compound of hydrochloric acid with a base; -- distinguished from a chloride where only chlorine unites with the base.
A compound radical NH4 having the chemical relations of a strongly basic element like the alkali metals.
A concretion or calculus formed in the gall bladder or biliary passages.
A concretion or coagulation; esp. a soft slimy coagulated mass as of blood; a coagulum.
A conductor conduit or artificial channel for conveying water especially one for supplying large cities with water.
A cone of paper which is placed in a vessel of lard or other fat and used as a taper.
A conflict by collisions; a crowding or bumping together; interference.
A confused collection; hence confusion; disorder.
A confused mixture; a mass or collection without order.
A confused noise; uproar; tumult.
A congregation or assembly of Jews met for the purpose of worship or the performance of religious rites.
A coniferous tree of the genus Cupressus. The species are mostly evergreen and have wood remarkable for its durability.
A conjurer; an enchanter; a magician.
A connoisseur in eating and drinking; an epicure.
A consonance or harmony of sounds agreeable to the ear whether the sounds are vocal or instrumental or both.
A consonant sound formed by the aid of the tongue; -- a term especially applied to certain articulations (as those of t d th and n) and to the letters denoting them.
A conspicuous wild flower (Centaurea Cyanus) growing in grainfields.
A constable's prison; a lockup watch-house or station house.
A constitutional disease characterized by the production of tubercles in the internal organs and especially in the lungs where it constitutes the most common variety of pulmonary consumption.
A constrictor of machines and engines; one versed in the principles of machines.
A constructer.

A contagious constitutional febrile disease characterized by a peculiar eruption; variola. The cutaneous eruption is at first a collection of papules which become vesicles (first flat subsequently umbilicated) and then pustules and finally thick crusts which slough after a certain time often leaving a pit or scar.

A contagious affection of the skin due to the presence of a vegetable parasite and forming ring-shaped discolored patches covered with vesicles or powdery scales. It occurs either on the body the face or the scalp. Different varieties are distinguished as Tinea circinata Tinea tonsurans etc. but all are caused by the same parasite (a species of Trichophyton).

A contagious continued fever lasting from two to three weeks attended with great prostration and cerebral disorder and marked by a copious eruption of red spots upon the body. Also called jail fever famine fever putrid fever spottled fever etc.
A continuous humming noise as of bees; a confused murmur as of general conversation in low tones or of a general expression of surprise or approbation.
A continuous composition not divided into what are called movements or governed by the ordinary rules of musical design but in which the author's fancy roves unrestricted by set form.
A contraction for Violoncello.
A contraction of the muscles of the jaw by which its motion is suspended; a variety of tetanus.
A contrite person.
A contrivance often consisting of a noose of cord or the like by which a bird or other animal may be entangled and caught; a trap; a gin.
A contrivance turning on a vertical axis by a handle or winch and giving a circular motion to the ore to be washed; a stirrer.

A contrivance attached to some elevated object for the purpose of showing which way the wind blows; a weathercock. It is usually a plate or strip of metal or slip of wood often cut into some fanciful form and placed upon a perpendicular axis around which it moves freely.

A contrivance for carrying objects from place to place; esp. one for conveying grain coal etc. -- as a spiral or screw turning in a pipe or trough an endless belt with buckets or a truck running along a rope.

A contrivance for effecting ventilation; especially a contrivance or machine for drawing off or expelling foul or stagnant air from any place or apartment or for introducing that which is fresh and pure.
A contrivance somewhat in the form of an umbrella by means of which a descent may be made from a balloon or any eminence.
A contrivance somewhat resembling a bird and often baited with raw meat; -- used by falconers in recalling hawks.
A convent or monastery which is also a place of refuge or entertainment for travelers on some difficult road or pass as in the Alps.
A convex body or surface.
A cooperator.
A copier; a transcriber; an imitator; a plagiarist.
A copy of a work of art as of a picture or statue made by the maker of the original.
A copy of a writing made by the manifold process.
A copy of anything made either so as to be deceptive or so as to give every part and detail of the original; an exact copy or likeness.
A cormorant.
A corner; angle; niche.
A costume for women consisting of a short dress with loose trousers gathered round ankles and (commonly) a broad-brimmed hat.
A country in Eastern Asia.
A country seat; a country or suburban residence of some pretensions to elegance.
A coursing back or coursing again along the line of a previous coursing; renewed course; return; retreat; recurence.
A court or inclosure attached to a house.

A covenant real whereby the grantor of an estate of freehold and his heirs were bound to warrant and defend the title and in case of eviction by title paramount to yield other lands of equal value in recompense. This warranty has long singe become obsolete and its place supplied by personal covenants for title. Among these is the covenant of warranty which runs with the land and is in the nature of a real covenant.
A cover; a shelter; a protection.

A covered and inclosed entrance to a building whether taken from the interior and forming a sort of vestibule within the main wall or projecting without and with a separate roof. Sometimes the porch is large enough to serve as a covered walk.
A covered building used chiefly for storing grain hay and other productions of a farm. In the United States a part of the barn is often used for stables.
A covered pot in which coffee is prepared or is brought upon the table for drinking.
A covering fixed over a bed dais or the like or carried on poles over an exalted personage or a sacred object etc. chiefly as a mark of honor.
A covering for the hand worn to defend it from cold or injury. It differs from a glove in not having a separate sheath for each finger.

A covering for the head consisting of hair interwoven or united by a kind of network either in imitation of the natural growth or in abundant and flowing curls worn to supply a deficiency of natural hair or for ornament or according to traditional usage as a part of an official or professional dress the latter especially in England by judges and barristers.
A covering in front for ornament or other purpose; an exterior covering or sheathing.
A covering of feathers.
A covering or ornament for the head; a headtire.
A covering or protecting for the breast.
A covering overhead; especially a tent.
A cow or calf; -- familiarly so called.
A cowhide or coarse riding whip made of untanned (or raw) hide twisted.
A crab apple; -- so named from its harsh taste.
A crayon made of a paste composed of a color ground with gum water.

A creeping plant and its fruit of several species of the genus Cucumis esp. Cucumis sativus the unripe fruit of which is eaten either fresh or picked. Also similar plants or fruits of several other genera.

A crimson or pink color; also a style of dress cut low and square in the neck; also a mode of dressing the hair by drawing it straight back from the forehead over a roll; -- so called after the Marchioness de Pompadour of France. Also much used adjectively.
A crooked back; a humped back.
A crowd; a number of persons or things crowded together in a confused manner; tumult; confusion.
A crowd; a throng; a multitude or great number of persons.
A crown or garland bestowed among the Romans as a reward for distinguished services.
A crude potash obtained from beet-root residues and other similar sources.

A cryptogamous plant of a cellular structure with distinct stem and simple leaves. The fruit is a small capsule usually opening by an apical lid and so discharging the spores. There are many species collectively termed Musci growing on the earth on rocks and trunks of trees etc. and a few in running water.

A crystalline granular rock consisting of quartz feldspar and mica and usually of a whitish grayish or flesh-red color. It differs from gneiss in not having the mica in planes and therefore in being destitute of a schistose structure.
A crystalline substance.
A cuckoo.
A cultivator of or dealer in flowers.
A cup or bowl; especially the cup used in the sacrament of the Lord's Supper.
A cup or glass filled to the brim or till the liquor runs over particularly in drinking a health or toast.
A cuplike spoon often of large size with a long handle used in lading or dipping.
A current below the surface of water sometimes flowing in a contrary direction to that on the surface.
A current of water; a stream.
A curve of the third degree.

A cutaneous disease which first appears as blebs or as reddish shining slightly prominent spots with spreading edges. These are often followed by an eruption of dark or yellowish prominent nodules frequently producing great deformity. In one variety of the disease anaesthesia of the skin is a prominent symptom. In addition there may be wasting of the muscles falling out of the hair and nails and distortion of the hands and feet with destruction of the bones and joints. It is incurable and is probably contagious.
A cutting instrument resembling shears but smaller consisting of two cutting blades with handles movable on a pin in the center by which they are held together. Often called a pair of scissors.
A cutting instrument.
A cutting; a scion.
A cycler.
A cyprinoid fish of the Mississippi valley (Pimephales promelas); -- called also black-headed minnow.
A dance of Polish origin but now common everywhere. It is performed by two persons in common time.
A dance performed by two persons in circular figures with a whirling motion; also a piece of music composed in triple measure for this kind of dance.
A daring villain; a bandit; one who sets law at defiance; a professional assassin or murderer.
A dark obscure or inexplicable saying; a riddle; a statement the hidden meaning of which is to be discovered or guessed.
A dark variety of sandstone much used for building purposes.
A daughter of one's stepfather or stepmother by a former marriage.
A dawdler.
A day of sentence or condemnation; day of death.
A dead body whether of man or beast; a corpse; now commonly the dead body of a beast.
A dead body embalmed and dried after the manner of the ancient Egyptians; also a body preserved by any means in a dry state from the process of putrefaction.
A dead human body; a corpse.
A dead person; one deceased.
A dealer in staple goods.
A debt; an entry on the debtor (Dr.) side of an account; -- mostly used adjectively.
A deception for mockery or mischief; a deceptive trick or story; a practical joke.
A declamatory strain or flight of censure or abuse; a rambling invective; an oration or harangue abounding in censorious and bitter language.
A declaration of something to come; a foretelling; a prediction; esp. an inspired foretelling.
A deed; an action; a gest.
A deep guttural sound as of a hog.
A deep and long cut; an incision of considerable length and depth particularly in flesh.
A deep bright red tinged with orange or yellow -- of many tints and shades; a vivid or bright red color.
A deep crevice or fissure as in embankment; one of the clefts or fissure by which the mass of a glacier is divided.
A deep opening made by disruption as a breach in the earth or a rock; a yawning abyss; a cleft; a fissure.
A deep red color tinged with blue; also red color in general.
A deep trench around the rampart of a castle or other fortified place sometimes filled with water; a ditch.
A defeat by artifice shifts and turns; discomfiture.
A defect of the eye or of a lens in consequence of which the rays derived from one point are not brought to a single focal point thus causing imperfect images or indistinctness of vision.
A definite summary of what is believed; esp. a summary of the articles of Christian faith; a confession of faith for public use; esp. one which is brief and comprehensive.
A degree usually a slight degree of some color taste or something foreign infused into another substance or mixture or added to it; tincture; color; dye; hue; shade; taste.
A dense growth of brushwood grasses reeds vines etc.; an almost impenetrable thicket of trees canes and reedy vegetation as in India Africa Australia and Brazil.
A deodorizer.
A deposit more or less resembling an inverted stalactite formed by calcareous water dropping on the floors of caverns; hence a similar deposit of other material.
A deposition esp. an excessive deposition of coloring matter.
A deputy; a delegate; a substitute.
A derisive cry or shout.
A description of the ocean.
A design carried out by means of the above process; a pattern on metal glass etc. produced by etching.

A device consisting of a pipe or tube bent so as to form two branches or legs of unequal length by which a liquid can be transferred to a lower level as from one vessel to another over an intermediate elevation by the action of the pressure of the atmosphere in forcing the liquid up the shorter branch of the pipe immersed in it while the continued excess of weight of the liquid in the longer branch (when once filled) causes a continuous flow. The flow takes place only when the discharging extremity of the pipe ia lower than the higher liquid surface and when no part of the pipe is higher above the surface than the same liquid will rise by atmospheric pressure; that is about 33 feet for water and 30 inches for mercury near the sea level.

A device usually of metal consisting of a frame with one more movable tongues or catches used for fastening things together as parts of dress or harness by means of a strap passing through the frame and pierced by the tongue.
A device to magnify sound or direct it in a given direction in a greater volume as a very large funnel used as an ear trumpet or as a speaking trumpet.
A devotee.
A diamond-shaped figure usually with the upper and lower angles slightly acute borne upon a shield or escutcheon. Cf. Fusil.
A die; a half-round set hammer used for forming grooves and spreading iron; -- called also a creaser.
A dignitary or presiding officer in certain ecclesiastical and lay bodies; esp. an ecclesiastical dignitary subordinate to a bishop.
A diminutive of Ann or Anne the proper name.
A direct and pointed reproof; a reprimand; also chastisement; punishment.
A direction in written or printed music to return to the proper pitch after having played an octave higher.

A discharge of atmospheric electricity accompanied by a vivid flash of light commonly from one cloud to another sometimes from a cloud to the earth. The sound produced by the electricity in passing rapidly through the atmosphere constitutes thunder.
A discharge pipe with a valve and spout at which water may be drawn from the mains of waterworks; a water plug.

A disciple of the philosopher Zeno; one of a Greek sect which held that men should be free from passion unmoved by joy or grief and should submit without complaint to unavoidable necessity by which all things are governed.
A discoloration by foreign matter; a spot.
A discourse on flowers.
A discourse or address; a talk; a writing.

A disease characterized by difficulty of breathing (due to a spasmodic contraction of the bronchi) recurring at intervals accompanied with a wheezing sound a sense of constriction in the chest a cough and expectoration.
A disease attended with inflammation and ulceration of the colon and rectum and characterized by griping pains constant desire to evacuate the bowels and the discharge of mucus and blood.
A disease in horses and swine in which the upper part of the throat or groups of lymphatic glands elsewhere swells.
A disease in sheep in which they pine away.
A disease in sheep and cattle marked by great nervousness or by dullness and stupor.
A disease of the glands under the ear in horses; the vives.
A disease seated in the nerves.

A disease which is attended with a persistent excessive discharge of urine. Most frequently the urine is not only increased in quantity but contains saccharine matter in which case the disease is generally fatal.
A diseased condition of the system brought about by the continued use of alcoholic liquors.
A dish made by boiling any article of food to a pulp and rubbing it through a sieve.
A dish made of fresh fish or clams biscuit onions etc. stewed together.
A disposition or arrangement of troops for attacking an enemy unexpectedly from a concealed station. Hence: Unseen peril; a device to entrap; a snare.
A distortion of the countenance whether habitual from affectation or momentary aad occasional to express some feeling as contempt disapprobation complacency etc.; a smirk; a made-up face.
A district on the west coast of Africa (formerly noted for its export of gold and slaves) after which the Guinea fowl Guinea grass Guinea peach etc. are named.
A ditch; a channel for water made by digging.

A divice of gauze or wire covering the mouth or nose to prevent the inhalation of noxious substances as dust or smoke. Being warmed by the breath it tempers cold air passing through it and may also be used for the inhalation of medicated vapors.
A dividing membrane or thin partition commonly with an opening through it.
A divisible substance.
A document as a letter deed or will wholly in the handwriting of the person from whom it proceeds and whose act it purports to be.
A dog kept to watch and guard premises or property and to give notice of the approach of intruders.
A dominating power.
A door or gate; hence a way of entrance or exit especially one that is grand and imposing.
A door; especially one of a pair of folding doors or one of the leaves of such a door.
A door-keeper; a porter; one who has the care of a public building or a building occupied for offices suites of rooms etc.
A draining; a gradual flowing off of any liquid; also that which flows out of a drain.
A drake; the male of Anas boschas.
A draught; a dose; usually a draught or dose of a liquid medicine.
A dress or exterior put on for purposes of concealment or of deception.
A dried berry of the black pepper (Piper nigrum).
A drink composed of spirit (usually gin) and water sweetened.
A drinking together; a merry feast.
A drizzling shower; a falling or leaking in drops.
A drone; a slow lazy fellow; a sluggard.
A drooping.
A drop of dew.
A drop of rain.
A drop; a clot or coagulation.

A drug which in medicinal doses generally allays morbid susceptibility relieves pain and produces sleep; but which in poisonous doses produces stupor coma or convulsions and when given in sufficient quantity causes death. The best examples are opium (with morphine)
a dry fruit or pod which is made up of several parts or carpels and opens to discharge the seeds as the capsule of the poppy the flax the lily etc.
A dry measure containing four pecks eight gallons or thirty-two quarts.

A due proportion of the several parts of a body to each other; adaptation of the form or dimensions of the several parts of a thing to each other; the union and conformity of the members of a work to the whole.
A dull heavy person.
A dull lusterless surface in certain of the arts as gilding metal work glassmaking etc.
A dull spiritless person.
A dull sound without resonance like that produced by striking with or striking against some comparatively soft substance; also the stroke or blow producing such sound.
A dunce; a stupid fellow.

A dwarf umbelliferous plant somewhat resembling fennel (Cuminum Cyminum) cultivated for its seeds which have a bitterish warm taste with an aromatic flavor and are used like those of anise and caraway.
A dwelling for a number of paupers maintained at public expense; an almshouse; a workhouse.
A dwelling house on a farm; a farmer's residence.
A dwelling place -- whether a part or whole of a house or other shelter.

A dyestuff extracted from certain lichens (Roccella tinctoria Lecanora tartarea etc.) as a blue amorphous mass which consists of a compound of the alkaline carbonates with certain coloring matters related to orcin and orcein.
A dynamo-electric machine.
A fabled marine creature typically represented as having the upper part like that of a woman and the lower like a fish; a sea nymph sea woman or woman fish.

A fabric usually of worsted worked upon a warp of linen or other thread by hand the designs being usually more or less pictorial and the stuff employed for wall hangings and the like. The term is also applied to different kinds of embroidery.
A fabric made of silk or wool or of silk and wool and having a transversely corded or ribbed surface.
A fabulous animal generally represented as a monstrous winged serpent or lizard with a crested head and enormous claws and regarded as very powerful and ferocious.
A fabulous animal with one horn; the monoceros; -- often represented in heraldry as a supporter.
A fabulous being represented as half man and half horse.
A failing short; a becoming deficient; failure; deficiency; imperfection; weakness; lapse; fault; infirmity.
A failure or abortive effort.
A failure or backing out
A faint cloudlike self-luminous mass of matter situated beyond the solar system among the stars. True nebulae are gaseous; but very distant star clusters often appear like them in the telescope.
A faint tremulous light; a gleaming; a glimmer.
A faint unsteady light; feeble scattered rays of light; also a gleam.
A fainting fit; syncope.
A fall or perpendicular descent of the water of a river or stream or a descent nearly perpendicular; a cascade; a cataract.
A fall of water over a precipice as in a river or brook; a waterfall less than a cataract.
A fall or descent of rain; the water or amount of water that falls in rain.
A fall that breaks the neck.
A falling in drops or the sound so made.
A falling or letting fall in drops; a dripping; that which drips or falls in drops.
A false or artificial voice; that voice in a man which lies above his natural voice; the male counter tenor or alto voice.
A false or erroneous trial; a trial which has no result.

A false tale or report maliciously uttered tending to injure the reputation of another; the malicious utterance of defamatory reports; the dissemination of malicious tales or suggestions to the injury of another.
A falsehood; a lie; -- used euphemistically.
A fast of forty days beginning with Ash Wednesday and continuing till Easter observed by some Christian churches as commemorative of the fast of our Savior.
A fastening consisting of an iron ring around the wrist usually connected by a chain with one on the other wrist; a manacle; -- usually in the plural.
A fastening together of the pars or ends of one or more threads cords ropes etc. by any one of various ways of tying or entangling.
A fastness; a fort or fortress; fortfield place; a place of security.
A fatal epidemic disease; a pestilence; specif. the plague.

A fatty solid substance produced by bees and employed by them in the construction of their comb; -- usually called beeswax. It is first excreted from a row of pouches along their sides in the form of scales which being masticated and mixed with saliva become whitened and tenacious. Its natural color is pale or dull yellow.
A fault wrong or mistake.

A feast of the Jews instituted to commemorate the sparing of the Hebrews in Egypt when God smiting the firstborn of the Egyptians passed over the houses of the Israelites which were marked with the blood of a lamb.
A feast with loose and noisy jollity; riotous festivity or merrymaking; a carousal.
A feast; a sumptuous entertainment of eating and drinking; often a complimentary or ceremonious feast followed by speeches.
A feather; esp. a soft downy feather or a long conspicuous or handsome feather.
A fee offered to professional men for their services.
A feeling of contempt and aversion; the regarding anything as unworthy of or beneath one; scorn.
A Feigned story or tale intended to instruct or amuse; a fictitious narration intended to enforce some useful truth or precept; an apologue.
A felling by a knock as of a combatant or of an animal.
A female deer or antelope; specifically the female of the fallow deer of which the male is called a buck. Also applied to the female of other animals as the rabbit.
A female fox.
A female friend who attends on a bride at her wedding.
A female god; a divinity or deity of the female sex.
A female governor; a woman invested with authority to control and direct; especially one intrusted with the care and instruction of children -- usually in their homes.
A female heir.
A female host; a woman who hospitably entertains guests at her house.
A female lion.
A female of noble rank; a peeress.
A female sculptor.
A female servant employed to do housework esp. to take care of the rooms.
A female servant.
A female sorcerer.
A female steward; specifically a woman employed in passenger vessels to attend to the wants of female passengers.
A female waiter or attendant; a waiting maid or waiting woman.
A female; a woman; -- in the language of Indian tribes of the Algonquin family correlative of sannup.
A fencer's foil.
A fermented drink made of water and honey with malt yeast etc.; metheglin; hydromel.
A fern of the genus Pteris esp. the P. aquilina common in almost all countries. It has solitary stems dividing into three principal branches. Less properly: Any fern.
A fertile or green spot in a waste or desert esp. in a sandy desert.

A festival celebrated with merriment and revelry in Roman Gatholic countries during the week before Lent esp. at Rome and Naples during a few days (three to ten) before Lent ending with Shrove Tuesday.
A festival; a holiday; a solemn or more commonly a joyous anniversary.
A fibrous material obtained by deviling or tearing into fibers refuse woolen goods old stockings rags druggets etc.
A fictitious name assumed for the time as by an author; a pen name.
A field where corn is or has been growing; -- in England a field of wheat rye barley or oats; in America a field of Indian corn.
A fiend.
A figurative or symbolical reference.

A figurative sentence or discourse in which the principal subject is described by another subject resembling it in its properties and circumstances. The real subject is thus kept out of view and we are left to collect the intentions of the writer or speaker by the resemblance of the secondary to the primary subject.
A figure bounded by three lines and containing three angles.
A figure in which a harts or indelicate word or expression is softened; a way of describing an offensive thing by an inoffensive expression; a mild name for something disagreeable.
A figure of speech by which the orator or writer suddenly breaks off from the previous method of his discourse and addresses in the second person some person or thing absent or present.

A figure of speech in which the expression is an evident exaggeration of the meaning intended to be conveyed or by which things are represented as much greater or less better or worse than they really are; a statement exaggerated fancifully through excitement or for effect.
A fillet or narrow woven fabric commonly of silk used for trimming some part of a woman's attire for badges and other decorative purposes.
A fillet or strip of woven material used in dressing and binding up wounds etc.
A fillet; a band for the head.

A final proposition concession or condition; especially the final propositions conditions or terms offered by either of the parties in a diplomatic negotiation; the most favorable terms a negotiator can offer the rejection of which usually puts an end to the hesitation.
A fine eruption or efflorescence on the body with little or no elevation.
A fine kind of leather prepared commonly from goatskin (though an inferior kind is made of sheepskin) and tanned with sumac and dyed of various colors; -- said to have been first made by the Moors.
A fine powder as of sandarac or cuttlefish bone -- formerly used to prevent ink from spreading on manuscript.
A fireplace or hearth.
A firm elastic substance resembling horn taken from the upper jaw of the right whale; baleen. It is used as a stiffening in stays fans screens and for various other purposes.
A first principle or element.
A fish of the group Abdominales.
A fishing boat.
A fixed daily allowance of provisions assigned to a soldier in the army or a sailor in the navy for his subsistence.
A fixed pin or short axis on the end of which a wheel or other body turns.
A fixed point or station; a basis or fundamental principle; a position from which objects or principles are viewed and according to which they are compared and judged.

A fixture for drawing a liquid as water molasses oil etc. from a pipe cask or other vessel in such quantities as may be desired; -- called also tap and cock. It consists of a tubular spout stopped with a movable plug spigot
A fklat cake turned on the griddle while cooking; a griddlecake or pacake.
A flake or small filmy mass of snow.
A flake; also a lock as of wool.
A flat circular stone revolving on an axle for grinding or sharpening tools or shaping or smoothing objects.
A flat stone used in paving or any rock which will split into such stones.
A flat surface; especially a broad level elevated area of land; a table-land.
A flatfish of the family Pleuronectidae of many species.
A flea.
A fleet of armed ships; a squadron. Specifically the Spanish fleet which was sent to assail England a. d. 1558.
A fleet of ships; an assemblage of merchantmen or so many as sail in company.

A fleshy three-celled many-seeded fruit as the melon pumpkin cucumber etc. of the order Cucurbitaceae; and especially the bottle gourd (Lagenaria vulgaris) which occurs in a great variety of forms and when the interior part is removed serves for bottles dippers
A flight of missiles as arrows bullets or the like; the simultaneous discharge of a number of small arms.
A flight of stairs or steps; a staircase.
A flight of stairs with their supporting framework casing balusters etc.
A flitch.
A float; esp. a floating object moored to the bottom to mark a channel or to point out the position of something beneath the water as an anchor shoal rock etc.
A floor timber in a ship.
A flourish of trumpets as in coming into the lists etc.; also a short and lively air performed on hunting horns during the chase.
A flowing out; efflux.
A flowing to or towards; a concourse; an influx.
A fluted or ribbed board on which clothes are rubbed in washing them.
A fold of muscous membrane often found at the orifice of the vagina; the vaginal membrane.
A fold or plait; a wrinkle.
A fold; a plait; a turn or twist as of a cord.
A fold; a wrinkle; a collection of folds.
A follower of Plato; a Platonist.
A follower of the yoga philosophy; an ascetic.
A food made by boiling some leguminous or farinaceous substance or the meal of it in water or in milk making of broth or thin pudding.
A fool; a silly or stupid person.

A foot consisting of four syllables: either two long and two short -- that is a spondee and a pyrrhic in which case it is called the greater Ionic; or two short and two long -- that is a pyrrhic and a spondee in which case it is called the smaller Ionic.
A foot journey or excursion.
A forced or affected smile; a simper.
A foreigner.
A fork or farming utensil used in pitching hay sheaves of grain or the like.
A forked support; a crotch.
A forked tool used by clothiers in dressing cloth.

A form of headdress worn by the ancient Persians. According to Xenophon the royal tiara was encircled with a diadem and was high and erect while those of the people were flexible or had rims turned over.
A form of instruction by means of questions and answers.

A form of silica or silicon dioxide (SiO2) occurring in hexagonal crystals which are commonly colorless and transparent but sometimes also yellow brown purple green and of other colors; also in cryptocrystalline massive forms varying in color and degree of transparency being sometimes opaque.

A form of sleep or somnambulism brought on by artificial means in which there is an unusual suspension of some powers and an unusual activity of others. It is induced by an action upon the nerves through the medium of the senses as in persons of very feeble organization by gazing steadly at a very bright object held before the eyes or by pressure upon certain points of the surface of the body.
A formal or elaborate argumentative discourse oral or written; a disquisition; an essay; a discussion.
A formal question or inquiry; esp. (Law) a question asked in writing.

A fortification made in haste of trees earth palisades wagons or anything that will obstruct the progress or attack of an enemy. It is usually an obstruction formed in streets to block an enemy's access.
A fortified place; a large and permanent fortification sometimes including a town; a fort; a castle; a stronghold; a place of defense or security.
A fortress in or near a fortified city commanding the city and fortifications and intended as a final point of defense.
A foul back street of a city especially one filled with a poor dirty degraded and often vicious population; any low neighborhood or dark retreat; -- usually in the plural.
A four-sided figure having only right angles; a right-angled parallelogram.
A fragment of any solid substance; a thick piece.
A fragment or particle rubbed off by the act of filing.
A fragment; a scrap.

A fragrant edible berry of a delicious taste and commonly of a red color the fruit of a plant of the genus Fragaria of which there are many varieties. Also the plant bearing the fruit. The common American strawberry is Fragaria virginiana; the European F. vesca. There are also other less common species.
A frame (commonly) of wood serving to hold a canvas upright or nearly upright for the painter's convenience or for exhibition.
A frame consisting of two bars crossing each other at right angles and turning on a post or pin to hinder the passage of beasts but admitting a person to pass between the arms; a turnstile.
A frame from which is suspended the rope with which criminals are executed by hanging usually consisting of two upright posts and a crossbeam on the top; also a like frame for suspending anything.
A frame or grating of various kinds.
A framework trough or tube upon or through which objects are made to slide from a higher to a lower level or through which water passes to a wheel.
A frantic revel; drunken revelry.
A freight; a cargo.
A French gold coin of twenty francs or about $3.86.
A French title of courtesy given to a girl or an unmarried lady equivalent to the English Miss.
A frequent recurrence of the same tone or sound producing a dull uniformity; absence of variety as in speaking or singing.
A fresh-water herbivorous fish (Cyprinus carpio.). Several other species of Cyprinus Catla and Carassius are called carp.
A frightful goblin; an imp; a bugaboo; also a name formerly given to the household spirit Robin Goodfellow.
A fringe or border.
A frolic; a jolly time.
A frolicsome leap or spring; a skip; a jump as in mirth or dancing; a prank.

A fruit allied to the plum of an orange color oval shape and delicious taste; also the tree (Prunus Armeniaca of Linnaeus) which bears this fruit. By cultivation it has been introduced throughout the temperate zone.
A fuller of cloth.
A functional nervous affection or disease that is a disease of the nerves without any appreciable change of nerve structure.
A fungus (Ustilago foetida) which affects the ear of cereals filling the grains with a fetid dust; -- also called pepperbrand.
A furrow channel or long hollow such as may be formed by cutting molding grinding the wearing force of flowing water or constant travel; a depressed way; a worn path; a rut.
A furrow.
A future existence or state.
A gable.
A gale of piercingly cold wind usually accompanied with fine and blinding snow; a furious blast.
A gambling game with dice.

A game called also daughts played on a checkerboard by two persons each having twelve men (counters or checkers) which are moved diagonally. The game is ended when either of the players has lost all his men or can not move them.
A game similar to lawn tennis played with shuttlecocks.
A game at cards; whist.

A game of ball originating among the North American Indians now the popular field sport of Canada and played also in England and the United States. Each player carries a long-handled racket called a crosse. The ball is not handled but caught with the crosse and carried on it or tossed from it the object being to carry it or throw it through one of the goals placed at opposite ends of the field.
A game of ball of Eastern origin resembling hockey with the players on horseback.
A game of cards played by two or four persons in which there is a crib. It is characterized by a great variety of chances.
A game of cards; -- called also taroc.

A game of chance in which a small ball is made to move round rapidly on a circle divided off into numbered red and black spaces the one on which it stops indicating the result of a variety of wagers permitted by the game.

A game of chance played with cards on which are inscribed numbers and any contrivance (as a wheel containing numbered balls) for determining a set of numbers by chance. The player holding a card having on it the set of numbers drawn from the wheel takes the stakes after a certain percentage of them has been deducted for the dealer. A variety of lotto is called keno.

A game of chance and skill played by two persons on a board marked off into twenty-four spaces called points. Each player has fifteen pieces or men the movements of which from point to point are determined by throwing dice. Formerly called tables.
A game played on a chessboard by two persons with two differently colored sets of men sixteen in each set. Each player has a king a queen two bishops two knights two castles or rooks and eight pawns.

A game played with ivory balls o a cloth-covered rectangular table bounded by elastic cushions. The player seeks to impel his ball with his cue so that it shall either strike (carom upon) two other balls or drive another ball into one of the pockets with which the table sometimes is furnished.
A gap or hole in a hedge hence wall or the like through which a wild animal is accustomed to pass; a muset.
A garden.
A garment worn by men covering the hips and thighs; smallclothes.

A gaseous compound of carbon and hydrogen in the proportion of two atoms of the former to two of the latter. It is a colorless gas with a peculiar unpleasant odor and is produced for use as an illuminating gas in a number of ways but chiefly by the action of water on calcium carbide. Its light is very brilliant.
A gaseous compound of hydrogen and nitrogen NH3 with a pungent smell and taste: -- often called volatile alkali and spirits of hartshorn.
A gaseous element found in the atmospheres of the sun and earth and in some rare minerals.
A gate where toll is taken.
A gathering of people for social purposes; an informal party or reception.
A gay or sportive action; a ludicrous merry or mischievous trick; a caper; a frolic.
A gear; a tackle.
A general disease characterized by painful often multiple local inflammations usually affecting the joints and muscles but also extending sometimes to the deeper organs as the heart.
A general name for the numerous species of diurnal Lepidoptera.
A general or comprehensive view.
A general term any round piece of timber used as a mast yard boom or gaff.
A general view or a collection of heads or parts so arranged as to exhibit a general view of the whole; an abstract or summary of a discourse; a syllabus; a conspectus.
A gentle push or jog as with the elbow.

A gentlewoman; -- an appellation or courteous form of address given to a lady especially an elderly or a married lady; -- much used in the address at the beginning of a letter to a woman. The corresponding word in addressing a man is Sir.
A genuine quality.

A genus (Abies) of coniferous trees often of large size and elegant shape some of them valued for their timber and others for their resin. The species are distinguished as the balsam fir the silver fir the red fir etc. The Scotch fir is a Pinus.
A genus of a single species belonging to the order Uricaceae; hemp.
A genus of American and Asiatic trees with aromatic bark and large sweet-scented whitish or reddish flowers.
A genus of climbing orchidaceous plants natives of tropical America.
A genus of composite plants mostly perennial and of many species including the many varieties of garden chrysanthemums (annual and perennial) and also the feverfew and the oxeye daisy.
A genus of eight-armed cephalopods
A genus of endogenous bulbous plants with handsome flowers having a cup-shaped crown within the six-lobed perianth and comprising the daffodils and jonquils of several kinds.

A genus of flowering plants having elegant drooping flowers with four sepals four petals eight stamens and a single pistil. They are natives of Mexico and South America. Double-flowered varieties are now common in cultivation.
A genus of large American serpents including the boa constrictor the emperor boa of Mexico (B. imperator) and the chevalier boa of Peru (B. eques).
A genus of leguminous plants containing many species and including the sensitive plants (Mimosa sensitiva and M. pudica).
A genus of low herbs (Bellis) belonging to the family Compositae. The common English and classical daisy is B. prennis which has a yellow disk and white or pinkish rays.

A genus of perennial plants belonging to the natural order Liliaceae and having erect much branched stems and very slender branchlets which are sometimes mistaken for leaves. Asparagus racemosus is a shrubby climbing plant with fragrant flowers. Specifically: The Asparagus officinalis a species cultivated in gardens.
A genus of plants some species of which produce beautiful and fragrant flowers; Cape jasmine; -- so called in honor of Dr. Alexander Garden.
A genus of plants (herbs shrubs or trees) some species of which have large showy flowers. Some species are cultivated in India for their fiber which is used as a substitute for hemp.
A genus of plants (Rumex) some species of which are well-known weeds which have a long taproot and are difficult of extermination.

A genus of plants having a beaklike tours or receptacle around which the seed capsules are arranged and membranous projections or stipules at the joints. Most of the species have showy flowers and a pungent odor. Called sometimes crane's-bill.
A genus of plants of the Ranunculus or Crowfoot family; windflower. Some of the species are cultivated in gardens.
A genus of showy flowering shrubs mostly natives of China or of North America; false honeysuckle. The genus is scarcely distinct from Rhododendron.
A genus of shrubs (Sambucus) having broad umbels of white flowers and small black or red berries.

A genus of solanaceous herbs with funnelform or salver-shaped corollas. Two species are common in cultivation Petunia violacera with reddish purple flowers and P. nyctaginiflora with white flowers. There are also many hybrid forms with variegated corollas.
A genus of trees including the orange lemon citron etc. originally natives of southern Asia.
A gift begged; a present.
A gift; endowment.
A gigantic coniferous tree (Sequoia sempervirens) of California and its light and durable reddish timber.
A girl belonging to or attending a school.
A girl employed to attend children.
A girl or woman who attends the customers of a bar as in a tavern or beershop.
A girl or woman with a somewhat brown or dark complexion.
A girl who indulges in boisterous play.
