A giving suck; the secretion and yielding of milk by the mammary gland.
A glass water bottle for the table or toilet; -- called also croft.
A gliding slipping or gradual falling; an unobserved or imperceptible progress or passing away ; -- restricted usually to immaterial things or to figurative uses.
A goat upon whose head were symbolically placed the sins of the people after which he was suffered to escape into the wilderness.
A goblin; a bugbear.
A goddess of the mountains forests meadows or waters.
A going or moving from place to place without any determinate business or object; an excursion or stroll merely for recreation.
A going out; particularly (the Exodus) the going out or journey of the Israelites from Egypt under the conduct of Moses; and hence any large migration from a place.
A going; a walk; a march; a way.
A gradual increase in the strength and fullness of tone with which a passage is performed.
A grain yielded by a hardy cereal grass (Secale cereale) closely allied to wheat; also the plant itself. Rye constitutes a large portion of the breadstuff used by man.
A granary; a building or place where grain is stored for preservation.
A grandmother; a grandam; familiarly an old woman.
A grandson or grandchild or remoter lineal descendant.
A grape or a bunch of grapes.
A grated iron utensil for broiling flesh and fish over coals.
A gray color; any mixture of white and black; also a neutral or whitish tint.
A grayish coarse double blanket worn by countrywomen in the west of England over the shoulders like a cloak or shawl.
A great collection of ore without any vein coming into it or going out from it.
A great fall of water over a precipice; a large waterfall.
A great gun; a piece of ordnance or artillery; a firearm for discharging heavy shot with great force.
A great number of persons collected together; a numerous collection of persons; a crowd; an assembly.
A griddle.
A gridiron.
A gripe or clinching with or as with the fingers or claws; seizure; grasp.
A grizzly bear.
A group somewhat lessdistinct than speciesusually are but based on characters more important than those which characterize ordinary varieties; often a geographical variety or race.
A growth of minute powdery or webby fungi whitish or of different colors found on various diseased or decaying substances.
A guard to protect or defend the person; a lifeguard.
A gymnast.
A hair of a horse especially one from the mane or tail; the hairs of the mane or tail taken collectively; a fabric or tuft made of such hairs.
A half god or an inferior deity; a fabulous hero the offspring of a deity and a mortal.
A half sphere; one half of a sphere or globe when divided by a plane passing through its center.
A half suppressed broken laugh.
A half.
A halt; the act of limping.
A handicraft; a trade; art of making.
A hanging down of the head; a drooping attitude; a limp appearance; an ungainly clownish gait; a sidewise depression or hanging down as of a hat brim.
A hard heavy and durable wood which admits of a fine polish or gloss. The usual color is black but it also occurs red or green.
A hard tough but easily fusible alloy originally consisting of tin with a little lead but afterwards modified by the addition of copper antimony or bismuth.
A hard and sharp-pointed projection from a woody stem; usually a branch so transformed; a spine.

A hard brittle brownish gelatin obtained by boiling to a jelly the skins hoofs etc. of animals. When gently heated with water it becomes viscid and tenaceous and is used as a cement for uniting substances. The name is also given to other adhesive or viscous substances.
A hard protuberance; a hard swelling or rising; a bunch; a lump.

A harp-shaped instrument of music set horizontally on legs like the grand piano with strings of wire played by the fingers by means of keys provided with quills instead of hammers for striking the strings. It is now superseded by the piano.
A harsh shrill cry as of one in acute pain or in fright; a shriek; a scream.
A harsh nasal noise made in sleep.
A hart or stag three years old.
A head or leading man especially of a village community.
A headdress for men and boys; a cap.

A headdress worn by men in the Levant and by most Mohammedans of the male sex consisting of a cap and a sash scarf or shawl usually of cotton or linen wound about the cap and sometimes hanging down the neck.
A health station or retreat; a sanatorium.
A hearer or listener.
A heavy stupid fellow; a blockhead; a numskull; an ignoramus; a dunce; a dullard.
A heavy fall as of something flat; hence also a crushing reply.
A heavy gaseous hydrocarbon C3H8 of the paraffin series occurring naturally dissolved in crude petroleum and also made artificially; -- called also propyl hydride.
A heavy mallet used to drive wedges beat pavements etc.
A heavy wooden hammer or beetle.
A hedge.
A hedgehog.
A helper; an assistant; a confederate in some action or enterprise.
A herdsman's hut in the mountains of Switzerland.
A high steep bank as by a river or the sea or beside a ravine or plain; a cliff with a broad face.
A high officer in the monarchical establishments of the Middle Ages.
A highly volatile mixture of fluid hydrocarbons obtained from petroleum as also by the distillation of bituminous coal. It is used in making air gas and in giving illuminating power to water gas.
A highway; a much traveled or main road.
A hind in the year of its age.
A hint suggestion token or memorial to awaken memory; that which reminds or recalls to memory; a souvenir.
A hint; an intimation.
A hissing and humming sound.
A hissing sound as of something frying over a fire.
A hissing sound.
A history or description of books and manuscripts with notices of the different editions the times when they were printed etc.
A hive for a swarm of bees. Also used figuratively.
A hobby ; freak; whim.
A hog ox or other large animal roasted or broiled whole for a feast.
A hog.
A holding or a mode of holding an estate; tenure; the temporary possession of what belongs to another.
A holding on or remaining in a particular state; permanence as of condition habits abode etc.; perseverance; constancy; duration; stay.
A holding with the feet; firm standing; that on which one may tread or rest securely; footing.
A holding; restraint; custody; guard; charge; care; preservation.
A hole or crevice through which one may peep without being discovered.
A hole in the ground or hiding place for concealing and preserving provisions which it is inconvenient to carry.
A hole made by boring; a perforation.
A hole or apertupe in a door or lock for receiving a key.
A hole through which a man may descend or creep into a drain sewer steam boiler parts of machinery etc. for cleaning or repairing.
A hollow ball or shell of iron filled with powder of other explosive ignited by means of a fuse and thrown from the hand among enemies.
A hollow cut in anything; a nick; an indentation.
A hollow place in the earth; an abyss; a deep chasm or basin
A hollow vessel or dish to hold water for washing and for various other uses.
A hollow; an arched vault; a cavity; a recess.
A hollow-horned ruminant of the genus Capra of several species and varieties esp. the domestic goat (C. hircus) which is raised for its milk flesh and skin.
A hood; especially an ornamental or an official hood.
A horizontal wheel or frame commonly with wooden horses etc. on which children ride; a merry-go-round.
A horse especially a spirited horse for state of war; -- used chiefly in poetry or stately prose.
A hospital or place where the infirm or sick are lodged and nursed gratuitously or where out-patients are treated.
A hotchpotch.
A house appropriated for the use of a school or schools or for instruction.
A house for hatching fish etc.
A house in which nuns reside; a cloister or convent in which women reside for life under religious vows.
A house kept warm to shelter tender plants and shrubs from the cold air; a place in which the plants of warmer climates may be reared and fruits ripened.
A house occupied by a club.
A house of lewdness or ill fame; a house frequented by prostitutes; a bawdyhouse.
A house of religious retirement or of secusion from ordinary temporal concerns especially for monks; -- more rarely applied to such a house for females.
A house on deck where the cooking is done; -- commonly called the galley.

A house or room artificially warmed or heated; a forcing house or hothouse; a drying room; -- formerly designating an artificially warmed dwelling or room a parlor or a bathroom but now restricted in this sense to heated houses or rooms used for horticultural purposes or in the processes of the arts.
A house or shed built of boards boughs or other slight materials for temporary occupation.
A house where ale is retailed; hence a tippling house.
A house where any manufacture is carried on; a workshop.
A house where beasts are butchered for the market.
A house where insane persons are confined; an insane asylum; a bedlam.
A housewife or housekeeper.
A human being in his native state of rudeness; one who is untaught uncivilized or without cultivation of mind or manners.
A human being that eats human flesh; hence any that devours its own kind.
A human body in general whether living or dead; -- sometimes contemptuously.
A hump; a protuberance.
A hundred times as much or as many.
A hurt; an injury.
A husk; a pod.
A hybrid animal; specifically one generated between an ass and a mare sometimes a horse and a she-ass.
A hymenopterous insect of the Linnaean genus Formica which is now made a family of several genera; an emmet; a pismire.
A hypocrite; esp. a superstitious hypocrite.
A introductory portion; an introduction or preface as to a book document etc.; specifically the introductory part of a statute which states the reasons and intent of the law.
A jag or snag; a knob; a protuberance; also the point or gist as of a story.
A jerk or twitch.
A jet or current of water or vapor directed upon some part of the body to benefit it medicinally; a douche bath.
A joining; a union; an alliance.
A judicial court of chancery which in England and in the United States is distinctively a court with equity jurisdiction.
A juice drawn from various kinds of palms in the East Indies; or a spirituous liquor procured from it by fermentation.
A junction or joining made by splicing.
A keen reproachful expression; a satirical remark uttered with some degree of scorn or contempt; a taunt; a gibe; a cutting jest.
A keen-edged knife of peculiar shape used in shaving the hair from the face or the head.
A keeper of archives or records.
A keeper; a guardian; a watchman.
A kernel; hence a central mass or point about which matter is gathered or to which accretion is made; the central or material portion; -- used both literally and figuratively.
A kick as of a beast from impatience or uneasiness.
A kick; a blow with the foot.
A kind of ale brewed with brackish water obtained from a particular well; -- so called from the first brewer of it one Thomas Tipper.
A kind of ball-shaped fungus (Lycoperdon giganteum and other species of the same genus) full of dustlike spores when ripe; -- called also bullfist bullfice puckfist puff and puffin.
A kind of boat used in the East Indies.
A kind of broad-brimmed hat worn in Spain and in Spanish America.
A kind of candy made of molasses or brown sugar boiled down and poured out in shallow pans.

A kind of cap or cover or sometimes a broad ring for the end of the finger used in sewing to protect the finger when pushing the needle through the material. It is usually made of metal and has upon the outer surface numerous small pits to catch the head of the needle.
A kind of chopping instrument for trimming the edges of roofing slates.
A kind of cigar of large size and superior quality; also the size in which such cigars are classed.

A kind of cloak worn by the Spanish Americans having the form of a blanket with a slit in the middle for the head to pass through. A kind of poncho made of rubber or painted cloth is used by the mounted troops in the United States service.
A kind of close carriage with two or four wheels usually a public vehicle.
A kind of coarse heavy frieze formerly used for garments.
A kind of coarse woolen cloth having a thick nap or frieze.
A kind of cup or drinking vessel having a foot or standard but without a handle.
A kind of dagger with a slender rounded and pointed blade.
A kind of dandy; especially one characterized by an ultrafashionable style of dress and other affectations.
A kind of deep blue one of the seven prismatic colors.
A kind of earthen or metal drinking cup with a handle -- usually cylindrical and without a lip.
A kind of fish. Same as Cod.
A kind of French brandy so called from the town of Cognac.
A kind of fur prepared from lambskin dressed with the wool on; -- used formerly as an edging and ornament esp. of scholastic habits.
A kind of German biscuit or cake in the form of a twisted ring salted on the outside.
A kind of glass produced by volcanoes. It is usually of a black color and opaque except in thin splinters.
A kind of handwriting in which the downward slope of the letters is from left to right.
A kind of headdress formerly worn by ladies raising the hair and fore part of the cap to a great height.
A kind of herpes (Herpes zoster) which spreads half way around the body like a girdle and is usually attended with violent neuralgic pain.
A kind of hood worn by the canons of a cathedral church; a sort of amice.

A kind of intoxicating liquor distilled from cane juice or from the scummings of the boiled juice or from treacle or molasses or from the lees of former distillations. Also sometimes used colloquially as a generic or a collective name for intoxicating liquor.
A kind of knitting done by means of a hooked needle with worsted silk or cotton; crochet work. Commonly used adjectively.
A kind of large thin muffin or cake light and spongy and cooked on a griddle or spider.
A kind of latticework formed of or covered with vines branches of trees or other plants for shade; a bower.
A kind of laugh with short catches of the voice or breath; a light silly laugh.
A kind of light passenger vehicle carrying four persons.
A kind of lottery in which several persons pay in shares the value of something put up as a stake and then determine by chance (as by casting dice) which one of them shall become the sole possessor.
A kind of machine blanket or wrapping material used by calico printers.
A kind of nightgown for men.
A kind of orange much like the mandarin but of deeper color and higher flavor. It is said to have been produced in America from the mandarin.
A kind of play with a ball against a wall resembling tennis; -- so named because three fives or fifteen are counted to the game.
A kind of riddle based upon some fanciful or fantastic resemblance between things quite unlike; a puzzling question of which the answer is or involves a pun.

A kind of ring or bent piece of metal wood leather or the like horizontal in one part for receiving the foot of a rider and attached by a strap to the saddle -- used to assist a person in mounting a horse and to enable him to sit steadily in riding as well as to relieve him by supporting a part of the weight of the body.
A kind of sauce much used in India containing garlic pepper ginger and other strong spices.
A kind of scepter or spear with three prongs -- the common attribute of Neptune.
A kind of short petticoat reaching from the waist to the knees worn in the Highlands of Scotland by men and in the Lowlands by young boys; a filibeg.

A kind of sledge made of pliable board turned up at one or both ends used for coasting down hills or prepared inclined planes; also a sleigh or sledge to be drawn by dogs or by hand over soft and deep snow.

A kind of small hand-pump for throwing a stream of liquid or for purposes of aspiration. It consists of a small cylindrical barrel and piston or a bulb of soft elastic material with or without valves and with a nozzle which is sometimes at the end of a flexible tube; -- used for injecting animal bodies cleansing wounds etc.
A kind of small onion (Allium Ascalonicum) native of Palestine; the eschalot or shallot.
A kind of small pinchers with long jaws -- used for bending or cutting metal rods or wire for handling small objects such as the parts of a watch etc.
A kind of stand or piece of furniture having shelves for books ornaments etc.; an etagere.
A kind of sugar confection which dissolves easily in the mouth.
A kind of swelling in the cheek.

A kind of thick paste or cement compounded of whiting or soft carbonate of lime and linseed oil when applied beaten or kneaded to the consistence of dough -- used in fastening glass in sashes stopping crevices and for similar purposes.
A kind of under waist stiffened with whalebone etc. worn esp. by women; a corset; stays.
A kind of war hatchet used by the American Indians. It was originally made of stone but afterwards of iron.
A kind of waved silk usually called watered silk manufactured like taffeta but thicker and stronger. The watering is given to it by calendering.
A kind of wild red cherry.
A kind of woolen stuff.
A king; a chief; the title of the emperor of Russia.
A knife; a cutting tool.
A knot a knob; a protuberance; a swelling.
A knot of threads or other thing united confusedly or so interwoven as not to be easily disengaged; a snarl.
A knot or coarse part in cloth.
A knot or complication of hair thread or the like difficult to disentangle; entanglement; hence intricate complication; embarrassing difficulty.
A knot; a cluster; a group; a crowd; a flock.
A knot; a protuberance; a song.

A labiate shrub (Rosmarinus officinalis) with narrow grayish leaves growing native in the southern part of France Spain and Italy also in Asia Minor and in China. It has a fragrant smell and a warm pungent bitterish taste. It is used in cookery perfumery etc. and is an emblem of fidelity or constancy.
A land full of wonders or marvels.
A lane.
A lapping with the tongue.

A large amphibious herbivorous mammal (Hippopotamus amphibius) common in the rivers of Africa. It is allied to the hogs and has a very thick naked skin a thick and square head a very large muzzle small eyes and ears thick and heavy body and short legs. It is supposed to be the behemoth of the Bible. Called also zeekoe and river horse. A smaller species (H. Liberiencis) inhabits Western Africa.

A large arboreal anthropoid ape of West Africa. It is larger than a man and is remarkable for its massive skeleton and powerful muscles which give it enormous strength. In some respects its anatomy more than that of any other ape except the chimpanzee resembles that of man.
A large deep hollow place in the earth; a large cave.

A large esculent farinaceous tuber of various climbing plants of the genus Dioscorea; also the plants themselves. Mostly natives of warm climates. The plants have netted-veined petioled leaves and pods with three broad wings. The commonest species is D. sativa but several others are cultivated.
A large heavy hammer usually wielded with both hands; -- called also sledge hammer.

A large savage carnivorous mammal (Felis leopardus). It is of a yellow or fawn color with rings or roselike clusters of black spots along the back and sides. It is found in Southern Asia and Africa. By some the panther (Felis pardus) is regarded as a variety of leopard.

A large strong wasp. The European species (Vespa crabro) is of a dark brown and yellow color. It is very pugnacious and its sting is very severe. Its nest is constructed of a paperlike material and the layers of comb are hung together by columns. The American white-faced hornet (V. maculata) is larger and has similar habits.

A large American carnivore (Felis concolor) found from Canada to Patagonia especially among the mountains. Its color is tawny or brownish yellow without spots or stripes. Called also catamount cougar American lion mountain lion and panther or painter.

A large and powerful feline animal (Felis onca) ranging from Texas and Mexico to Patagonia. It is usually brownish yellow with large dark somewhat angular rings each generally inclosing one or two dark spots. It is chiefly arboreal in its habits. Called also the American tiger.
A large and tall breed of domestic fowl.
A large Australian bird of two species (Dromaius Novae-Hollandiae and D. irroratus) related to the cassowary and the ostrich. The emu runs swiftly but is unable to fly.
A large basket usually with a cover used for the packing and carrying of articles.
A large basket or hamper of wickerwork used for the transportation of china crockery and similar wares.
A large bee of the genus Bombus sometimes called humblebee; -- so named from its sound.

A large bird of the genus Struthio of which Struthio camelus of Africa is the best known species. It has long and very strong legs adapted for rapid running; only two toes; a long neck nearly bare of feathers; and short wings incapable of flight. The adult male is about eight feet high.

A large carnivorous reptile of the Crocodile family peculiar to America. It has a shorter and broader snout than the crocodile and the large teeth of the lower jaw shut into pits in the upper jaw which has no marginal notches. Besides the common species of the southern United States there are allied species in South America.
A large cask or vessel for wine or beer. It contains two hogsheads.

A large cervine mammal (Alces machlis or A. Americanus) native of the Northern United States and Canada. The adult male is about as large as a horse and has very large palmate antlers. It closely resembles the European elk and by many zoologists is considered the same species.
A large dark-colored variety of the leopard by some zoologists considered a distinct species. It is marked with large ringlike spots the centers of which are darker than the color of the body.

A large deer of several species. The European elk (Alces machlis or Cervus alces) is closely allied to the American moose. The American elk or wapiti (Cervus Canadensis) is closely related to the European stag.
A large draught of liquor.
A large drinking cup with a wide mouth supported on a foot or standard.

A large estate where work of any kind is done as agriculture manufacturing mining or raising of animals; a cultivated farm with a good house in distinction from a farming establishment with rude huts for herdsmen etc.; -- a word used in Spanish-American regions.
A large fire built in the open air as an expression of public joy and exultation or for amusement.
A large fresh-water fish (Esox lucius) found in Europe and America highly valued as a food fish; -- called also pickerel gedd luce and jack.

A large heavy knife resembling a broadsword often two or three feet in length -- used by the inhabitants of Spanish America as a hatchet to cut their way through thickets and for various other purposes.
A large knife.
A large ladle; a vessel with a long handle used for dipping liquids; a utensil for bailing boats.
A large lump or piece; a hunch.
A large mass of ice generally floating in the ocean.
A large mass or body of snow and ice sliding swiftly down a mountain side or falling down a precipice.
A large medal or memorial coin.

A large North American herb of the genus Phytolacca (P. decandra) bearing dark purple juicy berries; -- called also garget pigeon berry pocan and pokeweed. The root and berries have emetic and purgative properties and are used in medicine. The young shoots are sometimes eaten as a substitute for asparagus and the berries are said to be used in Europe to color wine.
A large number or mass of small animals or insects especially when in motion.
A large pebble; a rounded stone not too large to be handled; a small boulder; -- used for paving streets and for other purposes.
A large pile of hay grain straw or the like usually of a nearly conical form but sometimes rectangular or oblong contracted at the top to a point or ridge and sometimes covered with thatch.

A large reptile of the genus Crocodilus of several species. They grow to the length of sixteen or eighteen feet and inhabit the large rivers of Africa Asia and America. The eggs laid in the sand are hatched by the sun's heat. The best known species is that of the Nile (C. vulgaris or C. Niloticus). The Florida crocodile (C. Americanus) is much less common than the alligator and has longer jaws. The name is also sometimes applied to the species of other related genera as the gavial and the alligator.
A large revolving platform for turning railroad cars locomotives etc. in a different direction; -- called also turnplate.

A large ruminant used in Asia and Africa for carrying burdens and for riding. The camel is remarkable for its ability to go a long time without drinking. Its hoofs are small and situated at the extremities of the toes and the weight of the animal rests on the callous. The dromedary (Camelus dromedarius) has one bunch on the back while the Bactrian camel (C. Bactrianus) has two. The llama alpaca and vicuï¿½a of South America belong to a related genus (Auchenia).

A large South American snake of the Boa family (Eunectes murinus) which lives near rivers and preys on birds and small mammals. The name is also applied to a similar large serpent (Python tigris) of Ceylon.
A large species of American grass of the genus Zea (Z. Mays) widely cultivated as a forage and food plant; Indian corn. Also its seed growing on cobs and used as food for men animals.
A large stick of wood forming the back of a fire on the hearth.
A large stove or oven; a furnace of brick or stone or a heated chamber for the purpose of hardening burning or drying anything.

A large tree the Artocarpus integrifolia common in the East Indies closely allied to the breadfruit from which it differs in having its leaves entire. The fruit is of great size weighing from thirty to forty pounds and through its soft fibrous matter are scattered the seeds which are roasted and eaten. The wood is of a yellow color fine grain and rather heavy and is much used in cabinetwork. It is also used for dyeing a brilliant yellow.
A large tree (Ficus Sycomorus) allied to the common fig. It is found in Egypt and Syria and is the sycamore or sycamine of Scripture.
A large tree of the genus Swietenia (S. Mahogoni) found in tropical America.
A large vessel cistern or tub especially one used for holding in an immature state chemical preparations for dyeing or for tanning or for tanning leather or the like.

A large voracious fish (Pomatomus saitatrix) of the family Carangidae valued as a food fish and widely distributed on the American coast. On the New Jersey and Rhode Island coast it is called the horse mackerel in Virginia saltwater tailor or skipjack.
A large wine bottle.
A lark that mounts and sings as it files especially the common species (Alauda arvensis) found in Europe and in some parts of Asia and celebrated for its melodious song; -- called also sky laverock.
A lash; a strap or cord; especially a lash used to inflict pain or punishment; an instrument of punishment or discipline; a whip.
A lateral division of a building separated from the middle part called the nave by a row of columns or piers which support the roof or an upper wall containing windows called the clearstory wall.
A Latin god of commerce and gain; -- treated by the poets as identical with the Greek Hermes messenger of the gods conductor of souls to the lower world and god of eloquence.
A Latin preposition signifying for before forth.
A lattice or grating.
A laundering; a washing.
A law or rule.
A lawgiver; one who makes laws for a state or community; a member of a legislative body.

A lawless military adventurer especially one in quest of plunder; a freebooter; -- originally applied to buccaneers infesting the Spanish American coasts but introduced into common English to designate the followers of Lopez in his expedition to Cuba in 1851 and those of Walker in his expedition to Nicaragua in 1855.
A laxative medicine.
A lay or skein containing 120 yards of yarn.
A laying fast ho1d of; also that by which anything is seized and held a grapnel.
A laying out or expending.
A lazy person.
A leader; a chief; a prince.
A leading or drawing off of water from a stream or source.
A leaf of a book or manuscript.
A league or compact between two or more persons bodies of men or states for mutual support or common action; alliance.
A leaking; also the quantity that enters or issues by leaking.
A leap on one leg as of a boy; a leap as of a toad; a jump; a spring.
A leap; a spring; a hostile advance.
A learned man; a teacher; esp. a Brahman versed in the Sanskrit language and in the science laws and religion of the Hindoos; in Cashmere any clerk or native official.
A lease by a tenant or lessee to another person; an underlease.
A leather case for a pistol carried by a horseman at the bow of his saddle.
A leguminous plant of the genus Ervum (Ervum Lens) of small size common in the fields in Europe. Also its seed which is used for food on the continent.
A leguminous plant of the genus Medicago. The black medic is the Medicago lupulina; the purple medic or lucern is M. sativa.
A lengthened slow monotonous utterance.
A lenitive; an emollient.
A lens of glass to assist the sight. Eyeglasses are used singly or in pairs.
A lesser kind of triumph allowed to a commander for an easy bloodless victory or a victory over slaves.
A letter letters syllable or syllables added or appended to the end of a word or a root to modify the meaning; a postfix.
A letter or writing usually under seal conferring some privilege honor or power; a document bearing record of a degree conferred by a literary society or educational institution.

A level oblong space surrounded on three sides by seats of wood earth or stone rising in tiers one above another and divided lengthwise through the middle by a barrier around which the track or course was laid out. It was used for chariot races games and public shows.
A lever; also leverage.
A lifting or rising; a swell; a panting or deep sighing.
A lifting up by success; exaltation; inriation with pride of prosperity.
A light brisk musical movement.
A light colorless gaseous inflammable hydrocarbon CH4; marsh gas.
A light liquid food made by boiling meal of maize oatmeal or fiour in water or milk; thin porridge.
A light loose over-garment like a smock frock worn especially by workingmen in France; also a loose coat of any material as the undress uniform coat of the United States army.
A light quik blow or stroke with the fingers or hand; a tap.
A light smooth-bored gun often double-barreled especially designed for firing small shot at short range and killing small game.
A light spongy cylindrical cake used for breakfast and tea.
A light with a powerful reflector placed at the head of a locomotive or in front of it to throw light on the track at night or in going through a dark tunnel.

A light and elegantly furnished vessel used either for private parties of pleasure or as a vessel of state to convey distinguished persons from one place to another; a seagoing vessel used only for pleasure trips racing etc.

A light canoe made of skins stretched over a frame and usually capable of carrying but one person who sits amidships and uses a double-bladed paddle. It is peculiar to the Eskimos and other Arctic tribes.
A light of dazzling brilliancy.
A light one horse two-wheeled vehicle.
A light or luminary formed of some combustible substance as of resinous wood; a large candle or flambeau or a lamp giving a large flaring flame.

A light silver-white metallic element malleable and ductile quite permanent in dry air but tarnishing in moist air. It burns forming (the oxide) magnesia with the production of a blinding light (the so-called magnesium light) which is used in signaling in pyrotechny or in photography where a strong actinic illuminant is required. Its compounds occur abundantly as in dolomite talc meerschaum etc. Symbol Mg. Atomic weight 24.4. Specific gravity
A light sleep; a drowse.
A light two-wheeled carriage for a single person.
A light vehicle for conveying small loads. It has two handles and one wheel and is rolled by a single person.
A light wine of several kinds originally made in the province of Champagne in France.
A lighted coal smoldering amid ashes; -- used chiefly in the plural to signify mingled coals and ashes; the smoldering remains of a fire.
A line or long narrow division of anything of a different color or structure from the ground; hence any linear variation of color or structure.
A line at right angles to the plane of the horizon; a vertical line or direction.
A line of ancestors; descent; lineage; genealogy; a register or record of a line of ancestors.
A line of stout posts or timbers set firmly in the earth in contact with each other (and usually with loopholes) to form a barrier or defensive fortification.
A line or band used to lash a furled sail securely. Sea gaskets are common lines; harbor gaskets are plaited and decorated lines or bands. Called also casket.
A line or long mark of a different color from the ground; a stripe; a vein.
A liqueur distilled from fermented cherry juice and flavored with the pit of a variety of cherry which grows in Dalmatia.
A liquor generally spirituous in which a bitter herb leaf or root is steeped.
A liquor composed of vegetable acid especially lemon juice and sugar with spirit to preserve it.
A liquor made of rum and molasses.
A list of dramas operas pieces parts etc. which a company or a person has rehearsed and is prepared to perform.
A list or collection of words arranged in alphabetical order and explained; a dictionary or lexicon either of a whole language a single work or author a branch of science or the like; a word-book.
A little ball.
A little bite or bit of food.
A little book.
A little drop; a tear.
A little face; a small plane surface.
A little hillock of earth thrown up by moles working under ground; hence a very small hill or an insignificant obstacle or difficulty.
A little intoxicated; fuddled; stupid with liquor; bousy.
A little mass or weight of lead or the like attached to a line and used by builders etc. to indicate a vertical direction; a plummet; a plumb bob.
A little pie.
A little round hill; a mound; a small elevation of earth; the top or crown of a hill.
A little sack or bag for carrying papers books or small articles of wearing apparel; a hand bag.
A little spark; a scintillation.
A little towel or small cloth esp. one for wiping the fingers and mouth at table.
A little tower frequently a merely ornamental structure at one of the angles of a larger structure.
A little; a bit as of space time or distance.
A lively spirited march; also a lively style of dancing.
A lively dance of the Highlanders of Scotland; also the music to the dance; -- often called Scotch reel.

A lizardlike reptile of the genus Chamaeleo of several species found in Africa Asia and Europe. The skin is covered with fine granulations; the tail is prehensile and the body is much compressed laterally giving it a high back.
A lobby in a theater; a greenroom.
A local and habitual convulsive motion of certain muscles; especially such a motion of some of the muscles of the face; twitching; velication; -- called also spasmodic tic.
A lock which is not self-latching but requires a key to throw the bolt forward.

A locomotive engine; a self-propelling wheel carriage especially one which bears a steam boiler and one or more steam engines which communicate motion to the wheels and thus propel the carriage -- used to convey goods or passengers or to draw wagons railroad cars etc.
A loding room; esp. a sleeping place partitioned off from a large dormitory.
A loin of beef or a part of a loin.

A long hollow vessel generally for holding water or other liquid especially one formed by excavating a log longitudinally on one side; a long tray; also a wooden channel for conveying water as to a mill wheel.

A long narrow boat with a high prow and stern used in the canals of Venice. A gondola is usually propelled by one or two oarsmen who stand facing the prow or by poling. A gondola for passengers has a small open cabin amidships for their protection against the sun or rain. A sumptuary law of Venice required that gondolas should be painted black and they are customarily so painted now.
A long narrow piece cut or torn off; a strip.
A long narrow pliable strip of leather cloth or the like; specifically a strip of thick leather used in flogging.
A long narrow sword; a rapier.
A long pointed weapon used in war and hunting by thrusting or throwing; a weapon with a long shaft and a sharp head or blade; a lance.
A long slender pointed rod usually of iron for holding meat while roasting.
A long pillow or cushion used to support the head of a person lying on a bed; -- generally laid under the pillows.
A long rope or chain by which an animal is fastened as to a stake so that it can range or feed only within certain limits.
A long seat usually with a cushioned bottom back and ends; -- much used as a comfortable piece of furniture.
A long-horned animal as a cow goat or beetle.
A looking after; a regard to.
A looking back on things past; view or contemplation of the past.
A loose flowing upper garment
A loose negligent dress; ordinary dress as distinguished from full dress.
A loose garment to be worn over other garments; an enveloping robe; a cloak. Hence figuratively a covering or concealing envelope.
A loose gown used for undress; also a gown used for a sleeping garnment.
A loose outer garment extending from the neck downwards and commonly without sleeves. It is longer than a cape and is worn both by men and by women.
A loose under-garment worn by women and covering the body below the waist.
A looseness; diarrhea.
A loss of advantage or deduction from profit value success etc.; a discouragement or hindrance; objectionable feature.
A lost forsaken or solitary person.
A loud deep prolonged sound as of a large beast or of a person in distress anger mirth etc. or of a noisy congregation.
A loud prolonged cry; an outcry.
A loud ringing sound like that made by metallic substances when clanged or struck together.
A loud noise made by sudden collision; a bang.
A loud noise of many confused voices; a tumult; uproar.
A loud resounding outcry or noise as of an enraged bull; a roar.
A lovely maiden daughter of a king and mistress of Eros or Cupid. She is regarded as the personification of the soul.
A lover of mistress.
A lover.
A low confused and indistinct sound like that of running water.
A low continued moan; a murmur.
A low moaning sound; usually a deep mournful sound uttered in pain or great distress; sometimes an expression of strong disapprobation.
A low sluttish woman.
A low whining broken cry; a low whining sound expressive of complaint or grief.
A low hill of drifting sand usually formed on the coats but often carried far inland by the prevailing winds.
A low irregular shrub (Artemisia tridentata) of the order Compositae covering vast tracts of the dry alkaline regions of the American plains; -- called also sagebush and wild sage.
A low monotonous noise as of bees in flight of a swiftly revolving top of a wheel or the like; a drone; a buzz.
A low or subdued tone or utterance; a tone less loud than usual.
A low stool to support the feet of one when sitting.
A low wall serving as a foundation a substructure or a terrace wall.

A luminous circle usually prismatically colored round the sun or moon and supposed to be caused by the refraction of light through crystals of ice in the atmosphere. Connected with halos there are often white bands crosses or arches resulting from the same atmospheric conditions.
A lump of food.
A lump; a mass esp. a native lump of a precious metal.
A lunar distance.
A lyric composition.
A machine for beheading a person by one stroke of a heavy ax or blade which slides in vertical guides is raised by a cord and let fall upon the neck of the victim.
A machine for smoothing linen or cotton cloth as sheets tablecloths napkins and clothing by roller pressure.
A made-up face; a grimace.
A made-up story; stuff; nonsense; humbug; -- often an exclamation of contempt.
A magazine or other publication which appears at stated or regular intervals.

A magical figure cut or engraved under certain superstitious observances of the configuration of the heavens to which wonderful effects are ascribed; the seal figure character or image of a heavenly sign constellation or planet engraved on a sympathetic stone or on a metal corresponding to the star in order to receive its influence.
A magnificent tomb or stately sepulchral monument.
A maid that waits at hand; a female servant or attendant.
A maidservant who has the care of chambers making the beds sweeping cleaning the rooms etc.
A maker of gowns or similar garments; a mantuamaker.
A maker or adapter of plays.
A male cat especially when full grown or of large size.
A male for whom one has stood sponsor in baptism.
A male hawk.
A male horse not castrated; a male horse kept for breeding.
A male servant.
A male voice the compass of which partakes of the common bass and the tenor but which does not descend as low as the one nor rise as high as the other.
A male waiting servant; a servant who attends on gentleman's person; a body servant.
A male witch; a wizard; a sprite; an imp.
A man employed in a large family or on a large estate to manage the domestic concerns supervise other servants collect the rents or income keep accounts and the like.
A man employed in labor whether in tillage or manufactures; a worker.
A man employed in tending feeding and guarding sheep esp. a flock grazing at large.
A man newly married or just about to be married.
A man of any age who has not been married.
A man of coarse nature and manners; an awkward fellow; an ill-bred person; a boor.
A man of extrems enmity or evil intentions.
A man of learning; one versed in literature or science; a person eminent for acquirements.
A man of the same race or family; one related by blood.
A man versed in public affairs and in the principles and art of government; especially one eminent for political abilities.
A man who becomes sponsor for a child at baptism and makes himself a surety for its Christian training and instruction.
A man who commits adultery; a married man who has sexual intercourse with a woman not his wife.
A man who has charge of a door or gate; a doorkeeper; one who waits at the door to receive messages.
A man who has lost his wife by death and has not married again.
A man who is mad; lunatic; a crazy person.
A man who is skilled in traveling upon ice as among glaciers.
A man who makes a practice of amusing others by low tricks antic gestures etc.; a droll; a mimic; a harlequin; a clown; a merry-andrew.
A man who manages a boat; a rower of a boat.
A man who rings a bell especially to give notice of anything in the streets. Formerly also a night watchman who called the hours.
A man who sells milk or delivers is to customers.
A man who takes great care to dress in the latest fashion; a dandy.
A man whose business is to drive a coach or carriage.
A man whose business is to extinguish fires in towns; a member of a fire company.
A man; one; -- used with a verb in the singular and corresponding to the present indefinite one or they.
A manger or rack; a feeding place for animals.
A mark in the skin or flesh of an animal made by a wound or ulcer and remaining after the wound or ulcer is healed; a cicatrix; a mark left by a previous injury; a blemish; a disfigurement.
A mark indicating the height to which water has risen or at which it has stood; the usual limit of high or low water.
A mark made with a burning iron; a brand.
A mark on the ear of sheep oxen dogs etc. as by cropping or slitting.
A mark or cross as the signature of a person who is unable to write.
A mark or depression in the middle of the abdomen; the umbilicus.
A mark or short dash thus [-] placed at the end of a line which terminates with a syllable of a word the remainder of which is carried to the next line; or between the parts of many a compound word.
A mark or stain; hence a slight reproach or disgrace; a stigma; a reproachful intimation; an innuendo.
A mask; a masquerade.
A mason's tool used in spreading and dressing mortar and breaking bricks to shape them.

A mass of fluid especially of a liquid having a whirling or circular motion tending to form a cavity or vacuum in the center of the circle and to draw in towards the center bodies subject to its action; the form assumed by a fluid in such motion; a whirlpool; an eddy.
A mass of hexagonal waxen cells formed by bees and used by them to hold their honey and their eggs.
A mass of stone or iron which has fallen to the earth from space; an aerolite.
A mass of timbers built into the bow and stern of a vessel to give solidity.
A mass; a heap.

A massive compact limestone; a variety of calcite capable of being polished and used for architectural and ornamental purposes. The color varies from white to black being sometimes yellow red and green and frequently beautifully veined or clouded. The name is also given to other rocks of like use and appearance as serpentine or verd antique marble and less properly to polished porphyry granite etc.
A massive somewhat impure variety of quartz in color usually of a gray to brown or nearly black breaking with a conchoidal fracture and sharp edge. It is very hard and strikes fire with steel.
A master in any art especially in music; a composer.
A master of the use of language; a talker.
A master; a lord; especially an absolute or irresponsible ruler or sovereign.
A match or contest of gamecocks.
A mate companion or associate.
A mate; a partner; esp. an accomplice or confederate.

A material object supposed among certain African tribes to represent in such a way or to be so connected with a supernatural being that the possession of it gives to the possessor power to control that being.
A matter of doctrine; also a system of doctrines.
A meal taken at the close of the day; the evening meal.
A mean sneaking fellow.
A mean worthless fellow; a rascal; a villain; a man without honor or virtue.
A measure for fresh herrings -- as many as will fill a barrel.
A measure of capacity equal to half a quart or four gills -- used in liquid and dry measures.
A measure of length containing six feet; the space to which a man can extend his arms; -- used chiefly in measuring cables cordage and the depth of navigable water by soundings.
A measure of length; the eighth part of a mile; forty rods; two hundred and twenty yards.
A measure of length; the thousandth part of one millimeter; the millionth part of a meter.
A measure; a standard of measure; an instrument to determine dimensions distance or capacity; a standard.
A median line or point.
A medicine or agent to assist hearing.
A medicine or other substance that produces contraction in the soft organic textures and checks discharges of blood mucus etc.
A medicine that causes vomiting; an emetic; a vomit.
A medicine which excites action in the stomach; a cardial.
A medicine with diuretic properties.
A mediocre person.

A medium of great elasticity and extreme tenuity supposed to pervade all space the interior of solid bodies not excepted and to be the medium of transmission of light and heat; hence often called luminiferous ether.
A medley or mixture.

A meeting especially a preliminary meeting of persons belonging to a party to nominate candidates for public office or to select delegates to a nominating convention or to confer regarding measures of party policy; a political primary meeting.
A member of a college.
A member of a family which has occupied several European thrones and whose descendants still claim the throne of France.
A member of a jury; a juryman.
A member of the Congress of the United States esp. of the House of Representatives.
A member of the lobby; a person who solicits members of a legislature for the purpose of influencing legislation.

A member of the solar system which usually moves in an elongated orbit approaching very near to the sun in its perihelion and receding to a very great distance from it at its aphelion. A comet commonly consists of three parts: the nucleus the envelope or coma and the tail; but one or more of these parts is frequently wanting.
A member or inhabitant of a colony.
A mender of brass kettles pans and other metal ware.
A mender of shoes.
A merman; the male of the mermaid.
A merry frolic; especially a drinking frolic; a carousal.
A merry-andrew; a buffoon.
A mesh.
A message sent by telegraph; a telegraphic dispatch.
A messenger sent before to give notice of the approach of others; a harbinger; a sign foreshowing something; a prognostic.
A messenger sent with haste to convey letters or dispatches usually on public business.

A metallic element intermediate in value between silver and gold occurring native or alloyed with other metals also as the platinum arsenide (sperrylite). It is heavy tin-white metal which is ductile and malleable but very infusible and characterized by its resistance to strong chemical reagents. It is used for crucibles for stills for sulphuric acid rarely for coin and in the form of foil and wire for many purposes. Specific gravity 21.5. Atomic weight 194.3. Symbol Pt. Formerly called platina.
A metallic element of the alkaline group occurring in several minerals as petalite spodumene lepidolite triphylite etc. and otherwise widely disseminated though in small quantities.

A metallic pin with a head used for uniting two plates or pieces of material together by passing it through them and then beating or pressing down the point so that it shall spread out and form a second head; a pin or bolt headed or clinched at both ends.
A metallic runner with a frame shaped to fit the sole of a shoe -- made to be fastened under the foot and used for moving rapidly on ice.
A metallic vessel with a wide mouth often without a cover used for heating and boiling water or other liguids.
A Mexican shrub (Euphorbia pulcherrima) with very large and conspicuous vermilion bracts below the yellowish flowers.

A microscopic vegetable organism belonging to the class Algae usually in the form of a jointed rodlike filament and found in putrefying organic infusions. Bacteria are destitute of chlorophyll and are the smallest of microscopic organisms. They are very widely diffused in nature and multiply with marvelous rapidity both by fission and by spores. Certain species are active agents in fermentation while others appear to be the cause of certain infectious diseases.
A migratory bird or other animal.
A military man serving on horseback; a knight.
A military state or condition; reliance on military force in administering government; a military system.
A military vassal mentioned in Domesday Book.
A militiaman who was to be ready to march at a moment's notice; -- a term used in the American Revolution.

A milky or colored juice in certain plants in cavities (called latex cells or latex tubes). It contains the peculiar principles of the plants whether aromatic bitter or acid and in many instances yields caoutchouc upon coagulation.
A mill for sawing especially one for sawing timber or lumber.
A mill operated by the power of the wind usually by the action of the wind upon oblique vanes or sails which radiate from a horizontal shaft.

A mill worked by persons treading upon steps on the periphery of a wide wheel having a horizontal axis. It is used principally as a means of prison discipline. Also a mill worked by horses dogs etc. treading an endless belt.
A mineral consisting like quartz of silica but inferior to quartz in hardness and specific gravity.

A mineral having many varieties differing in color and in their constituents but with the same crystallization (isometric) and conforming to the same general chemical formula. The commonest color is red the luster is vitreous and the hardness greater than that of quartz. The dodecahedron and trapezohedron are the common forms.

A mineral occurring in rhombic prisms generally yellowish and pellucid also colorless and of greenesh bluish or brownish shades. It sometimes occurs massive and opaque. It is a fluosilicate of alumina and is used as a gem.

A mineral or rock consisting chiefly of the hydrous silicate of magnesia. It is usually of an obscure green color often with a spotted or mottled appearance resembling a serpent's skin. Precious or noble serpentine is translucent and of a rich oil-green color.
A mingling of discordant sounds; an inharmonious combination of sounds; discord.
A minute arachnid of the order Acarina of which there are many species.
A minute bloodsucking fly.
A minute part or portion of matter; a morsel; a little bit; an atom; a jot.
A miserable person; one profoundly unhappy.
A mistress of a family who is a lady; a woman in authority; especially a lady.
A mitten; also a covering for the wrist and hand and not for the fingers.
A mixed mass; a medley.
A mixture of beer spirit etc. stirred and heated by a hot iron.
A mixture of milk and eggs sweetened and baked or boiled.
A mixture.
A mixture; a compound.
A mixture; a mingled and confused mass of ingredients usually inharmonious; a jumble; a hodgepodge; -- often used contemptuously.
A mode of execution in engraving drawing and miniature painting in which shading is produced by lines crossing each other at angles more or less acute; -- called also crosshatching.
A model or measure.
A moderate and easy gallop adapted to pleasure riding.
A moderate but disagreeable degree of cold; a disagreeable sensation of coolness accompanied with shivering.
A moderate degree of wetness.
A moist slightly cohering mass consisting of soft undissolved animal or vegetable matter.
A moment; an instant.
A monatomic hydrocarbon radical C2H5 of the paraffin series forming the essential radical of ethane and of common alcohol and ether.
A money of account in China equal to one tenth of a tael; also a weight of 57.98 grains.
A monk.
A monk's hood; -- usually attached to the gown. The name was also applied to the hood and garment together.

A morbid condition characterized by yellowness of the eyes skin and urine whiteness of the faeces constipation uneasiness in the region of the stomach loss of appetite and general languor and lassitude. It is caused usually by obstruction of the biliary passages and consequent damming up in the liver of the bile which is then absorbed into the blood.
A more or less elongated process or organ simple or branched proceeding from the head or cephalic region of invertebrate animals being either an organ of sense prehension or motion.

A more or less spherical and transparent mass of granular protoplasm which by a process of multiplication and growth develops into a mass of cells constituting a new individual like the parent; an egg spore germ or germ cell.
A mountain or hill usually more or less conical in form from which lava cinders steam sulphur gases and the like are ejected; -- often popularly called a burning mountain.
A mouth or aperture as of a tube pipe etc.; an opening.

A movable frame of wattled twigs osiers or withes and stakes or sometimes of iron used for inclosing land for folding sheep and cattle for gates etc.; also in fortification used as revetments and for other purposes.

A movable frame or support for anything as scaffolding consisting of three or four legs secured to a top piece and forming a sort of stool or horse used by carpenters masons and other workmen; also a kind of framework of strong posts or piles and crossbeams for supporting a bridge the track of a railway or the like.
A moving flowing or running together; confluence.
A mowing or that which is gathered by mowing; -- chiefly used in composition.
A multitude of persons or of living beings pressing or pressed into a close body or assemblage; a crowd.
A muscle having three heads; specif. the great extensor of the forearm arising by three heads and inserted into the olecranon at the elbow.
A muscle having two heads or origins; -- applied particularly to a flexor in the arm and to another in the thigh.
A muscle which surrounds and by its contraction tends to close a natural opening.
A muscle; flesh.
A musical instrument consisting of a series of hemispherical glasses which by touching the edges with the dampened finger give forth the tones.
A musical instrument consisting of a triangular frame furnished with strings and sometimes with pedals held upright and played with the fingers.
A musical instrument used by the ancients. It is supposed to have been similar to the modern kettle drum though perhaps smaller.
A musical note produced by a number of vibrations which is a multiple of the number producing some other; an overtone.

A musical wind instrument consisting of a hollow cylinder or pipe with holes along its length stopped by the fingers or by keys which are opened by the fingers. The modern flute is closed at the upper end and blown with the mouth at a lateral hole.
A musical wind instrument now used chiefly in the Highlands of Scotland.
A muskmelon of several varieties having when mature a yellowish skin and flesh of a reddish orange color.
A mutual agreement of two or more persons or parties or one of the stipulations in such an agreement.
A myrtaceous genus of trees mostly Australian. Many of them grow to an immense height one or two species exceeding the height even of the California Sequoia.
A mysterious composite being the winged footstool and chariot of the Almighty described in Ezekiel i. and x.

A mystical word or collocation of letters written as in the figure. Worn on an amulet it was supposed to ward off fever. At present the word is used chiefly in jest to denote something without meaning; jargon.
A mythical person who makes children sleepy so that they rub their eyes as if there were sand in them.

A name applied to various marine univalve shells; esp. to those of the genus Strombus which are of large size. S. gigas is the large pink West Indian conch. The large king queen and cameo conchs are of the genus Cassis.
A name for several plants with golden yellow blossoms especially the Calendula officinalis and the cultivated species of Tagetes.
A name formerly given in Pennsylvania Maryland and Virginia to the Spanish real of one eighth of a dollar (or 12/ cents) valued at eleven pence when the dollar was rated at 7s. 6d.
A name given by coppersmiths to an alloy of copper tin iron etc. usually called white metal.
A name given in contempt derision or sportive familiarity; a familiar or an opprobrious appellation.
A name given in the United States to various species of siluroid fishes.
A name given to many umbrella-shaped fungi mostly of the genus Agaricus. The species are almost numberless. They grow on decaying organic matter.
A name given to several peculiar palms species of Calamus and Daemanorops having very long smooth flexible stems commonly called rattans.
A name of several kinds of water lilies.
A name or appellation which is added to or over and above the baptismal or Christian name and becomes a family name.
A narrow bridge for foot passengers only.
A narrow circle of persons associated by common interests or for the accomplishment of a common purpose; -- generally used in a bad sense.
A narrow opening made by the parting of any substance; a cleft.
A narrow opening resulting from a split or crack or the separation of a junction; a cleft; a fissure; a rent.
A narrow passage; especially a walk or passage in a garden or park bordered by rows of trees or bushes; a bordered way.
A narrow path or way for pedestrains only; a footway.
A narrow place formed by an angle in bodies or between bodies; a corner; a recess; a secluded retreat.
A nation or state recognized as carrying on war; a person engaged in warfare.
A native of Afghanistan.
A native or inhabitant of Sparta; figuratively a person of great courage and fortitude.
A native or inhabitant of the Orient or some Eastern part of the world; an Asiatic.
A native or inhabitant of the west.
A native or inhabitant of Venice.
A natural covered opening in the earth; a cave; also an artificial recess cave or cavernlike apartment.
A natural or acquired disposition or capacity for a particular purpose or tendency to a particular action or effect.
A natural stream of water smaller than a river or creek.

A naval officer of the highest rank; a naval officer of high rank of which there are different grades. The chief gradations in rank are admiral vice admiral and rear admiral. The admiral is the commander in chief of a fleet or of fleets.
A naval vessel having the parts above water covered and protected by iron or steel usually in large plates closely joined and made sufficiently thick and strong to resist heavy shot.
A nearly pellucid variety of feldspar showing pearly or opaline reflections from within. It is used as a gem. The best specimens come from Ceylon.
A necklace of a rural fashion bought at St. Audrey's fair; hence a necklace in general.

A nervous affection occurring almost exclusively in women in which the emotional and reflex excitability is exaggerated and the will power correspondingly diminished so that the patient loses control over the emotions becomes the victim of imaginary sensations and often falls into paroxism or fits.
A net or snare; any thread web or string spread for taking prey; -- usually in the plural.
A network; a plait; a fold; rarely a garment.
A new birth or revival.
A newspaper; a printed sheet published periodically; esp. the official journal published by the British government and containing legal and state notices.
A nightgown.

A nobleman of England ranking below a marquis and above a viscount. The rank of an earl corresponds to that of a count (comte) in France and graf in Germany. Hence the wife of an earl is still called countess.
A noise made in the throat.
A noisy blustering fellow more insolent than courageous; one who is threatening and quarrelsome; an insolent tyrannical fellow.
A noisy quarrel; loud angry contention; a wrangle; a tumult.
A noisy report; rumor.
A nominalist.
A noncommissioned officer next below a sergeant. In the United States army he is the lowest noncommissioned officer in a company of infantry. He places and relieves sentinels.
A noncommissioned officer or soldier who attends a superior officer to carry his orders or to render other service.

A nonmetalic element analogous to carbon. It always occurs combined in nature and is artificially obtained in the free state usually as a dark brown amorphous powder or as a dark crystalline substance with a meetallic luster. Its oxide is silica or common quartz and in this form or as silicates it is next to oxygen the most abundant element of the earth's crust. Silicon is characteristically the element of the mineral kingdom as carbon is of the organic world. Symbol Si. Atomic weight 28. Called also silicium.

A non-metallic gaseous element strongly acid or negative or associated with chlorine bromine and iodine in the halogen group of which it is the first member. It always occurs combined is very active chemically and possesses such an avidity for most elements and silicon especially that it can neither be prepared nor kept in glass vessels. If set free it immediately attacks the containing material so that it was not isolated until 1886. It is a pungent

A nonmetallic element of the halogen group occurring always in combination as in the iodides. When isolated it is in the form of dark gray metallic scales resembling plumbago soft but brittle and emitting a chlorinelike odor. Symbol I. Atomic weight 126.5. If heated iodine volatilizes in beautiful violet vapors.

A North American aquatic fur-bearing rodent (Fiber zibethicus). It resembles a rat in color and having a long scaly tail but the tail is compressed the bind feet are webbed and the ears are concealed in the fur. It has scent glands which secrete a substance having a strong odor of musk. Called also musquash musk beaver and ondatra.

A North American nocturnal carnivore (Procyon lotor) allied to the bears but much smaller and having a long full tail banded with black and gray. Its body is gray varied with black and white. Called also coon and mapach.
A nosegay; a bunch of flowers.
A notch; a cleft; a barb; a ragged or sharp protuberance; a denticulation.
A note of reference or comment at the foot of a page.
A notice given by an interested party to some officer not to do a certain act until the party is heard in opposition.
A noun or name; the part of speech which designates something that exists or some object of thought either material or immaterial.
A number letter or any quantity written on the right hand of and above another quantity and denoting how many times the latter is repeated as a factor to produce the power indicated
A number expressed in the scale of tens; specifically and almost exclusively used as synonymous with a decimal fraction.
A number of beasts assembled together.
A number of foxes together.

A number of lines or verses forming a division of a song or poem and agreeing in meter rhyme number of lines etc. with other divisions; a part of a poem ordinarily containing every variation of measure in that poem; a combination or arrangement of lines usually recurring; whether like or unlike in measure.
A number of things bound together as by a cord or envelope into a mass or package convenient for handling or conveyance; a loose package; a roll.
A numbering of the people and valuation of their estate for the purpose of imposing taxes etc.; -- usually made once in five years.
A nurse.

A painful and usually fatal disease resulting generally from a wound and having as its principal symptom persistent spasm of the voluntary muscles. When the muscles of the lower jaw are affected it is called locked-jaw or lickjaw and it takes various names from the various incurvations of the body resulting from the spasm.
A painting or depicting; a representation.
A painting or drawing in a single color; a picture made with a single color.

A pair of pinchers or tongs; an instrument for grasping holding firmly or exerting traction upon bodies which it would be inconvenient or impracticable to seize with the fingers especially one for delicate operations as those of watchmakers surgeons accoucheurs dentists etc.
A paling; a hurdle.
A paltry or disreputable fellow; a mean wretch.
A pan for warming beds.
A pandemic disease.

A paragraph added to a letter after it is concluded and signed by the writer; an addition made to a book or composition after the main body of the work has been finished containing something omitted or something new occurring to the writer.

A parasitic evergreen plant of Europe (Viscum album) bearing a glutinous fruit. When found upon the oak where it is rare it was an object of superstitious regard among the Druids. A bird lime is prepared from its fruit.
A paroxysm of extreme pain or anguish; a sudden and transitory agony; a throe.
A part of a helmet arranged so as to lift or open and so show the face. The openings for seeing and breathing are generally in it.
A part of a man's beard on the chin or lower lip which is allowed to grow and trimmed so as to resemble the beard of a goat.
A part of male dress in front of the breeches formerly made very conspicuous.

A part of speech partaking of the nature both verb and adjective; a form of a verb or verbal adjective modifying a noun but taking the adjuncts of the verb from which it is derived. In the sentences: a letter is written; being asleep he did not hear; exhausted by toil he will sleep soundly -- written being and exhaustedare participles.

A partaker; a person having an interest in any action or thing; one who has an interest in an estate created by another; a person having an interest derived from a contract or conveyance to which he is not himself a party. The term in its proper sense is distinguished from party.
A partition covering or frame of parallel or cross bars; a latticework resembling a window grate.
A partition in a vessel to separate apartments on the same deck.
A passage by which an inclosed place may be entered; a place of ingress; entrance.
A passage or way along or through which a carriage may be driven.
A passage or way into or out of any inclosed place; esp. a temporary way of access formed of planks.
A passage through a fence or wall; a gate; also a frame arch etc. in which a gate in hung or a structure at an entrance or gate designed for ornament or defense.
A passage through; a passage from one street or opening to another; an unobstructed way open to the public; a public road; hence a frequented street.
A passing round; circuit; circuitous course.
A paved yard or floor where ores are cleaned and sorted or where ore salt mercury etc. are trampled by horses to effect intermixture and amalgamation.
A pavement or sidewalk of flagstones; flagstones collectively.
A pawl click or detent for holding or propelling a ratchet wheel or ratch etc.
A pawnbroker's shop or room for storing articles put in pawn; hence a pledge or pawn.
A peculiar gait of a horse in which both legs on the same side are moved at the same time alternating with the legs on the other side.
A peculiar glandlike but ductless organ found near the stomach or intestine of most vertebrates and connected with the vascular system; the milt. Its exact function in not known.
A peculiarity of physical or mental constitution or temperament; a characteristic belonging to and distinguishing an individual; characteristic susceptibility; idiocrasy; eccentricity.
A pen or sty for pigs.
A pen for animals; esp. an inclosure made with wagons by emigrants in the vicinity of hostile Indians as a place of security for horses cattle etc.
A pen or inclosure for swine.
A pendent and usually conical mass of ice formed by freezing of dripping water.
A perennial cruciferous plant (Cheiranthus Cheiri) with sweet-scented flowers varying in color from yellow to orange and deep red. In Europe it very common on old walls.
A perennial plant; a plant which lives or continues more than two years whether it retains its leaves in winter or not.
A perennial suffrutescent plant (Ruta graveolens) having a strong heavy odor and a bitter taste; herb of grace. It is used in medicine.
A perforated stone-faced runner for grinding.
A performer esp. a skilled performer on the piano.
A perfumed liquid composed of alcohol and certain aromatic oils used in the toilet; -- called also cologne water and eau de cologne.
A period of six months; especially a term in a college or uneversity which divides the year into two terms.
A periodical work published once a quarter or four times in a year.
A perjured person.
A person or one of two or more persons chosen by parties who have a controversy to determine their differences.

A person whether negro Indian or white in whom by some defect of organization the substance which gives color to the skin hair and eyes is deficient or in a morbid state. An albino has a skin of a milky hue with hair of the same color and eyes with deep red pupil and pink or blue iris. The term is also used of the lower animals as white mice elephants etc.; and of plants in a whitish condition from the absence of chlorophyll.
A person affected by excessive enthusiasm particularly on religious subjects; one who indulges wild and extravagant notions of religion.
A person affected by lunacy; an insane person esp. one who has lucid intervals; a madman; a person of unsound mind.
A person affected with asthma.
A person affected with leprosy.
A person appointed.
A person diseased beyond cure.
A person excluded from the benefit of the law or deprived of its protection.
A person having red hair.
A person lower in station rank intellect etc. than another.
A person of consequence.
A person of the Mongolian race.
A person of weak intellect; a silly person.

A person or thing regarded with peculiar favor; one treated with partiality; one preferred above others; especially one unduly loved trusted and enriched with favors by a person of high rank or authority.
A person or thing that moves stirs or changes place.
A person or thing that shakes or by means of which something is shaken.
A person to whose sole decision a controversy or question between parties is referred; especially one chosen to see that the rules of a game as cricket baseball or the like are strictly observed.

A person transformed into a wolf in form and appetite either temporarily or permanently whether by supernatural influences by witchcraft or voluntarily; a lycanthrope. Belief in werewolves formerly general is not now extinct.
A person untaught or uninformed; one unlettered or unskilled; an ignoramous.
A person versed in chemistry or given to chemical investigation; an analyst; a maker or seller of chemicals or drugs.
A person well versed in theology; a professor of theology or divinity; a divine.
A person who accepts the creeds which are received in common by all parts of the orthodox Christian church.
A person who adheres to his sovereign or to the lawful authority; especially one who maintains his allegiance to his prince or government and defends his cause in times of revolt or revolution.
A person who bargains closely especially one who cheats in bargains; a swinder; also a cheating gamester.
A person who breeds or trains hawks for taking birds or game; one who follows the sport of fowling with hawks.
A person who claps.
A person who cuts wood.
A person who devotes himself to the spread of any system of principles.
A person who has committed a felony.
A person who is in present possession of a benefice or of any office.
A person who is inquisitive; one curious in research.
A person who knowingly utters falsehood; one who lies.
A person who lacks courage; a timid or pusillanimous person; a poltroon.
A person who lives in solitude; a recluse; a hermit.
A person who makes a business of taking care of people's hands especially their nails.
A person who presides at a public dinner or banquet and announces the toasts.
A person who retires from society and lives in solitude; a recluse; an anchoret; especially one who so lives from religious motives.
A person who rises in revolt against civil authority or an established government; one who openly and actively resists the execution of laws; a rebel.
A person who sells by auction; a person whose business it is to dispose of goods or lands by public sale to the highest or best bidder.
A person who takes no part in a contest; one who is either indifferent to a cause or forbears to interfere; a neutral.
A person whose business is to pack things; especially one who packs food for preservation.

A person whose employment is to clean the streets of a city by scraping or sweeping and carrying off the filth. The name is also applied to any animal which devours refuse carrion or anything injurious to health.
A pet; a darling.
A petty contrivance; a toy; a plaything; a knickknack.
A phosphorescent substance.
A piace where animals are kept and trained.
A picture representing a scene at sea.
A piece as a ring or hook attached to another piece by a pin in such a manner as to permit rotation about the pin as an axis.
A piece of burning wood.
A piece of cane or red with a knot at each end or a hollow cylinder of wood with a ridge at each end used to wind thread or yarn upon.
A piece of cloth usually square and often fine and elegant carried for wiping the face or hands.
A piece of cloth torn off; a tattered piece of cloth; a shred; a tatter; a fragment.
A piece of dining-room furniture having compartments and shelves for keeping or displaying articles of table service.
A piece of furniture holding the ewer or pitcher basin and other requisites for washing the person.
A piece of ground used for recreation.
A piece of ground where seed is sown for producing plants for transplantation; a nursery; a seed plat.
A piece of heavy ordnance formerly used for throwing stones and other ponderous missiles. It was the earliest kind of cannon.
A piece of lead attached to a line used in sounding the depth of water.
A piece of meat especially of veal or mutton cut for broiling.

A piece of metal or other hard material thick at one end and tapering to a thin edge at the other used in splitting wood rocks etc. in raising heavy bodies and the like. It is one of the six elementary machines called the mechanical powers.
A piece of orange or lemon peel or the aromatic oil which may be squeezed from such peel used to give flavor to liquor etc.
A piece of sculpture representing the upper part of the human figure including the head shoulders and breast.
A piece of stone natural or artificial used for whetting or sharpening edge tools.
A piece of thick plank armed with iron plates and fixed on the bow or fore channels of a vessel for the bill or fluke of the anchor to rest on.

A piece of timber laid horizontally or nearly so to which the planks of the floor or the laths or furring strips of a ceiling are nailed; -- called according to its position or use binding joist bridging joist ceiling joist trimming joist etc.
A piece or point of land extending beyond the adjacent coast into the sea or a lake; a promontory; a headland.
A piece split off; a splinter.
A pigpen.
A pigsty.
A pill or bolus for introduction into the rectum; esp. a cylinder or cone of medicated cacao butter.
A pimp; also a bawd.
A pin or block of wood or metal fitting into holes in the abutting portions of two pieces and being partly in one piece and partly in the other to keep them in their proper relative position.
A pin usually forked or of bent wire for fastening the hair in place -- used by women.
A pin of wood or metal for fastening meat to a spit or for keeping it in form while roasting.
A pin or peg used to stop the vent in a cask; also the plug of a faucet or cock.
A pinch; a tweak; a twitch.
A pipe canal channel or passage for conveying water or fluid.
A pipe used for carrying off surplus water.
A pipe with a long flexible stem so arranged that the smoke is cooled by being made to pass through water.
A piping or whistling sound caused by difficult respiration.
A pit or inclosed area for cockfights.
A pit deceitfully covered to entrap wild beasts or men; a trap of any kind.
A pit in which the dead body of a human being is deposited; a grave; a sepulcher.
A pit or vat for packing away green fodder for winter use so as to exclude air and outside moisture.
A place spot or location.
A place for washing.
A place in a river or other water where it may be passed by man or beast on foot by wading.
A place in an animal body where the skin and flesh are ruptured or bruised so as to be tender or painful; a painful or diseased place such as an ulcer or a boil.
A place in which to lie or rest; especially the bed or couch of a wild beast.
A place mended by darning.
A place near the fire or hearth; home; domestic life or retirement.
A place of deposit for the storing of goods; a warehouse; a storehouse.
A place of orisons or prayer; especially a chapel or small room set apart for private devotions.
A place of shelter; hence dwelling; habitation; residence; abode.
A place of trade; a market place; a mart; esp. a city or town with extensive commerce; the commercial center of a country.
A place or building for making observations on the heavenly bodies.

A place or building in which stores of wealth are deposited; especially a place where public revenues are deposited and kept and where money is disbursed to defray the expenses of government; hence also the place of deposit and disbursement of any collected funds.
A place or building where athletic exercises are performed; a school for gymnastics.
