A place or room for the stowage of cargo in a ship; also the act of stowing cargo; the pulling and moving about of packages incident to close stowage; -- formerly written romage.
A place that covers and protects; a shelter; a defense.
A place to walk in whether in the open air as the gallery of a cloister or within a building.
A place where anything is deposited for sale or keeping.

A place where anything is kept in store; especially a place where water is collected and kept for use when wanted as to supply a fountain a canal or a city by means of aqueducts or to drive a mill wheel or the like.
A place where arms and instruments of war are deposited for safe keeping.
A place where butter and cheese are made or where milk and cream are put up in cans for market.
A place where medicines are prepared and dispensed; esp. a place where the poor can obtain medical advice and medicines gratuitously or at a nominal price.
A place where persons under arrest are temporarily locked up; a watchhouse.
A place where the bodies of persons found dead are exposed that they may be identified or claimed by their friends; a deadhouse.
A place where the business of canning fruit meat etc. is carried on.
A place where the work of tanning is carried on.
A place where things are or may be reposited or laid up for safety or preservation; a depository.
A place where water boils up; a spring that wells forth.
A placing or being placed in nearness or contiguity or side by side.
A plaintive cry of or like that of a sheep.
A plaintive tone; the nasal childish tone of mean complaint; mean or affected complaint.
A plait band or narrow fabric formed by intertwining or weaving together different strands.
A plane figure having five angles and consequently five sides; any figure having five angles.
A plane figure having many angles and consequently many sides; esp. one whose perimeter consists of more than four sides; any figure having many angles.
A plane figure of eight sides and eight angles.
A plane figure of six angles.
A plane four-sided figure having two sides parallel to each other.
A plant and its flower of the ranunculaceous genus Paeonia. Of the four or five species one is a shrub; the rest are perennial herbs with showy flowers often double in cultivation.
A plant drug or medicine characterized by a fragrant smell and usually by a warm pungent taste as ginger cinnamon spices.

A plant (Astragalus Hornii) growing in the Southwestern United States which is said to poison horses and cattle first making them insane. The name is also given vaguely to several other species of the same genus. Called also loco weed.
A plant (Fagopyrum esculentum) of the Polygonum family the seed of which is used for food.
A plant (Solanum Melongena) of East Indian origin allied to the tomato and bearing a large smooth edible fruit shaped somewhat like an egg; mad-apple.
A plant and flower of the genus Lilium endogenous bulbous plants having a regular perianth of six colored pieces six stamens and a superior three-celled ovary.
A plant from which layers are propagated by bending its branches into the soil.

A plant having twigs suitable for making brooms to sweep with when bound together; esp. the Cytisus scoparius of Western Europe which is a low shrub with long straight green angular branches minute leaves and large yellow flowers.
A plant of different species of the genus Trifolium.
A plant of several species of the genus Aquilegia.
A plant of the Cabbage species (Brassica oleracea) of many varieties resembling the cauliflower. The curd or flowering head is the part used for food.
A plant of the genus Allium (A. Porrum) having broadly linear succulent leaves rising from a loose oblong cylindrical bulb. The flavor is stronger than that of the common onion.

A plant of the genus Allium (A. sativum is the cultivated variety) having a bulbous root a very strong smell and an acrid pungent taste. Each root is composed of several lesser bulbs called cloves of garlic inclosed in a common membranous coat and easily separable.

A plant of the genus Aralia the root of which is highly valued as a medicine among the Chinese. The Chinese plant (Aralia Schinseng) has become so rare that the American (A. quinquefolia) has largely taken its place and its root is now an article of export from America to China. The root when dry is of a yellowish white color with a sweetness in the taste somewhat resembling that of licorice combined with a slight aromatic bitterness.
A plant of the genus Asphodelus.
A plant of the genus Campanula; -- so named from its bell-shaped flowers.
A plant of the genus Cannabis (C. sativa) the fibrous skin or bark of which is used for making cloth and cordage. The name is also applied to various other plants yielding fiber.

A plant of the genus Hedera (H. helix) common in Europe. Its leaves are evergreen dark smooth shining and mostly five-pointed; the flowers yellowish and small; the berries black or yellow. The stem clings to walls and trees by rootlike fibers.
A plant of the genus Ranunculus or crowfoot particularly R. bulbosus with bright yellow flowers; -- called also butterflower golden cup and kingcup. It is the cuckoobud of Shakespeare.

A plant of the genus Urtica covered with minute sharp hairs containing a poison that produces a stinging sensation. Urtica gracitis is common in the Northern and U. chamaedryoides in the Southern United States. the common European species U. urens and U. dioica are also found in the Eastern united States. U. pilulifera is the Roman nettle of England.

A plant of the genus Viola (V. tricolor) and its blossom originally purple and yellow. Cultivated varieties have very large flowers of a great diversity of colors. Called also heart's-ease love-in-idleness and many other quaint names.
A plant of the genus Zingiber of the East and West Indies. The species most known is Z. officinale.
A plant of the Parsley family (Apium graveolens) of which the blanched leafstalks are used as a salad.
A plant of the Rubia (R. tinctorum). The root is much used in dyeing red and formerly was used in medicine. It is cultivated in France and Holland.
A plant reared from the seed as distinguished from one propagated by layers buds or the like.
A plant; chard.
A plate or thin piece of baked clay used for covering the roofs of buildings for floors for drains and often for ornamental mantel works.
A plate of cartilage or a series of bony or cartilaginous plates or segments in the median line of the pectoral skeleton of most vertebrates above fishes; the breastbone.
A plate of metal covering the breast as defensive armor.
A platform projecting from the wall of a building usually resting on brackets or consoles and inclosed by a parapet.
A platform; the bottom of a room; a floor; pavement.
A play among boys in which one stoops down and another leaps over him by placing his hands on the shoulders of the former.
A play among children in which they are seated upon the opposite ends of a plank which is balanced in the middle and move alternately up and down.
A play on words which have the same sound but different meanings; an expression in which two different applications of a word present an odd or ludicrous idea; a kind of quibble or equivocation.
A player on the harp; a harper.
A player on the violin.
A pleasing taste; flavor that gratifies the palate; hence enjoyable quality; power of pleasing.
A pleasure boat; a vessel or boat of state elegantly furnished and decorated.
A pledge; a pawn.
A pliant strip of wood or metal bent in a circular form and united at the ends for holding together the staves of casks tubs etc.
A plug introduced into a natural or artificial cavity of the body in order to arrest hemorrhage or for the application of medicine.
A plum; esp. a dried plum used in cookery.
A plume or bunch of feathers esp. such a bunch worn on the helmet; any military plume or ornamental group of feathers.
A plunderer.
A poem describing the life and manners of shepherds; a poem in which the speakers assume the character of shepherds; an idyl; a bucolic.
A point equally distant from the extremities of a line figure or body or from all parts of the circumference of a circle; the middle point or place.

A pointed instrument for piercing small holes as in leather or wood; used by shoemakers saddlers cabinetmakers etc. The blade is differently shaped and pointed for different uses as in the brad awl saddler's awl shoemaker's awl etc.
A pointed instrument for pricking or puncturing as a goad an awl a skewer etc.
A pointed instrument of the dagger kind fitted on the muzzle of a musket or rifle so as to give the soldier increased means of offense and defense.
A pointed instument for clearing the teeth of substances lodged between them.
A pointed missile weapon intended to be thrown by the hand; a short lance; a javelin; hence any sharp-pointed missile weapon as an arrow.
A poisonous American serpent (Ancistrodon conotortrix) closely allied to the rattlesnake but without rattles; -- called also copper-belly and red viper.

A pole or piece of wood constructed with a step or loop to raise the foot above the ground in walking. It is sometimes lashed to the leg and sometimes prolonged upward so as to be steadied by the hand or arm.
A politician.
A poor person; especially one development on private or public charity. Also used adjectively.
A popular kind of narrative poem adapted for recitation or singing.
A porous earthen pot used in India for cooling water etc.
A port on the seashore or one accessible for seagoing vessels. Also used adjectively.
A portable chair or covered vehicle for carrying a single person -- usually borne on poles by two men. Called also sedan chair.

A portable lock with a bow which is usually jointed or pivoted at one end so that it can be opened the other end being fastened by the bolt -- used for fastening by passing the bow through a staple over a hasp or through the links of a chain etc.
A portable set of steps.
A portion of a curved line.
A portion of anything taken separately; a fragment of a whole; a part.
A portion of land nearly surrounded by water and connected with a larger body by a neck or isthmus.
A post on which a sign hangs or on which papers are placed to give public notice of anything.
A post or courier; a letter carrier.
A post or station without the limits of a camp or at a distance from the main body of an army for observation of the enemy.
A pouch or sac without opening usually membranous and containing morbid matter which is accidentally developed in one of the natural cavities or in the substance of an organ.
A pouring or streaming downwards; esp. a heavy or continuous shower.
A powerful alkaloid C17H21NO4 obtained from the leaves of coca. It is a bitter white crystalline substance and is remarkable for producing local insensibility to pain.

A powerful brass instrument of the trumpet kind thought by some to be the ancient sackbut consisting of a tube in three parts bent twice upon itself and ending in a bell. The middle part bent double slips into the outer parts as in a telescope so that by change of the vibrating length any tone within the compass of the instrument (which may be bass or tenor or alto or even in rare instances soprano) is commanded. It is the only member of the family of wind instruments whose scale both diatonic and chromatic is complete without the aid of keys or pistons
A prayer or petition.
A prayer.
A precious stone of a carmine red color sometimes verging to violet or intermediate between carmine and hyacinth red. It is a red crystallized variety of corundum.
A precious stone of a rich green color a variety of beryl.
A preface.
A preparation made from the seeds of the chocolate tree and used in making a beverage; also the beverage made from cocoa or cocoa shells.
A preserve or confection made of the pulp of fruit as the quince pear apple orange etc. boiled with sugar and brought to a jamlike consistence.
A pretty or dear little bird; -- a pet name.
A price less than the value.
A priest of Shamanism; a wizard among the Shamanists.
A primitive Chinese instrument of the cittern kind with from five to twenty-five silken strings.
A prince of the imperial family of Austria.
A prince; a potentate.
A print made by lithography.
A printed and stitched book containing only a few leaves; a pamphlet.
A printed programme of a play with the parts assigned to the actors.
A prisoner taken by force or stratagem esp. by an enemy in war; one kept in bondage or in the power of another.
A privy or water-closet esp. in a camp hospital etc.
A privy or jakes.
A procession distinguished by ostentation and splendor; a pageant.
A professional rider of horses in races.
A projecting mass of masonry used for resisting the thrust of an arch or for ornament and symmetry.
A prolonged or exhaustive discussion; especially an acrimonious or invective harangue; a strain of abusive or railing language; a philippic.
A prolonged sound like that letter s made by forcing out the breath between the tongue and teeth esp. as a token of disapprobation or contempt.
A prop or support.
A proper name of a man.
A property which is not essential; a nonessential; anything happening accidentally.
A proposition or thing which denies or opposes another; contrariety.
A proprietor or owner; one who has exclusive title to a thing; one who possesses or holds the title to a thing in his own right.
A protuberance; especially the protuberance formed by a crooked back.
A public command or ordinance by the sovereign power; the proclamation of a law made by an absolute authority as if by the very act of announcement; a decree.
A public establishment for the storage or for the manufacture and storage of arms and all military equipments whether for land or naval service.
A public house where travelers and other transient guests are accomodated with rooms and meals; an inn; a hotel; especially in modern times a public house licensed to sell liquor in small quantities.
A public proclamation; a manifesto or edict issued by authority.
A public speaker; one who delivers an oration; especially one distinguished for his skill and power as a public speaker; one who is eloquent.
A public square in a city or town.
A pull with the utmost effort as in the athletic contest called tug of war; a supreme effort.
A pulling with force; a violent pull.
A pupil who attends the same school as another.
A puppet moved by strings as in a puppet show.
A pustular affection of the skin due to changes in the sebaceous glands.
A pustular eruptive disease of the cow which when communicated to the human system as by vaccination protects from the smallpox; vaccinia; -- called also kinepox cowpock and kinepock.
A putting off of that which was appointed; a postponement or delay.
A quadrat.

A quadrumanous mammal esp. of the family Simiadae having teeth of the same number and form as in man and possessing neither a tail nor cheek pouches. The name is applied esp. to species of the genus Hylobates and is sometimes used as a general term for all Quadrumana. The higher forms the gorilla chimpanzee and ourang are often called anthropoid apes or man apes.

A quadruped of the genus Sus and allied genera of Suidae; esp. the domesticated varieties of S. scrofa kept for their fat and meat called respectively lard and pork; swine; porker; specifically a castrated boar; a barrow.
A quagmire filled with decayed moss and other vegetable matter; wet spongy ground where a heavy body is apt to sink; a marsh; a morass.
A quantic of the seventh degree.
A quick rolling movement; a gallop.
A quick breathing; a catching of the breath; a gasp.
A quick succession of slight sounds.
A quick succession or confusion of small sounds like those made by shaking leaves or straw by rubbing silk or the like; a rustling.
A quilted bed; a bed stuffed with hair moss or other suitable material and quilted or otherwise fastened.
A race for three-old horses run annually at Epsom (near London) for the Derby stakes. It was instituted by the 12th Earl of Derby in 1780.
A raftsman.
A railway sleeper lying parallel with the rail.
A raised level space shelf or platform of earth supported on one or more sides by a wall a bank of tuft or the like whether designed for use or pleasure.
A raised structure (as a square or oblong erection of stone or wood) on which sacrifices are offered or incense burned to a deity.
A rapid succession of sharp clattering sounds.

A rare element of the chromium group found in certain minerals as wolfram and scheelite and isolated as a heavy steel-gray metal which is very hard and infusible. It has both acid and basic properties. When alloyed in small quantities with steel it greatly increases its hardness. Symbol W (Wolframium). Atomic weight 183.6. Specific gravity 18.
A rascal; a swindler; a rogue.
A rash or eruption; a sudden or transient fit of sickness.
A rattling clinking or tinkling sound as of little bells or pieces of metal.
A rattling noise esp. that made by the collision of hard bodies; also any loud abrupt sound; a repetition of abrupt sounds.
A raving lunatic; a madman.
A ray of light from the moon.

A reaping instrument consisting of a steel blade curved into the form of a hook and having a handle fitted on a tang. The sickle has one side of the blade notched so as always to sharpen with a serrated edge. Cf. Reaping hook under Reap.
A rebound or skipping as of a ball along the ground when a gun is fired at a low angle of elevation or of a fiat stone thrown along the surface of water.
A recessed portion of a room or a small room opening into a larger one; especially a recess to contain a bed; a lateral recess in a library.
A recital.
A recitation or song of a rhapsodist; a portion of an epic poem adapted for recitation or usually recited at one time; hence a division of the Iliad or the Odyssey; -- called also a book.
A reckless furious man; a person urged by furious passions and regardless of consequence; a wild ruffian.
A record of something which it is desired to remember; a note to help the memory.
A rectangular figure longer than it is broad; hence any figure longer than it is broad.
A rectangular garment or piece of cloth usually made of the checkered material called tartan but sometimes of plain gray or gray with black stripes. It is worn by both sexes in Scotland.

A red acid berry much used for making sauce etc.; also the plant producing it (several species of Vaccinum or Oxycoccus.) The high cranberry or cranberry tree is a species of Viburnum (V. Opulus) and the other is sometimes called low cranberry or marsh cranberry to distinguish it.
A red amorphous powder consisting of ferric oxide. It is used in polishing glass metal or gems and as a cosmetic etc. Called also crocus jeweler's rouge etc.

A reddish crust or sediment in wine casks consisting essentially of crude cream of tartar and used in marking pure cream of tartar tartaric acid potassium carbonate black flux etc. and in dyeing as a mordant for woolen goods; -- called also argol wine stone etc.
A reflection; a jeer or gibe; a sally; a brief satire; a squib.
A refractory person.
A refreshing drink common in the East made of the juice of some fruit diluted sweetened and flavored in various ways.
A register or roll showing the order in which officers enlisted men companies or regiments are called on to serve.
A relative in general; especially a descendant whether male or female; a granddaughter or a grandson.
A remarkable meteorological phenomenon of the nature of a tornado or whirlwind usually observed over the sea but sometimes over the land.
A remedy for acidity of the stomach as an alkali or absorbent.
A remedy to counteract the effects of poison or of anything noxious taken into the stomach; -- used with against for or to.
A remedy which allays irritability and irritation and irritative activity or pain.
A removable case or covering for a pillow usually of white linen or cotton cloth.
A representation in art of the figure of Christ upon the cross; esp. the sculptured figure affixed to a real cross of wood ivory metal or the like used by the Roman Catholics in their devotions.
A representation of the outlines of an object filled in with a black color; a profile portrait in black such as a shadow appears to be.
A representation of two of the leg bones or arm bones of a skeleton laid crosswise often surmounted with a skull and serving as a symbol of death.
A resin containing more or less of an essential or volatile oil.

A restatement of a text passage or work expressing the meaning of the original in another form generally for the sake of its clearer and fuller exposition; a setting forth the signification of a text in other and ampler terms; a free translation or rendering; -- opposed to metaphrase.
A resting place.
A retired nook; especially a small sheltered inlet creek or bay; a recess in the shore.
A revolving frame in a footpath preventing the passage of horses or cattle but admitting that of persons; a turnpike.
A Rhenish wine of a light yellow color either sparkling or still. The name is also given indiscriminately to all Rhenish wines.
A rhizopod. common in fresh water capable of undergoing many changes of form at will.

A rich stuff for shawls scarfs etc. originally made in Cashmere from the soft wool found beneath the hair of the goats of Cashmere Thibet and the Himalayas. Some cashmere of fine quality is richly embroidered for sale to Europeans.
A rick.
A riddle or obscure question; an enigma; a ridiculous hoax.
A riddle or sieve.
A rider on horseback; one skilled in the management of horses; a mounted man.
A ridge of land left unplowed between furrows or at the end of a field; a piece missed by the plow slipping aside.
A ridge of mountain and craggy rocks with a serrated or irregular outline.
A ridge.
A right line drawn from one angle to another not adjacent of a figure of four or more sides and dividing it into two parts.
A right line drawn or extending from the center of a circle to the periphery; the semidiameter of a circle or sphere.
A right or estate inherited from one's father; or in a larger sense from any ancestor.

A right-lined quadrilateral figure whose opposite sides are parallel and consequently equal; -- sometimes restricted in popular usage to a rectangle or quadrilateral figure which is longer than it is broad and with right angles.

A rigid piece which is capable of turning about one point or axis (the fulcrum) and in which are two or more other points where forces are applied; -- used for transmitting and modifying force and motion. Specif. a bar of metal wood or other rigid substance used to exert a pressure or sustain a weight at one point of its length by receiving a force or power at a second and turning at a third on a fixed point called a fulcrum. It is usually named as the first of the six mechanical powers and is of three kinds
A ring series of rings or spiral into which a rope or other like thing is wound.
A ring for gauging wooden pins.
A ringlet especially of hair; anything of a spiral or winding form.
A rite or ceremony performed with religious reverence; religious or ritual ceremony.
A road that crosses another; an obscure road intersecting or avoiding the main road.
A road; especially the part traveled by carriages.
A robber upon the sea; a pirate; -- a term applied especially to the piratical adventurers who made depredations on the Spaniards in America in the 17th and 18th centuries.

A rock consisting chiefly of calcium carbonate or carbonate of lime. It sometimes contains also magnesium carbonate and is then called magnesian or dolomitic limestone. Crystalline limestone is called marble.
A rock made of sand more or less firmly united. Common or siliceous sandstone consists mainly of quartz sand.
A rocket that ascends high and burns as it flies; a species of fireworks.
A rod or staff carried as an emblem of authority.
A rodent of the genus Lepus having long hind legs a short tail and a divided upper lip. It is a timid animal moves swiftly by leaps and is remarkable for its fecundity.
A roll of paper or parchment; a writing formed into a roll; a schedule; a list.
A rolling marshy mossy plain of Northern Siberia.
A Roman officer who controlled or superintended a particular command charge department etc..
A romping girl; a hoiden.
A rooflike cover usually of canvas extended over or before any place as a shelter from the sun rain or wind.
A room attached to any place of public resort where cloaks overcoats etc. may be deposited for a time.
A room for balls or dancing.
A room for business or social conversation for the reception of guests etc.
A room in which pupils are taught.
A room or apartment where a show is exhibited.
A room or apartment where clothes are kept or wearing apparel is stored; a portable closet for hanging up clothes.
A room or rooms under a building and usually below the surface of the ground where provisions and other stores are kept.
A roommate especially in a college or university; an old and intimate friend.
A rope or long thong of leather with a running noose used for catching horses cattle etc.
A rope or wire on which clothes are hung to dry.
A rope used to hold in place the foremost lower corners of the courses when the vessel is closehauled; also a rope employed to pull the lower corner of a studding sail to the boom.

A rotating wheel mounted in a ring or rings for illustrating the dynamics of rotating bodies the composition of rotations etc. It was devised by Professor W. R. Johnson in 1832 by whom it was called the rotascope.
A rotunda.
A rough haphazard struggle or trial of strength; a disorderly wrestling at close quarters.
A round building; especially one that is round both on the outside and inside like the Pantheon at Rome. Less properly but very commonly used for a large round room.
A round dance.
A round mass of snow pressed or roller together or anything resembling such a mass.
A rounded mass or irregular shape; a little knot or lump.
A roundish mass of dough boiled in soup or as a sort of pudding; often a cover of paste inclosing an apple or other fruit and boiled or baked.
A round-up.
A rover in quest of booty or plunder; a plunderer; one who pillages.
A roving frolicsome thing; a trifler; -- used rarely as a term of endearment.
A rubbing or kneading of the body especially when performed as a hygienic or remedial measure.
A rude picture as of a bird beast or the like used by the North American Indians as a symbolic designation as of a family or a clan.
A rule of diet; a fixed allowance of food as in workhouse prison etc.
A ruler or sovereign of a Mohammedan state; specifically the ruler of the Turks; the Padishah or Grand Seignior; -- officially so called.
A ruler or state that pays tribute or a stated sum to a conquering power for the purpose of securing peace and protection or as an acknowledgment of submission or for the purchase of security.
A running into; hence an entering into a territory with hostile intention; a temporary invasion; a predatory or harassing inroad; a raid.
A running knot or loop which binds the closer the more it is drawn.
A running or issuing of blood as from the nose or a wound; a hemorrhage; the operation of letting blood as in surgery; a drawing or running of sap from a tree or plant.
A rushing or setting upon; an attack; an assault; a storming; especially the assault of an army.
A russet color; a pigment of a russet color.
A Russian drink distilled from rye.

A sacred character; a character in picture writing as of the ancient Egyptians Mexicans etc. Specifically in the plural the picture writing of the ancient Egyptian priests. It is made up of three or as some say four classes of characters: first the hieroglyphic proper or figurative in which the representation of the object conveys the idea of the object itself; second
A sacred place; a consecrated spot; a holy and inviolable site.
A sacred place; hence a place of retreat; a room reserved for personal use.
A sacred song; a poetical composition for use in the praise or worship of God.
A saddle for women in which the rider sits with both feet on one side of the animal mounted.
A sailor; a seaman.
A salad made of sliced cabbage.
A sale at second hand or at retail; also a second sale.
A salient angle or part; a projection.
A salt of lactic acid.
A salt of nitric acid.
A salt of phosphoric acid.
A sapling left standing in a fallen wood.

A sauce compounded of raw yolks of eggs beaten up with olive oil to the consistency of a sirup and seasoned with vinegar pepper salt etc.; -- used in dressing salads fish etc. Also a dish dressed with this sauce.
A sauce.
A saw used with one hand.
A scampering; a hasty flight.
A Scandinavian legend or heroic or mythic tradition among the Norsemen and kindred people; a northern European popular historical or religious tale of olden time.
A scarf band or kerchief of silk etc. passing around the neck or collar and tied in front; a bow of silk etc. fastened in front of the neck.

A scarf or band worn about the waist over the shoulder or otherwise; a belt; a girdle -- worn by women and children as an ornament; also worn as a badge of distinction by military officers members of societies etc.
A scent bag or perfume cushion to be laid among handkerchiefs garments etc. to perfume them.
A schedule system or scheme of duties imposed by the government of a country upon goods imported or exported.

A scheme of equalizing the social conditions of life; specifically a scheme which contemplates the abolition of inequalities in the possession of property as by distributing all wealth equally to all or by holding all wealth in common for the equal use and advantage of all.

A school for young children conducted on the theory that education should be begun by gratifying and cultivating the normal aptitude for exercise play observation imitation and construction; -- a name given by Friedrich Froebel a German educator who introduced this method of training in rooms opening on a garden.
A scoop with a long handle used to wash the sides of a vessel and formerly to wet the sails or deck.
A screen of boards inclosing a house and materials while builders are at work.
A scuffle; a wrangle; a brawl.
A scurf which forms on the head and comes off in small or particles.
A seaport town of Arabia on the Red Sea.

A season or day of rest; one day in seven appointed for rest or worship the observance of which was enjoined upon the Jews in the Decalogue and has been continued by the Christian church with a transference of the day observed from the last to the first day of the week which is called also Lord's Day.

A seat for a rider -- usually made of leather padded to span comfortably a horse's back furnished with stirrups for the rider's feet to rest in and fastened in place with a girth; also a seat for the rider on a bicycle or tricycle.
A seat in an open boat reaching from one side to the other or athwart the boat.
A seat; especially a royal seat; a throne.
A secdond trial experiment or test; a second judicial trial as of an accused person.
A secluded private or obscure way; a path or road aside from the main one.
A secluded and narrow valley; a dale; a depression between hills.
A second growth of grass; aftergrass.
A second location.
A second or further writ which is issued after a first writ has expired without effect.
A second or repeated issue.
A second or repeated marriage.
A second union; union formed anew after separation secession or discord.
A seed.
A seizing by violence; a hurrying along; rapidity with violence.

A self-acting apparatus for regulating temperature by the unequal expansion of different metals liquids or gases by heat as in opening or closing the damper of a stove or the like as the heat becomes greater or less than is desired.

A self-evident and necessary truth or a proposition whose truth is so evident as first sight that no reasoning or demonstration can make it plainer; a proposition which it is necessary to take for granted.

A semifluid or fluid oleoresin primarily the exudation of the terebinth or turpentine tree (Pistacia Terebinthus) a native of the Mediterranean region. It is also obtained from many coniferous trees especially species of pine larch and fir.

A sensation of dryness in the throat associated with a craving for liquids produced by deprivation of drink or by some other cause (as fear excitement etc.) which arrests the secretion of the pharyngeal mucous membrane; hence the condition producing this sensation.
A sentence phrase or word forming part of an heraldic achievment.
A sentence in which the ideas fall or become less important and striking at the close; -- the opposite of climax. It produces a ridiculous effect.

A series of arches with the columns or piers which support them the spandrels above and other necessary appurtenances; sometimes open serving as an entrance or to give light; sometimes closed at the back (as in the cut) and forming a decorative feature.
A series of short convulsive inspirations the glottis being suddenly closed so that little or no air enters into the lungs.
A series of three dramas which although each of them is in one sense complete have a close mutual relation and form one historical and poetical picture. Shakespeare's Henry VI. is an example.

A serpent or monster in the lake or marsh of Lerna in the Peloponnesus represented as having many heads one of which when cut off was immediately succeeded by two others unless the wound was cauterized. It was slain by Hercules. Hence a terrible monster.
A servant or slave employed in husbandry and in some countries attached to the soil and transferred with it as formerly in Russia.
A service of pastry fruits or sweetmeats at the close of a feast or entertainment; pastry fruits etc. forming the last course at dinner.
A set of staves and headings sufficient in number for one hogshead cask barrel or the like trimmed and bound together in compact form.
A setting out starting or beginning.
A settled mart; an emporium; a city or town to which merchants brought commodities for sale or exportation in bulk; a place for wholesale traffic.
A severe paroxysmal pain in the abdomen due to spasm obstruction or distention of some one of the hollow viscera.
A shade of difference; a delicate gradation.
A shaft or missile intended to be shot from a crossbow or catapult esp. a short stout blunt-headed arrow; a quarrel; an arrow or that which resembles an arrow; a dart.
A shaking or agitation; a shock; caused by the collision of two bodies.
A shaking; a tremulous motion.
A shallow sound channel pond or lake especially one into which the sea flows.
A share; a part or portion; -- obsolete except in the colloquial phrase to go snacks i. e. to share.
A sharp brief ringing sound made by a collision of metallic or other sonorous bodies; -- usually expressing a duller or less resounding sound than clang and a deeper and stronger sound than clink.
A sharp hooked nail as of a beast or bird.
A sharp narrow spade usually with a long handle used by farmers for digging up large-rooted weeds; a similarly shaped implement used for various purposes.
A sharp quick cry; a bark.
A sharp quick noise; a smack.

A sharp shrill disagreeable sound suddenly utered either of the human voice or of any animal or instrument such as is made by carriage wheels when dry by the soles of leather shoes or by a pipe or reed.
A sharp shrill outcry or scream; a shrill wild cry such as is caused by sudden or extreme terror pain or the like.
A sharp burst of thunder; a sudden report of a discharge of atmospheric electricity.
A sharp pinch or jerk; a twist or twitch.
A sharp-pointed instrument.
A sheath; a theca.
A shed or roof sloping from the main wall or building as over a door or window; a lean-to. Also figuratively.
A sheep.
A shelf on which articles may be laid; also that which resembles such a shelf in form or use as a projecting ridge or part or a molding or edge in joinery.
A shelf to hold books.
A shell used as a die.
A shell or husk; a cod or pod.
A shelter in which one may rest.
A shift or turn from the point in question; a trifling or evasive distinction; an evasion; a cavil.

A shining material used for ornamental purposes; especially a very thin gauzelike cloth with much gold or silver woven into it; also very thin metal overlaid with a thin coating of gold or silver brass foil or the like.
A ship or seagoing vessel propelled by the power of steam; a steamer.
A ship's side; hence by extension a ship; -- found chiefly in adverbial phrases.
A shirt worn next the skin under another shirt; -- called also undervest.
A shock of grain.
A shoe for horses consisting of a narrow plate of iron in form somewhat like the letter U nailed to a horse's hoof.
A shoe made of deerskin or other soft leather the sole and upper part being one piece. It is the customary shoe worn by the American Indians.

A shoe or clog as of iron attached to a chain and placed under the wheel of a wagon to prevent its turning when descending a steep hill; a drag; a skidpan; also by extension a hook attached to a chain and used for the same purpose.
A shoot of a plant springing from the root or bottom of the original stalk; a sucker.
A shoot of light; a small stream of light; a beam; a ray; a glimpse.
A shoot or sprout of a plant; a sucker.
A short heavy curving sword used in the navy.
A short precise step; an affected manner.
A short sharp note as of a bird or insect.
A short sleeveless coat or garment for men worn under the coat extending no lower than the hips and covering the waist; a vest.
A short stiff coarse hair as on the back of swine.
A short sudden pull thrust push twitch jolt shake or similar motion.
A short suppressed laugh; the expression of satisfaction exultation or derision.
A short thick heavy piece of wood.
A short variously distorted foot; also the deformity usually congenital which such a foot exhibits; talipes.
A short crowbar used by burglars in breaking open doors.
A short dressing jacket for women.
A short entertainment exhibited on the stage between the acts of a play or between the play and the afterpiece to relieve the tedium of waiting.
A short piece of rope or line for fastening something in ships.
A short poem -- usually amatory.

A short poem treating concisely and pointedly of a single thought or event. The modern epigram is so contrived as to surprise the reader with a witticism or ingenious turn of thought and is often satirical in character.
A short poetical composition proper to be set to music or sung; a lyric poem; esp. now a poem characterized by sustained noble sentiment and appropriate dignity of style.
A short sleep taken about the middle of the day or after dinner; a midday nap.
A short sleep; a doze; a siesta.
A short sleep; a nap.
A short stick with one end loaded or thicker and heavier that the other used as an offensive weapon.
A short weapon used for stabbing. This is the general term: cf. Poniard Stiletto Bowie knife Dirk Misericorde Anlace.
A shovel-like utensil for conveying away dust brushed from the floor.
A shrapnel shell; shrapnel shells collectively.
A shrill somewhat prolonged cry.
A shrill sound.

A shrub of the genus Syringa. There are six species natives of Europe and Asia. Syringa vulgaris the common lilac and S. Persica the Persian lilac are frequently cultivated for the fragrance and beauty of their purplish or white flowers. In the British colonies various other shrubs have this name.

A shrub or small tree of the genus Corylus as the C. avellana bearing a nut containing a kernel of a mild farinaceous taste; the filbert. The American species are C. Americana which produces the common hazelnut and C. rostrata.

A shrubby plant of the genus Jasminum bearing flowers of a peculiarly fragrant odor. The J. officinale common in the south of Europe bears white flowers. The Arabian jasmine is J. Sambac and with J. angustifolia comes from the East Indies. The yellow false jasmine in the Gelseminum sempervirens. Several other plants are called jasmine in the West Indies as species of Calotropis and Faramea.
A sieve with coarse meshes usually of wire for separating coarser materials from finer as chaff from grain cinders from ashes or gravel from sand.
A sign made without words; a beck.
A signal fire to notify of the approach of an enemy or to give any notice commonly of warning.
A signer; one who signs or subscribes.
A silk cloth of a thick close texture and overshot woof which has a glossy surface.
A silk fabric having a short close nap of erect threads. Inferior qualities are made with a silk pile on a cotton or linen back.
A silver coin and money of account in the East Indies.
A silver coin and money of account of Great Britain and its dependencies equal to twelve pence or the twentieth part of a pound equivalent to about twenty-four cents of the United States currency.
A silver coin of the United States of the value of ten cents; the tenth of a dollar.
A similar channel or groove made in wood or other material esp. in plaited cloth as in a lady's ruffle.
A simple podlike pericarp which contains several seeds and opens along the inner or ventral suture as in the peony larkspur and milkweed.
A simpleton; a blockhead; a stupid person; a ninny.
A singer or vocal musician as opposed to an instrumentalist.
A single cut as with shears or scissors; a clip.
A single particle of ice falling from a cloud; a frozen raindrop; a pellet of hail.
A single pass of a needle in sewing; the loop or turn of the thread thus made.
A single unvaried tone or sound.
A sip or small draught; esp. a draught of intoxicating liquor; a dram.
A sitting on eggs for the purpose of hatching young; a brooding on or keeping warm (eggs) to develop the life within by any process.
A skilled worker; an artisan; esp. one who operates a machine in a mill or manufactory.
A skillful hand; a dabster; an expert.
A skin or hide of a beast with the wool or hair on; a pelt; -- used chiefly in composition as woolfell.
A skirting board.
A slanting direction or plane; a slope.
A slap; a quick stroke.
A slave; a villain; a serf; a bondman.
A sleeping room or a building containing a series of sleeping rooms; a sleeping apartment capable of containing many beds; esp. one connected with a college or boarding school.
A sleepy person.
A slender graceful breed of dogs remarkable for keen sight and swiftness. It is one of the oldest varieties known and is figured on the Egyptian monuments.
A slender stalk or blade in vegetation.
A slice of beef broiled or cut for broiling; -- also extended to the meat of other large animals.

A sliding piece which either is moved by or moves against fluid pressure. It usually consists of a short cylinder fitting within a cylindrical vessel along which it moves back and forth. It is used in steam engines to receive motion from the steam and in pumps to transmit motion to a fluid; also for other purposes.
A slight sharp tinkling sound made by the collision of sonorous bodies.
A slight coloring.

A slight frame of wood three or four feet long and about one third as wide with thongs or cords stretched across it and having a support and holder for the foot; -- used by persons for walking on soft snow.
A slight natural depression or indentation on the surface of some part of the body esp. on the cheek or chin.
A slight shake; a shake or push intended to give notice or awaken attention; a push; a jolt.
A slight twist with the fingers.

A slightly acrid gum resin produced by the common hemp (Cannabis saltiva) of the variety Indica when cultivated in a warm climate; also the tops of the plant from which the resinous product is obtained. It is narcotic and has long been used in the East for its intoxicating effect.
A slightly built or temporary habitation; especially a tent.
a slovenly manner.
A slow graceful dance consisting of a coupee a high step and a balance.
A small mean dwelling; a rough slight building for temporary use; a hut.
A small plain brown and gray European song bird (Luscinia luscinia). It sings at night and is celebrated for the sweetness of its song.
A small pointed piece of wood used in fastening boards together in attaching the soles of boots or shoes etc..
A small portable keyed wind instrument whose tones are generated by play of the wind upon free metallic reeds.
A small retired valley; a ravine.
A small shrill flute the pitch of which is an octave higher than the ordinary flute; an octave flute.
A small usually hard tumor on the skin formed by enlargement of its vascular papillae and thickening of the epidermis which covers them.
A small and mean bed; a bed of straw.
A small Asiatic mammal (Ailurus fulgens) having fine soft fur. It is related to the bears and inhabits the mountains of Northern India.
A small ax with a short handle to be used with one hand.
A small bag or pouch the opening of which is made to draw together closely used to carry money in; by extension any receptacle for money carried on the person; a wallet; a pocketbook; a portemonnaie.
A small bag; usually a leathern bag.
A small basket of rushes reeds or willow twigs etc.
A small bone in the foot of a horse.
A small book or case for carrying papers money etc. in the pocket; also a notebook for the pocket.
A small bottle usually of glass; a little glass vessel with a narrow aperture intended to be closed with a stopper.
A small bottle-shaped vessel for holding fluids.
A small bundle as of straw or other like substance.
A small cake composed chiefly of the white of eggs almonds and sugar.
A small cask or barrel.
A small cavern or hollow place in the side of a hill or among rocks; esp. a cave used by a wild beast for shelter or concealment.
A small chest or box esp. of rich material or ornamental character as for jewels etc.
A small compartment in a desk or case for the keeping of letters documents etc.; -- so called from the resemblance of a row of them to the compartments in a dovecote.
A small cord covered with cloth -- used as trimming for women's dresses.
A small cup from which to drink tea.
A small cushion in which pins may be stuck for use.
A small dish pan or vase.

A small domesticated cyprinoid fish (Carassius auratus); -- so named from its color. It is native of China and is said to have been introduced into Europe in 1691. It is often kept as an ornament in small ponds or glass globes. Many varieties are known. Called also golden fish and golden carp.
A small drum especially a shallow drum with only one skin played on with the hand and having bells at the sides; a timbrel.

A small European fresh-water cyprinoid fish (Phoxinus laevis formerly Leuciscus phoxinus); sometimes applied also to the young of larger kinds; -- called also minim and minny. The name is also applied to several allied American species of the genera Phoxinus Notropis or Minnilus and Rhinichthys.

A small European insectivore (Erinaceus Europaeus) and other allied species of Asia and Africa having the hair on the upper part of its body mixed with prickles or spines. It is able to roll itself into a ball so as to present the spines outwardly in every direction. It is nocturnal in its habits feeding chiefly upon insects.
A small European rodent (Cricetus frumentarius). It is remarkable for having a pouch on each side of the jaw under the skin and for its migrations.
A small European singing bird (Erythacus rubecula) having a reddish breast; -- called also robin redbreast robinet and ruddock.

A small fish about three inches in length of the Herring family (Engraulis encrasicholus) caught in vast numbers in the Mediterranean and pickled for exportation. The name is also applied to several allied species.

A small flag; a pennon. The narrow / long pennant (called also whip or coach whip) is a long narrow piece of bunting carried at the masthead of a government vessel in commission. The board pennant is an oblong nearly square flag carried at the masthead of a commodore's vessel.
A small fragment or piece; especially a small piece of bread or other food broken or cut off.
A small fruit tree (Ficus Carica) with large leaves known from the remotest antiquity. It was probably native from Syria westward to the Canary Islands.
A small glass tube often with an enlargement or bulb in the middle and usually graduated -- used for transferring or delivering measured quantities.
A small horse.
A small horse.
A small horse; a pony; hence any horse.
A small hound or hunting dog twelve to fifteen inches high used in hunting hares and other small game.
A small house hivel or cabin; a mean lodge or dwelling; a slightly built or temporary structure.
A small house on or above a vessel's deck containing the steering wheel.
A small house or building at a little distance from the main house; an outbuilding.
A small house; a cottage or hut.
A small image in the human form; a doll.
A small inlet or bay narrower and extending further into the land than a cove; a recess in the shore of the sea or of a river.
A small instrument with four strings played with a bow; a fiddle.
A small job; in the pl. the regular or daily light work of a household or farm either within or without doors.
A small kind of onion (Allium Ascalonicum) growing in clusters and ready for gathering in spring; a scallion or eschalot.
A small kind of seedless raisin imported from the Levant chiefly from Zante and Cephalonia; -- used in cookery.
A small knife with a thin keen blade -- used by surgeons and in dissecting.
A small lock; a catch or spring to fasten a necklace or other ornament.
A small mass of matter of irregular shape; an irregular or shapeless mass.
A small maul with a short handle -- used esp. for driving a tool as a chisel or the like; also a light beetle with a long handle -- used in playing croquet.
A small mug or cup.
A small opening as in the walls of fortification or in the bulkhead of a ship through which small arms or other weapons may be discharged at an enemy.
A small or cautious bite.
A small organ at the upper part of the vulva homologous to the penis in the male.
A small pan or vessel in which sauce was set on a table.
A small pan with a handle in which sauce is prepared over a fire; a stewpan.
A small part or piece.
A small piece of cloth worn by children over the breast to protect the clothes.
A small piece of paper or parchment containing the heads of a writing; a summary or digest.
A small pliant twig or osier; a rod for making basketwork and the like; a withe.
A small pocketknife; formerly a knife used for making and mending quill pens.
A small pond or pool where fish are kept for the table; a vivarium.
A small portable organ played with one hand the bellows being worked with the other -- used in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries.
A small protuberance on the stem or branches of a plant containing the rudiments of future leaves flowers or stems; an undeveloped branch or flower.
A small quantity of batter fried in boiling lard or in a frying pan. Fritters are of various kinds named from the substance inclosed in the batter.
A small quantity of dirty standing water; a muddy plash; a small pool.
A small quantity scattered or sparsely distributed; a sprinkling.
A small rodent (Chinchilla lanigera) of the size of a large squirrel remarkable for its fine fur which is very soft and of a pearly gray color. It is a native of Peru and Chili.
A small roll of tobacco used for smoking.
A small room or apartment for retirement; a room for privacy.
A small round dish with a handle usually of porcelain.
A small roundish stone or bowlder; especially a stone worn and rounded by the action of water; a pebblestone.
A small sailing vessel commonly rigged as a sloop used chiefly in the coasting and fishing trade.
A small shoot or branch of a tree or other plant of no definite length or size.
A small shoot or branch; a twig.
A small shoot or scion of a tree inserted in another tree the stock of which is to support and nourish it. The two unite and become one tree but the graft determines the kind of fruit.
A small shoot or twig of a tree or other plant; a spray.
A small singing bird of many genera and species belonging to the family Fringillidae.

A small song bird (Sialia sialis) very common in the United States and in the north one of the earliest to arrive in spring. The male is blue with the breast reddish. It is related to the European robin.
A small spoon used in stirring and sipping tea coffee etc. and for other purposes.

A small statue; -- usually applied to a figure much less than life size especially when of marble or bronze or of plaster or clay as a preparation for the marble or bronze as distinguished from a figure in terra cotta or the like. Cf. Figurine.
A small stick; a rod; a verge.
A small telescope for viewing distant terrestrial objects.
A small tower fort or castle; a keep.
A small tree of the genus Citrus (C. Japonica) growing in China and Japan; also its small acid orange-colored fruit used for preserves.
A small trough or wooden vessel sometimes scooped out of a block of wood for various domestic uses as in making bread chopping meat etc.
A small vessel of iron copper or other metal with a handle used for culinary purpose as for stewing meat.
A small village; a little cluster of houses in the country.
A small wax candle; a small lighted wax candle; hence a small light.
A small wooden vessel made of staves and hoops like a tub.
A small yellowish or brownish spot in the skin particularly on the face neck or hands.
A smaller group of trees than a forest and without underwood planted or growing naturally as if arranged by art; a wood of small extent.
A smart sarcastic turn or jest; a taunt; a severe retort; a gibe.
A smart resounding blow.
A smell; an odor.
A smith who works in iron with a forge and makes iron utensils horseshoes etc.
A smooth-skinned variety of peach.
A snug or confined place.
A soft earthy dark-colored rock or clay derived from the alteration of basalt.
A soft earthy substance of a white grayish or yellowish white color consisting of calcium carbonate and having the same composition as common limestone.
A soft nappy woolen cloth of loose texture.
A soft and flexible fabric for men's wear made wholly of wool except in some inferior kinds the wool being dyed usually in two colors before weaving.
A soft composition as of flour moistened with water or milk or of earth moistened to the consistence of dough as in making potter's ware.
A soft cover of cylindrical form usually of fur worn by women to shield the hands from cold.

A soft earth which is plastic or may be molded with the hands consisting of hydrous silicate of aluminium. It is the result of the wearing down and decomposition in part of rocks containing aluminous minerals as granite. Lime magnesia oxide of iron and other ingredients are often present as impurities.
A soft mineral of a soapy feel and a greenish whitish or grayish color usually occurring in foliated masses. It is hydrous silicate of magnesia. Steatite or soapstone is a compact granular variety.
A soldier armed with a musket.
A soldier armed with a rifle.
A soldier in a body of cavalry; a cavalryman; also the horse of a cavalryman.
A soldier in the Continental army or a piece of the Continental currency.
A soldier placed on guard; a sentinel.
A soldier who marches and fights on foot; a foot soldier.
A soldier; a fighting man.
A sole or supreme ruler; a sovereign; the highest ruler; an emperor king queen prince or chief.
A solemn authentic instrument in writing by which a person declares his will as to disposal of his estate and effects after his death.
A solemn affirmation or declaration made with a reverent appeal to God for the truth of what is affirmed.
A solid body standing on a triangular square or polygonal base and terminating in a point at the top; especially a structure or edifice of this shape.
A solid body which may be generated by the rotation of a parallelogram round one its sides; or a body of rollerlike form of which the longitudinal section is oblong and the cross section is circular.

A solid of the form described by the revolution of a right-angled triangle about one of the sides adjacent to the right angle; -- called also a right cone. More generally any solid having a vertical point and bounded by a surface which is described by a straight line always passing through that vertical point; a solid having a circle for its base and tapering to a point or vertex.
A solid whose bases or ends are any similar equal and parallel plane figures and whose sides are parallelograms.

A solution of continuity in any of the soft parts of the body discharging purulent matter found on a surface especially one of the natural surfaces of the body and originating generally in a constitutional disorder; a sore discharging pus. It is distinguished from an abscess which has its beginning at least in the depth of the tissues.
A solution of salt and water in which fish meat etc. may be preserved or corned; brine.
A son of one's husband or wife by a former marriage.
A song to quiet babes or lull them to sleep; that which quiets.
A son's or daughter's child; a child in the second degree of descent.
A son's or daughter's son.
A sorry fellow; a worthless person; a rogue.
A sort of bread made of unbolted rye which forms the chief food of the Westphalian peasants. It is acid but nourishing.
A sort of chest or box as in a window the lid of which serves for a seat.
A sort of cotton velveteen having the surface raised in ridges.

A sort of ecclesiastical heriot a customary gift claimed by and due to the minister of a parish on the death of a parishioner. It seems to have been originally a voluntary bequest or donation intended to make amends for any failure in the payment of tithes of which the deceased had been guilty.
A sort of leather prepared from the skin of the buffalo dressed with oil like chamois; also the skins of oxen elks and other animals dressed in like manner.
A sort of light spear to be thrown or cast by thew hand; anciently a weapon of war used by horsemen and foot soldiers; now used chiefly in hunting the wild boar and other fierce game.
A sort of petticoat worn by both sexes in Java and the Malay Archipelago.
A sort of very large nail; also a piece of pointed iron set with points upward or outward.
A sort of wild ox; a buffalo.
A sound formed in the throat; esp. a sound formed by the aid of the back of the tongue much retracted and the soft palate; also a letter representing such a sound.
A sound like that made by bees; a low murmuring sound; a hum.
A sound of quick movement as of something whirled through the air.
A soup thickened with the mucilaginous pods of the okra; okra soup.
A sour liquid used as a condiment or as a preservative and obtained by the spontaneous (acetous) fermentation or by the artificial oxidation of wine cider beer or the like.
A sour or acid substance; whatever produces a painful effect.

A South American ruminant (Auchenia llama) allied to the camels but much smaller and without a hump. It is supposed to be a domesticated variety of the guanaco. It was formerly much used as a beast of burden in the Andes.
A space of forty days; -- used of Lent.
A space or opening made by splitting; a crack; a crevice.
A spacious and elegant apartment for the reception of company or for works of art; a hall of reception esp. a hall for public entertainments or amusements; a large room or parlor.
A Spanish dollar; also an Argentine Chilian Colombian etc. coin equal to from 75 cents to a dollar; also a pound weight.
A Spanish light-colored dry wine made in Andalusia. As prepared for commerce it is colored a straw color or a deep amber by mixing with it cheap wine boiled down.
A sparrow.

A spear or javelin used to strike and kill large fish as whales; a harping iron. It consists of a long shank with a broad fiat triangular head sharpened at both edges and is thrown by hand or discharged from a gun.
A special business intrusted to a messenger; something to be told or done by one sent somewhere for the purpose; often a verbal message; a commission.

A species of asceticism among the Hindoos which consists in a complete abstraction from all worldly objects by which the votary expects to obtain union with the universal spirit and to acquire superhuman faculties.
A species of coarse potter's ware glazed and baked.
A species of food of a soft or moderately hard consistence variously made but often a compound of flour or meal with milk and eggs etc.
A species of Galium (G. Aparine) having a fruit set with hooked bristles which adhere to whatever they come in contact with; -- called also goose grass catchweed etc.

A species of hickory (Carya olivaeformis) growing in North America chiefly in the Mississippi valley and in Texas where it is one of the largest of forest trees; also its fruit a smooth oblong nut an inch or an inch and a half long with a thin shell and well-flavored meat.
A species of leopard (Cynaelurus jubatus) tamed and used for hunting in India. The woolly cheetah of South Africa is C. laneus.
A species of mint (Mentha viridis) growing in moist soil. It vields an aromatic oil.
A species of small open pie or piece of pastry containing jelly or conserve; a sort of fruit pie.

A species of the genus Bos or Bubalus (B. bubalus) originally from India but now found in most of the warmer countries of the eastern continent. It is larger and less docile than the common ox and is fond of marshy places and rivers.
A spectroscope fitted for measurements of the luminious spectra observed with it.
A speech or short poem addressed to the spectators and recited by one of the actors after the conclusion of the play.
A speech or writing in commendation of the character or services of a person.
A speech uttered by a person alone; soliloquy; also talk or discourse in company in the strain of a soliloquy.

A spheroidal body growing from a plant either above or below the ground (usually below) which is strictly a bud consisting of a cluster of partially developed leaves and producing as it grows a stem above and roots below as in the onion tulip etc. It differs from a corm in not being solid.
A spire; also the tower and spire taken together; the whole of a structure if the roof is of spire form.
A spirit; a ghost; an apparition; a hobgoblin.
A spirit; a soul; a shade; also an apparition.
A spiritual teacher guide or confessor amoung the Hindoos.
A spit.
A spitbox; a cuspidor.
A spongy semivitrifled substance which miners or smelters mix with the ores of metals to prevent their fusion.
A sponsor; a godfather or a godmother.
A spoon of the largest size commonly used at the table; -- distinguished from teaspoon dessert spoon etc.
A spot or stain as of ink on paper; a blur.
A spot; a blemish; a mole.
A spot; a stain; a daub.
A spout projecting from the roof gutter of a building often carved grotesquely.
A spring of water issuing from the earth.
A spring of water; hence water or a pure transparent liquid like water.
A spring or mineral water; -- so called from a place of this name in Belgium.
A square of fine linen worn by women as a covering for the head; hence anything similar in form or material worn for ornament on other parts of the person; -- mostly used in compounds.
A square or oblong cloth of wool cotton silk or other textile or netted fabric used especially by women as a loose covering for the neck and shoulders.
A square or oblong opening in a deck or floor affording passage from one deck or story to another; the entrance to a cellar.
A square; a measure; a rule.
A squirrel-like animal of the genus Tamias sometimes called the striped squirrel chipping squirrel ground squirrel hackee. The common species of the United States is the Tamias striatus.
A stack or conical pile of hay in the open air.
A stackyard.
A staff on which a flag is hoisted.
A staff or truncheon used for various purposes.
A staff with a crosspiece at the head to be placed under the arm or shoulder to support the lame or infirm in walking.
A stain; a tache.
A stake sharpened or pointed especially one used in fortification and encampments to mark bounds and angles; or one used for tethering horses.
A stalk or stem of certain species of grain pulse etc. especially of wheat rye oats barley more rarely of buckwheat beans and pease.
A standing without moving forward or backward; a stop; a state or rest.
A starlike body; esp. one of the numerous small planets whose orbits lie between those of Mars and Jupiter; -- called also planetoids and minor planets.

A state in which the thoughts expressions and actions are wild irregular and incoherent; mental aberration; a roving or wandering of the mind -- usually dependent on a fever or some other disease and so distinguished from mania or madness.
A state of agreement; harmony; union.
A state of being acquainted or of having intimate or more than slight or superficial knowledge; personal knowledge gained by intercourse short of that of friendship or intimacy.
A state of being in bad condition and wanting repair.
A state of being turbid or confused; hence intellectual cloudiness or dullness.
A state of difficulty or perplexity; doubt; uncertainty.
A state of holding on in a continuous course; manner of continuity; constant mode; general tendency; course; career.
A state of profound insensibility from which it is difficult or impossible to rouse a person.
A state of terror excited by the sudden appearance of danger; sudden and violent fear usually of short duration; a sudden alarm.
A state or government in which the supreme power is lodged in the hands of a monarch.

A state or place of purification after death; according to the Roman Catholic creed a place or a state believed to exist after death in which the souls of persons are purified by expiating such offenses committed in this life as do not merit eternal damnation or in which they fully satisfy the justice of God for sins that have been forgiven. After this purgation from the impurities of sin the souls are believed to be received into heaven.
A state or quality of lasting or duration; lastingness; continuance.
A state; a body politic consisting of a certain number of men united by compact or tacit agreement under one form of government and system of laws.
A station for rest and entertainment; a place of security and comfort; a refuge; a shelter.
A station.
A steak of beef; a slice of beef broiled or suitable for broiling.
A step or stepping; pressure with the foot; a footstep.
A stick three feet or a yard in length used as a measure of cloth etc.
A stick used as a handle of a broom.
A stick with which a drum is beaten.
A stiff compact pasteboard of various qualities for making cards etc. often having a polished surface.
A stolon.

A stone commonly of a pale to dark green color but sometimes whitish. It is very hard and compact capable of fine polish and is used for ornamental purposes and for implements esp. in Eastern countries and among many early peoples.
A stone at the foot of the slope of a gable the offset of a buttress or the like cut with a sloping surface and with a check to receive the coping stones and retain them in place.
A stone erected over a grave to preserve the memory of the deceased.

A stone imagined by some to be of impenetrable hardness; a name given to the diamond and other substances of extreme hardness; but in modern mineralogy it has no technical signification. It is now a rhetorical or poetical name for the embodiment of impenetrable hardness.
A stone laid over or erected near a grave usually with an inscription to preserve the memory of the dead; a tombstone.
A stone serving the same purpose as a milepost.
A stoppage or irritation of the windpipe producing the feeling of strangulation.
A stopping or standing still of the sun.
A storm accompanied with hail; a shower of hail.
A storm accompanied with lightning and thunder.
A storm characterized by high wind with little or no rain.
A storm with falling snow.
A straight path.
A stranger; an alien.
A strap of leather; especially one used for fastening anything.
A stratagem by which a thing is indirectly brought to pass or by which one thing seems intended and another is done; a trick; an artifice.
A stream of gas or vapor emitting light and heat in the process of combustion; a bright flame.
A stream or river flowing into a larger river or into a lake; a tributary stream.
A string or small rope composed of several strands twisted together.
A string of beads etc. or any continuous band or chain worn around the neck as an ornament.
A stringed instrument of music played with a bow; a violin; a kit.
A stringed instrument of music; a kind of harp much used by the ancients as an accompaniment to poetry.
A stringed musical instrument having a head and neck like the guitar and its body like a tambourine. It has five strings and is played with the fingers and hands.
A strip of tender flesh on either side of the vertebral column under the short ribs in the hind quarter of beef and pork. It consists of the psoas muscles.
A strip of wood or iron fastened on transversely to something in order to give strength prevent warping hold position etc.
A stroke of the tongue in licking.
A stroke; a blow.
A strong buoyant boat especially designed for saving the lives of shipwrecked people.
A strong closely woven linen or cotton fabric of which ticks for beds are made. It is usually twilled and woven in stripes of different colors as white and blue; -- called also ticken.
A strong offensive smell; a disgusting odor; a stench.

A strong alcoholic liquor distilled from wine. The name is also given to spirit distilled from other liquors and in the United States to that distilled from cider and peaches. In northern Europe it is also applied to a spirit obtained from grain.
A strong caustic alkaline solution of potassium salts obtained by leaching wood ashes. It is much used in making soap etc.
A strong current of air; a wind between a stiff breeze and a hurricane. The most violent gales are called tempests.
A strong malt liquor; strong porter.

A strong or fortified place; usually a small fortified place occupied only by troops surrounded with a ditch rampart and parapet or with palisades stockades or other means of defense; a fortification.
A strong pulling or drawing back; withdrawal.
A strong saddle girth as of canvas.
A strong vehicle with low runners or low wheels; or one without wheels or runners made of plank slightly turned up at one end used for transporting loads upon the snow ice or bare ground; a sled.
A strong vessel commonly in form of an inverted bell in which substances are pounded or rubbed with a pestle.
A structure of posts and boards for supporting workmen etc. as in building.
A structure or frame containing parallel or crosed bars with interstices; a kind of latticework such as is used ia the windows of prisons and cloisters.

A structure or platform of timber masonry iron earth or other material built on the shore of a harbor river canal or the like and usually extending from the shore to deep water so that vessels may lie close alongside to receive and discharge cargo passengers
A structure which heavy shot and shell will not penetrate.
A struggle between two persons to see which will throw the other down; a bout at wrestling; a wrestling match; a struggle.
A struggle; a scuffle.
A student of biology; one versed in the science of biology.
A stump or base of a branch that has been lopped off; a short branch or a sharp or rough branch; a knot; a protuberance.
A stupid fellow; a dolt; a person deficient in understanding.
A submarine plant or animal.
A subordinate place of worship
A subordinate; a subaltern.
A substance (usually liquid) suitable for or employed in solution or in dissolving something.

A substance of a reddish brown color and when fresh of the consistence of honey obtained from a bag being behind the navel of the male musk deer. It has a slightly bitter taste but is specially remarkable for its powerful and enduring odor. It is used in medicine as a stimulant antispasmodic. The term is also applied to secretions of various other animals having a similar odor.
A substance or preparation for rendering cloth leather etc. impervious to water.
A substance regarded as an element contained in the atmosphere and remarkable for its chemical inertness.
A substance that may be set on fire or which is liable to take fire and burn.
A substance which cleanses the skin as water or soap; a medicine to cleanse wounds ulcers etc.
A substance which prevents or retards putrefaction or destroys or protects from putrefactive organisms.
A sudden and brief blast or gust; a light temporary breeze.
A sudden and energetic effort as in an emergency; an increased exertion for a brief space.
A sudden and single emission of breath from the mouth; hence any sudden or short blast of wind; a slight gust; a whiff.
A sudden and violent ejection of air with an audible sound chiefly through the nose.
A sudden and violent issue of a fluid from an inclosed plase; an emission of a liquid in a large quantity and with force; the fluid thus emitted; a rapid outpouring of anything.
A sudden causeless change or turn of the mind; a whim of fancy; a capricious prank; a vagary or caprice.
A sudden expulsion of air from the mouth; a quick puff or slight gust as of air or smoke.
A sudden fall; a body of things falling.
A sudden flowing; a rush which fills or overflows as of water for cleansing purposes.
A sudden jerk; a quick throw or cast; a darting motion; hence a jeer.
A sudden motion or shock caused by an unexpected alarm surprise or apprehension of danger.
A sudden shock or jerk; a jolting motion as in a carriage moving over rough ground.
A sudden squall; a violent blast of wind; a sudden and brief rushing or driving of the wind. Snow and hail stormy gust and flaw.
A sudden thrust or pass as with a sword.
A sudden transference of property in land by the death of its owner.
A sudden turn; a starting from the point or line; hence an artful evasion or subterfuge; a shift; a quibble.
A sudden violent gust of wind often attended with rain or snow.
A suffocating smoke.

A suffruticose labiate plant (Salvia officinalis) with grayish green foliage much used in flavoring meats etc. The name is often extended to the whole genus of which many species are cultivated for ornament as the scarlet sage and Mexican red and blue sage.
A suffusion of the cheeks or face with red as from a sense of shame confusion or modesty.
A sum of money payable yearly to continue for a given number of years for life or forever; an annual allowance.

A sum of money to be divided and distributed; the share of a sum divided that falls to each individual; a distribute sum share or percentage; -- applied to the profits as appropriated among shareholders and to assets as apportioned among creditors.
A summary plan or scheme of something proposed affording a prospect of its nature; especially an exposition of the scheme of an unpublished literary work.
A supernatural being often represented as of diminutive size but sometimes as a giant and fabled to inhabit caves hills and like places; a witch.
A surface covered with tiles or composed of tiles.
A surface decoration made by inlaying in patterns small pieces of variously colored glass stone or other material; -- called also mosaic work.
A suspension of arms by agreement of the commanders of opposing forces; a temporary cessation of hostilities for negotiation or other purpose; an armistice.
A swape or sweep.
A swath.
A swaying irregular motion.

A sweet saccharine substance found on the leaves of trees and other plants in small drops like dew. Two substances have been called by this name; one exuded from the plants and the other secreted by certain insects esp. aphids.
A sweet viscid fluid esp. that collected by bees from flowers of plants and deposited in the cells of the honeycomb.
A sweetheart chosen on St. Valentine's Day.
A swell of sudden anger or arrogance; a fit of disappointment and petulance or anger; a rage.
A swelling on the skin; a large ulcerous affection; a boil; an eruptive disease.
A swelling produced by gas or air diffused in the cellular tissue.
A swift sailing boat.
A swinging couch or bed usually made of netting or canvas about six feet wide suspended by clews or cords at the ends.
A sworn statement in writing; a declaration in writing signed and made upon oath before an authorized magistrate.

A symbolical acknowledgment made by a feudal tenant to and in the presence of his lord on receiving investiture of fee or coming to it by succession that he was his man or vassal; profession of fealty to a sovereign.
A system of rules and ceremonies enjoined by law or established by custom in religious worship social intercourse or the courts of princes; outward form.
A table or bench on which meat and other things are dressed or prepared for use.
A table or tray strewn with sand anciently used for drawing calculating etc.
A tailless marsupial (Phascolarctos cinereus) found in Australia. The female carries her young on the back of her neck. Called also Australian bear native bear and native sloth.
A tall pole erected in an open place and wreathed with flowers about which the rustic May-day sports were had.
A tall rushlike plant (Cyperus Papyrus) of the Sedge family formerly growing in Egypt and now found in Abyssinia Syria Sicily etc. The stem is triangular and about an inch thick.
A tang.

A tangent line curve or surface; specifically that portion of the straight line tangent to a curve that is between the point of tangency and a given line the given line being for example the axis of abscissas or a radius of a circle produced.
A taste which remains in the mouth after eating or drinking.
A tattler; a telltale.
A team of horses harnessed one before the other.
A teat pap or nipple; -- formerly that of a human mother now that of a cow or other beast.
A teat.
A tedious journey.
A temporary movable habitation; a large tent; a marquee; esp. a tent raised on posts.
A temporary structure of timber boards etc. for various purposes as for supporting workmen and materials in building for exhibiting a spectacle upon for holding the spectators at a show etc.
A temporary substitute for a bed as one made on the floor or on chairs; -- perhaps originally from the shaking down of straw for this purpose.

A tenet or proposition contrary to received opinion; an assertion or sentiment seemingly contradictory or opposed to common sense; that which in appearance or terms is absurd but yet may be true in fact.
A term applied derisively to any literary or artistic work and esp. a painting done simply for money and the means of living.
A term by which Europeans designate religious temples and tower-like buildings of the Hindoos and Buddhists of India Farther India China and Japan -- usually but not always devoted to idol worship.
A term formerly restricted to mortification of the soft tissues which has not advanced so far as to produce complete loss of vitality; but now applied to mortification of the soft parts in any stage.
A term of contempt for a worthless dissipated fellow.
A term or period of three months.
A textile fabric with a nap or shag on one side longer and softer than the nap of velvet.
A thatched or tiled house or cottage of a single story usually surrounded by a veranda.
A theatrical exhibition; a spectacle.

A theory or system of social reform which contemplates a complete reconstruction of society with a more just and equitable distribution of property and labor. In popular usage the term is often employed to indicate any lawless revolutionary social scheme.
A thick and viscid liquid made from the juice of fruits herbs etc. boiled with sugar.
A thickening of the epidermis at some point esp. on the toes by friction or pressure. It is usually painful and troublesome.
