One who lines as a liner of shoes.
One who lives alone or in solitude; an anchoret; a hermit; a recluse.
One who loads a ship or one who charters and loads a ship.
One who loafs; a lazy lounger.
One who lodges temporarily in a hut or camp.
One who longs for anything.
One who looks.
One who loses.
One who lounges; ar idler.
One who loves his country and zealously supports its authority and interests.
One who loves; one who is in love; -- usually limited in the singular to a person of the male sex.
One who maintains or attends a ferry.
One who makes forms or molds; a manufacturer; specifically the Creator.
One who makes a business of lending money on the security of personal property pledged or deposited in his keeping.
One who makes a deposit especially of money in a bank; -- the correlative of depository.
One who makes a proposal or lays down a proposition.
One who makes an apology; one who speaks or writes in defense of a faith a cause or an institution; especially one who argues in defense of Christianity.
One who makes and tends a garden; a horticulturist.
One who makes ar a trade or business; a mercenary.
One who makes charts or maps.
One who makes cloths; one who dresses or fulls cloth.
One who makes jokes or jests.
One who makes matches for burning or kinding.
One who makes or deals in costumes as for theaters fancy balls etc.
One who makes peace by reconciling parties that are at variance.
One who makes up samples for inspection; one who examines samples or by samples.
One who manages or attends to a press esp. a printing press.
One who manifests an exquisite attention to external appearance; one who is overnice in dress or ornament; a fop; a dandy.
One who meddles; one who interferes or busies himself with things in which he has no concern; an officious person; a busybody.
One who mediates; especially one who interposes between parties at variance for the purpose of reconciling them; hence an intercessor.
One who mends or repairs.
One who milks; also a mechanical apparatus for milking cows.
One who moralizes; one who teaches or animadverts upon the duties of life; a writer of essays intended to correct vice and inculcate moral duties.
One who mourns or is grieved at any misfortune as the death of a friend.
One who narrates; one who relates a series of events or transactions.
One who navigates or sails; esp. one who direct the course of a ship or one who is skillful in the art of navigation; also a book which teaches the art of navigation.
One who negotiates; a person who treats with others either as principal or agent in respect to purchase and sale or public compacts.
One who numbers.
One who objects; one who offers objections to a proposition or measure.
One who observes forms and rules.
One who occupies or takes possession; one who has the actual use or possession or is in possession of a thing.
One who officiously communicates information of the private concerns of others; one who tells that which prudence should suppress.
One who officiously concerns himself with the affairs of others; a meddling person.
One who oppresses; one who imposes unjust burdens on others; one who harasses others with unjust laws or unreasonable severity.
One who or that which amplifies.
One who or that which chases; a pursuer; a driver; a hunter.
One who or that which defends or protects by warding off harm
One who originates.
One who oversees; a superintendent; a supervisor.
One who owes a debt; one who is indebted; -- correlative to creditor.
One who packs boxes.
One who partakes; a sharer; a participator.
One who patrols; a watchman; especially a policeman who patrols a particular precinct of a town or city.
One who pays; specifically the person by whom a bill or note has been or should be paid.
One who peels or strips.
One who performs accomplishes or fulfills.
One who performs massage.
One who persecutes or harasses.
One who pitches anything as hay quoits a ball etc.; specifically (Baseball) the player who delivers the ball to the batsman.
One who plagiarizes; or purloins the words writings or ideas of another and passes them off as his own; a literary thief; a plagiary.
One who plats or braids.

One who plays a part; especially one who for the purpose of winning approbation of favor puts on a fair outside seeming; one who feigns to be other and better than he is; a false pretender to virtue or piety; one who simulates virtue or piety.
One who plays at bowls or who rolls the ball in cricket or any other game.
One who plays golf.
One who plays on a bugle.
One who plays on a fiddle or violin.
One who plays on the organ.
One who pleads; one who argues for or against; an advotate.
One who plots or schemes; a contriver; a conspirator; a schemer.
One who poaches; one who kills or catches game or fish contrary to law.
One who poisons.
One who pokes.
One who possesses exalted rank or holds a position of dignity or honor; especially one who holds an ecclesiastical rank above that of a parochial priest or clergyman.
One who possesses; one who occupies holds owns or controls; one who has actual participation or enjoyment generally of that which is desirable; a proprietor.
One who practices alchemy.
One who practices or exhibits tricks by sleight of hand; one skilled in legerdemain; a conjurer.
One who practices polygamy or maintains its lawfulness.
One who practices robbery on the seas; a pirate.
One who practices rope dancing high vaulting or other daring gymnastic feats.
One who preaches; one who discourses publicly on religious subjects.
One who precedes another in the line of genealogy in any degree but usually in a remote degree; an ancestor.
One who predicts; a foreteller.
One who prepares and sells drugs or compounds for medicinal purposes.
One who prescribes the rules and measures of penance.
One who presents a petition.
One who procures or obtains; one who or that which brings on or causes to be done esp. by corrupt means.
One who professes and practices some liberal art; an artist.
One who professes ignorance or denies that we have any knowledge save of phenomena; one who supports agnosticism neither affirming nor denying the existence of a personal Deity a future life etc.
One who professes the science of law; one versed in the law especially in the civil law; a writer on civil and international law.
One who projects a scheme or design; hence one who forms fanciful or chimerical schemes.

One who pronounces a valedictory address; especially in American colleges the student who pronounces the valedictory of the graduating class at the annual commencement usually the student who ranks first in scholarship.
One who prophesies or foretells events; a predicter; a foreteller.
One who prospects; especially one who explores a region for minerals and precious metals.

One who protests; -- originally applied to those who adhered to Luther and protested against or made a solemn declaration of dissent from a decree of the Emperor Charles V. and the Diet of Spires in 1529 against the Reformers and appealed to a general council; -- now used in a popular sense to designate any Christian who does not belong to the Roman Catholic or the Greek Church.
One who provides furnishes or supplies; one who procures what is wanted.
One who provides gratification for the lust of others; a procurer; a pander.
One who provides victuals or whose business is to make provision for the table; a victualer; a caterer.
One who publishes.
One who puffs; one who praises with noisy or extravagant commendation.
One who punts a football; also one who propels a punt.
One who punts; specifically one who plays against the banker or dealer as in baccara and faro.
One who purchases; one who acquires property for a consideration generally of money; a buyer; a vendee.
One who pursues or chases; one who follows in haste with a view to overtake.
One who pursues the sports of the field; one who hunts fishes etc.
One who puts on roofs.
One who rambles; a rover; a wanderer.
One who ranges; a rover; sometimes one who ranges for plunder; a roving robber.
One who reaps.
One who receives instruction from another; a scholar; a learner; especially a follower who has learned to believe in the truth of the doctrine of his teacher; an adherent in doctrine.
One who records in shorthand what is said or done.
One who records; specifically a person whose official duty it is to make a record of writings or transactions.
One who redeems.
One who reefs; -- a name often given to midshipmen.
One who registers; a recorder; a keeper of records.
One who removes.
One who rents or leases an estate; -- usually said of a lessee or tenant.
One who repents especially one who repents of sin; a penitent.
One who responds. It corresponds in general to defendant.
One who retails anything.
One who retrieves.
One who rides on horseback; a horseman; a rider.
One who rigs or dresses; one whose occupation is to fit the rigging of a ship.
One who rises.
One who rivets.
One who roasts meat.
One who robs on the public road; a highway robber.
One who robs; in law one who feloniously takes goods or money from the person of another by violence or by putting him in fear.
One who rocks; specifically one who rocks a cradle.
One who rows with an oar.
One who rules; one who exercises sway or authority; a governor.
One who satirizes; especially one who writes satire.
One who saves.
One who scatters; esp. one who scatters money; an improvident person.
One who scolds or makes a practice of scolding; esp. a rude clamorous woman; a shrew.
One who scrambles; one who climbs on all fours.
One who scribbles; a petty author; a writer of no reputation; a literary hack.
One who sculptures; one whose occupation is to carve statues or works of sculpture.
One who seals; especially an officer whose duty it is to seal writs or instruments to stamp weights and measures or the like.
One who sees a thing done; one who has ocular view of anything.
One who seizes or grabs.
One who selects.
One who sells anything; one whose occupation is to sell goods or merchandise.
One who sells books.
One who sells.
One who sends goods from one place to another not in the same city or town esp. one who sends goods by water.
One who sends.
One who serves on board of the same ship with another; a fellow sailor.
One who serves.
One who shares; a participator; a partaker; also a divider; a distributer.
One who shaves; one whose occupation is to shave.
One who shoots as an archer or a gunner.
One who shops.
One who shuts or closes.
One who simulates or feigns.
One who sings or plays a solo.
One who sits; esp. one who sits for a portrait or a bust.
One who skates.
One who sketches.
One who slaughters animals or dresses their flesh for market; one whose occupation it is to kill animals for food.
One who sleeps; a slumberer; hence a drone or lazy person.
One who smuggles.
One who snatches or takes abruptly.
One who sneaks.
One who sounds a trumpet.
One who speculates. Specifically: (a) An observer; a contemplator; hence a spy; a watcher.
One who spells.
One who spends money profusely or improvidently; a prodigal; one who lavishes or wastes his estate. Also used figuratively.
One who spends; esp. one who spends lavishly; a prodigal; a spendthrift.
One who spoils; a plunderer; a pillager; a robber; a despoiler.
One who spots.
One who spreads reports or blazes matters abroad.
One who sprinkles.

One who squats; specifically one who settles unlawfully upon land without a title. In the United States and Australia the term is sometimes applied also to a person who settles lawfully upon government land under permission and restrictions before acquiring title.
One who stands near; a spectator; one who has no concern with the business transacting.
One who stays away from business or any duty; especially one who stays out of school without leave; an idler; a loiterer; a shirk.
One who steals anything in a shop or takes goods privately from a shop; one who under pretense of buying goods takes occasion to steal.
One who steals or forcibly carries away a human being; a manstealer.
One who steals purses or other articles from pockets.
One who steals; a thief.
One who steers; the helmsman of a vessel.
One who stickles.
One who stops closes shuts or hinders; that which stops or obstructs; that which closes or fills a vent or hole in a vessel.
One who strains.
One who strolls from place to place; one who has no settled habitation; an idle wanderer; a sturdy beggar; an incorrigible rogue; a vagabond.
One who strolls; a vagrant.
One who studies another's part with a view to assuming it in an emergency.
One who studies the stars; an astronomer.
One who stumps.
One who sues petitions or entreats; a petitioner; an applicant.
One who suffers; one who endures or undergoes suffering; one who sustains inconvenience or loss.
One who supplies.
One who sustains a great burden.
One who swindles or defrauds grossly; one who makes a practice of defrauding others by imposition or deliberate artifice; a cheat.
One who takes or receives; one who catches or apprehends.
One who takes the leading part in a drama; hence one who takes lead in some great scene enterprise conflict or the like.
One who talks; especially one who is noted for his power of conversing readily or agreeably; a conversationist.
One who tames or subdues.
One who tamps; specifically one who prepares for blasting by filling the hole in which the charge is placed.
One who tastes; especially one who first tastes food or drink to ascertain its quality.
One who tattles; an idle talker; one who tells tales.
One who teaches or practices gymnastic exercises; the manager of a gymnasium; an athlete.
One who teases or plagues.
One who teases or vexes.
One who tells relates or communicates; an informer narrator or describer.
One who tells fibs.

One who theoretically rejects every form of religious faith and every kind of religious worship and accepts only the facts and influences which are derived from the present life; also one who believes that education and other matters of civil policy should be managed without the introduction of a religious element.
One who thinks; especially and chiefly one who thinks in a particular manner.
One who thins or makes thinner.
One who throws. Specifically: (a) One who throws or twists silk; a throwster. (b) One who shapes vessels on a throwing engine.
One who tills; a husbandman; a cultivator; a plowman.
One who toasts.
One who toddles; especially a young child.
One who trades; a shopkeeper.
One who traffics or carries on commerce; a trader; a merchant.
One who transacts business for another; an agent.
One who translates; esp. one who renders into another language; one who expresses the sense of words in one language by equivalent words in another.

One who trenches; esp. one who cuts or digs ditches.
One who tricks; a deceiver; a tricker; a cheat.
One who trims arranges fits or ornaments.
One who trips or supplants; also one who walks or trips nimbly; a dancer.
One who trucks; a trafficker.
One who tumbles; one who plays tricks by various motions of the body; an acrobat.
One who tunes; especially one whose occupation is to tune musical instruments.
One who turns; especially one whose occupation is to form articles with a lathe.

One who uses or is skilled in the use of an oar; a rower.

One who violates his allegiance and betrays his country; one guilty of treason; one who in breach of trust delivers his country to an enemy or yields up any fort or place intrusted to his defense or surrenders an army or body of troops to the enemy unless when vanquished; also one who takes arms and levies war against his country; or one who aids an enemy in conquering his country.
One who votes; one who has a legal right to vote or give his suffrage; an elector; a suffragist.
One who vouches or gives witness or full attestation to anything.
One who voyages; one who sails or passes by sea or water.
One who waits in expectation; one held in dependence by hope of receiving some good.
One who walks; a pedestrian.
One who wanders about.
One who wanders from place to place having no fixed dwelling or not abiding in it and usually without the means of honest livelihood; a vagrant; a tramp; hence a worthless person; a rascal.
One who wanders; a rambler; one who roves; hence one who deviates from duty.
One who watches or guards; specifically (Mil.) a soldier set to guard an army camp or other place from surprise to observe the approach of danger and give notice of it; a sentry.
One who watches; one who sits up or continues; a diligent observer; specifically one who attends upon the sick during the night.
One who wears a red coat; specifically a red-coated British soldier.
One who wears or carries as appendant to the body.
One who weaves or whose occupation is to weave.
One who welds or unites pieces of iron etc. by welding.
One who whacks.
One who wheels or turns.
One who whitens or whose occupation is to whiten by bleaching.
One who will never cease to be; one exempt from death decay or annihilation.

One who withdraws or separates himself; especially one who withdraws from a church to which he has belonged; a seceder from an established church; a dissenter; a nonconformist; a schismatic; a sectary.
One who works a gun whether on land or sea; a cannoneer.
One who works in lead; esp. one who furnishes fits and repairs lead iron or glass pipes and other apparatus for the conveyance of water gas or drainage in buildings.
One who works in tin; a tinner.
One who worships false gods; an idolater; a heathen; one who is neither a Christian a Mohammedan nor a Jew.
One who wrestles; one who is skillful in wrestling.
One who writes an account or history of the life of a particular person; a writer of lives as Plutarch.
One who writes and publishes books; especially one who gathers his materials from other books; a compiler.
One who writes in cipher or secret characters.
One who writes; a draughtsman; a writer for another; especially an offical or public writer; an amanuensis or secretary; a notary; a copyist.
One whose business it is to bake bread biscuit etc.
One whose chief interests are in what is to come; one who anxiously eagerly or confidently looks forward to the future; an expectant.
One whose imagination is disturbed; one who sees visions or phantoms.
One whose life or property is insured.
One whose occupation is to assist in navigating ships; a seaman or sailor.
One whose occupation is to bind books.
One whose occupation is to build with bricks.
One whose occupation is to build with stone or brick; also one who prepares stone for building purposes.
One whose occupation is to catch fish.
One whose occupation is to cut out and make men's garments; also one who cuts out and makes ladies' outer garments.
One whose occupation is to dye cloth and the like.
One whose occupation is to full cloth.
One whose occupation is to make and repair watches.
One whose occupation is to make earthen vessels.
One whose occupation is to make or repair small firearms; an armorer.
One whose occupation is to manufacture utensils ornaments etc. of silver; a worker in silver.
One whose occupation is to tan hides or convert them into leather by the use of tan.
One whose occupation it is to make shoes and boots.
One whose occupation it is to shave or trim the beard and to cut and dress the hair of his patrons.
One whose office is to best the drum as in military exercises and marching.
One whose wealth is counted by millions of francs dollars or pounds; a very rich person; a person worth a million or more.
One's acts considered as fixing one's lot in the future existence. (Theos.) The doctrine of fate as the inflexible result of cause and effect; the theory of inevitable consequence.
One's native land; the native land of one's fathers or ancestors.
Open to the view; obvious to the eye; easy to be seen; plainly visible; manifest; attracting the eye.
Open to view; public; apparent; manifest.
Opening in blossoms; flowering.
Openly acknowledged or declared; admitted.
Openly given up to lewdness; devoted to base or infamous purposes.
Openly; evidently.
Operating in any way.
Operating with great effect; effective.
Opposed; opposite; adverse; antagonistic.

Opposite to the northern or arctic pole; relating to the southern pole or to the region near it and applied especially to a circle distant from the pole 23ï¿½ 28/. Thus we say the antarctic pole circle ocean region current etc.
Opposition of action; counteraction or contrariety of things or principles.
Opposition; contrariety.
Oppressive or unreasonably severe in making demands or requiring the exact fulfillment of obligations; harsh; severe.
Orderly arrangement; preparation; provision.
Orderly government; system of order; adminisration.
Organic structure; organization.
Organs that are necessary for life; more especially the heart lungs and brain.
Orig. blithesomeness; gladness; now the highest degree of happiness; blessedness; exalted felicity; heavenly joy.
Originally a bulwark or rampart of fortification or fortified town.

Originally a covered porch with seats at a house door; the Dutch stoep as introduced by the Dutch into New York. Afterward an out-of-door flight of stairs of from seven to fourteen steps with platform and parapets leading to an entrance door some distance above the street; the French perron. Hence any porch platform entrance stairway or small veranda at a house door.
Originally a desk or writing table with drawers for papers.
Originally a nickname for a member of the conservative section of the Democratic party in New York; hence one opposed to progress in general; a fogy.
Originally a painting in colors such as those in mediaeval manuscripts; in modern times any very small painting especially a portrait.
Originally a person put in charge of something especially a chief officer magistrate or keeper as of a county town hundred or castle; one to whom power/ of custody or care are intrusted.
Originally a piece of wood on which notches or scores were cut as the marks of number; later one of two books sheets of paper etc. on which corresponding accounts were kept.

Originally a shield-bearer or armor-bearer an attendant on a knight; in modern times a title of dignity next in degree below knight and above gentleman; also a title of office and courtesy; -- often shortened to squire.

Originally a small sharp-built vessel with two masts and fore-and-aft rig. Sometimes it carried square topsails on one or both masts and was called a topsail schooner. About 1840 longer vessels with three masts fore-and-aft rigged came into use and since that time vessels with four masts and even with six masts so rigged are built. Schooners with more than two masts are designated three-masted schooners four-masted schooners etc.
Originally a swordplayer; hence one who fought with weapons in public either on the occasion of a funeral ceremony or in the arena for public amusement.
Originally an elf's child; a changeling left by fairies or goblins; hence a deformed or foolish child; a simpleton; an idiot.
Originally an officer who had the care of horses; a groom.
Originally the complete dress especially in a military sense of a man or a horse; hence in general armor.
Ornamented with bosses; studded.
Osmose.
Ostensible reason or motive assigned or assumed as a color or cover for the real reason or motive; pretense; disguise.
Ostentatiously fine; showy; gay but tawdry or meretricious.
Otherwise; otherwise called; -- a term used in legal proceedings to connect the different names of any one who has gone by two or more and whose true name is for any cause doubtful.
Out of a straight line; winding; varying from directness.
Out of the natural or usual time; inopportunely; prematurely; unseasonably.
Outcry; clamor.
Outer.
Outward bound.
Over again; another time; in a new form; afresh.
Over and over; -- applied to a style of sewing or to a seam in which two edges usually selvedges are sewed together by passing each stitch over both.
Overcast or obscured with clouds; clouded.
Overcome by some foolish passion or desire; affected by infatuation.
Overcome by strong drink; intoxicated by or as by spirituous liquor; inebriated.
Overcome with grog; tipsy; unsteady on the legs.

Overfullness; especially excessive fullness of the blood vessels; repletion; that state of the blood vessels or of the system when the blood exceeds a healthy standard in quantity; hyperaemia; -- opposed to anaemia.
Overgrown with moss; abounding with or edged with moss.
Overseeing; superintending.
Pain in a tooth or in the teeth; odontalgia.
Paleness; want of color; pallidity.
Paper covered on one side with sand glued fast -- used for smoothing and polishing.
Parched; dried with heat.
Partaking of or exemplifying the characteristics of a statue; having the symmetry or other excellence of a statue artistically made.
Partaking of or of the nature of the crime or suicide.
Partaking of the nature of a bull or a blunder.
Partaking of the qualities of a bear; resembling a bear in temper or manners.
Partaking of the same nature; allied by natural characteristics; kindred; sympathetic.
Parted; disunited; distributed.
Partial or total darkness; thick shade; obscurity.
Parting; valedictory; final.
Partly burned or vitrified coal or other combustible in which fire is extinct.
Passed away; dead; gone.
Passing back; returning.

Passing before the sight or perception or as it were moving over or across a space or scene viewed and then disappearing; hence of short duration; not permanent; not lasting or durable; not stationary; passing; fleeting; brief; transitory.
Passing swiftly away; not durable; transient; transitory.
Passing through the air on wings or by the buoyant force of the atmosphere; flying; having the power to fly.
Passionate ardor in the pursuit of anything; eagerness in favor of a person or cause; ardent and active interest; engagedness; enthusiasm; fervor.
Past; gone by.
Paste of bread; a soft mass of moistened flour or meal kneaded or unkneaded but not yet baked.
Pasteboard for paper boxes; also a pasteboard box.
Paying tribute to another either from compulsion as an acknowledgment of submission or to secure protection or for the purpose of purchasing peace.
Peasants collectively; the body of rustics.
Peevish; irritable; irascible; techy; apt to take fire.
Penitent; sorry for sin.
Perceptible to the touch; tactile; palpable.
Performed with or characterized by art or skill.
Performing or appropriate to the office of a protector.
Performing or ready to perform the duties required by one who has the right to claim submission obedience or deference; submissive to natural or legal superiors; obedient as to parents or superiors.
Perk; pert; jaunty; trim.
Permitting water or other fluid to leak in or out.
Permitting; granting leave or liberty.
Perpendicular; vertical; conforming the direction of a line attached to a plumb.
Personal observation or examination; seeing with one's own eyes; ocular view.
Personally known; familiar.
Pert.
Pert; wanton.
Pertaining or suited to a dictator; absolute.
Pertaining to affected with or of the nature of epilepsy.
Pertaining to coming from or resembling the stars; starry; starlike.
Pertaining to connected with produced by or consisting of molecules.
Pertaining to consisting in or affecting the sense or bodily organs of perception; relating to or concerning the body in distinction from the spirit.
Pertaining to containing or consisting of seed or semen.
pertaining to containing or conveying lymph.
Pertaining to indicating or attended with congestion in some part of the body.
Pertaining to made of or resembling brass.
Pertaining to or abounding with anecdotes.
Pertaining to or affected with or characterized by myopia; nearsighted.
Pertaining to or becoming a feast; festal; joyous; gay; mirthful; sportive.
Pertaining to or being market of staple for commodities.
Pertaining to or caused by ecstasy or excessive emotion; of the nature or in a state of ecstasy.
Pertaining to or characterized by fiction; fictitious; romantic.
Pertaining to or characterized by great fear or funking.
Pertaining to or composed of ashes; filled or strewed with ashes.
Pertaining to or containing doctrine or something taught and to be believed.
Pertaining to or derived from the Bible.
Pertaining to or designed for wear.
Pertaining to or engaged in trade by the piece or large quantity; selling to retailers or jobbers rather than to consumers.
Pertaining to or furnishing a diagnosis; indicating the nature of a disease.
Pertaining to or having the form nature or habits of a beast.
Pertaining to or in the direction of the point between the north and west; being in the northwest; toward the northwest or coming from the northwest.
Pertaining to or in the direction of the southwest; proceeding toward the southwest; coming from the southwest.
Pertaining to or indicating fanaticism; extravagant in opinions; ultra; unreasonable; excessively enthusiastic especially on religious subjects.
Pertaining to or like the spine of a herring; especially characterized by an arrangement of work in rows of parallel lines which in the alternate rows slope in different directions.
Pertaining to or near the horizon.
Pertaining to or of the nature of rhythm
Pertaining to or performed or pronounced at an inauguration.
Pertaining to or proceeding from the heart; warm; cordial; bold; zealous; sincere; willing; also energetic; active; eager.
Pertaining to or resembling a brute or brutes; of a cruel gross and stupid nature; coarse; unfeeling; unintelligent.
Pertaining to or resembling feathers; covered with or as with feathers.
Pertaining to or resembling fluff or nap; soft and downy.
Pertaining to or situated near the anus.
Pertaining to or situated near the back or dorsum of an animal or of one of its parts; notal; tergal; neural.
Pertaining to or situated under the northern constellation called the Bear; northern; frigid.
Pertaining to or suitable for gypsies.
Pertaining to or suiting a scholar a school or schools; scholarlike.
Pertaining to or used in conversation esp. common and familiar conversation; conversational; hence unstudied; informal.
Pertaining to resembling or abounding in ice; cold; frosty.
Pertaining to resembling or hear the heart.
Pertaining to resembling or inhabiting heaven; celestial; not earthly.
Pertaining to suited to or used in devotion.
Pertaining to a commune.
Pertaining to a residue; remaining after a part is taken.
Pertaining to a sect or to sects; peculiar to a sect; bigotedly attached to the tenets and interests of a denomination.
Pertaining to adoption; made or acquired by adoption; fitted to adopt.
Pertaining to an acrobat.
Pertaining to an embryo; rudimentary; undeveloped.
Pertaining to baptism.
Pertaining to chivalry or knight-errantry; warlike; heroic; gallant; high-spirited; high-minded; magnanimous.
Pertaining to clairvoyance; discerning objects while in a mesmeric state which are not present to the senses.
Pertaining to conception.
Pertaining to dew; resembling consisting of or moist with dew.
