The act of secreting or concealing.
The act of securing fastening or tightening with a lace or laces.

The act of seducing; enticement to wrong doing; specifically the offense of inducing a woman to consent to unlawful sexual intercourse by enticements which overcome her scruples; the wrong or crime of persuading a woman to surrender her chastity.
The act of seeing; sight; also that which is beheld.
The act of seizing or the state of being seized; sudden and violent grasp or gripe; a taking into possession.
The act of seizing or taking hold of.
The act of seizing or taking hold of; seizure.

The act of setting apart or assigning to a particular use or person or of taking to one's self in exclusion of all others; application to a special use or purpose as of a piece of ground for a park or of money to carry out some object.
The act of setting free from the power of another from slavery subjection dependence or controlling influence; also the state of being thus set free; liberation.
The act of severing or the state of being severed; partition; separation.
The act of sewing; also the line along which two things or parts are sewed together or are united so as to form a seam or that which resembles a seam.
The act of shampooing.
The act of shaping metal by hammering or pressing.
The act of sharing; community; participation.
The act of shedding separating or casting off or out.
The act of shortening or reducing.
The act of shoving; a forcible push.
The act of shrinking; a contraction into less bulk or measurement.
The act of shuddering as with fear.
The act of shuffling; a mixing confusedly; a slovenly dragging motion.
The act of sipping; the taking of a liquid with the lips.
The act of slipping; also the amount of slipping.
The act of smiting; a blow.
The act of sneering.
The act of sniffing; perception by sniffing; that which is taken by sniffing.
The act of snorting; the sound produced in snorting.
The act of snuffing; perception by snuffing; a sniff.
The act of sobbing; a convulsive sigh or inspiration of the breath as in sorrow.
The act of sorrowing or expressing grief; lamentation; sorrow.
The act of sprinting; a run of a short distance at full speed.
The act of squandering; waste.
The act of standing sitting or walking with the feet far apart.
The act of starving or the state of being starved.
The act of stealing; theft.
The act of stitching or running in patterns as in making a quilt.
The act of stopping or arresting progress motion or action; also the state of being stopped.
The act of straggling.
The act of strengthening supporting or propping with a brace or braces; the state of being braced.
The act of stridding; a long step; the space measured by a long step.
The act of striking or giving blows; punishment or chastisement by blows.
The act of striking the heel of the fore foot with the toe of the hind foot; -- said of horses.
The act of striving; earnest endeavor.
The act of strutting; a pompous step or walk.
The act of stuttering; a stammer.
The act of subjecting or of bringing under the dominion of another; the act of subduing.
The act of submerging or putting under water or other fluid or of causing to be overflowed; the act of plunging under water or of drowning.
The act of summing or forming a sum or total amount; also an aggregate.
The act of summoning; a call by authority or by the command of a superior to appear at a place named or to attend to some duty.
The act of supposing laying down imagining or considering as true or existing what is known not to be true or what is not proved.
The act of suppressing or the state of being suppressed; repression.
The act of surrounding or defending with a bank.
The act of suspending anything; the state of being suspended.
The act of sustaining; support; maintenance; subsistence.
The act of swaying; a swaying motion; the swing or sweep of a weapon.
The act of swelling.
The act of symbolizing or the state of being symbolized.
The act of taking a large mouthful; a swallow or as much as is awallowed at once.
The act of taking feloniously the personal property of another without his consent and knowledge; theft; larceny.
The act of taking from an enemy by way of reteliation or indemnity.
The act of taking or grasping suddenly.
The act of taking or holding possession; possession; occupation.
The act of taking or putting into the stomach.
The act of taking pains; carefulness and fidelity in performance.
The act of talking to one's self; a discourse made by one in solitude to one's self; monologue.
The act of tasking food; the act of consuming or corroding.
The act of telling or relating the particulars of an event; rehearsal; recital.
The act of tempting or enticing to evil; seduction.
The act of that which swells.
The act of throwing or casting; a cast; a pitch.
The act of throwing with force.
The act of thrusting or pushing out; a driving out; expulsion.
The act of touching the football down behind the opponents' goal .
The act of transferring; conveyance; passage; transfer.
The act of transfusing or pouring as liquor out of one vessel into another.
The act of transgressing or of passing over or beyond any law civil or moral; the violation of a law or known principle of rectitude; breach of command; fault; offense; crime; sin.
The act of transmitting money bills or the like esp. to a distant place as in satisfaction of a demand or in discharge of an obligation.
The act of transporting or riding on a sled.
The act of transposing or the state of being transposed.
The act of traveling post.
The act of treading under foot; also the sound produced by trampling.
The act of trimming or removing what is superfluous.
The act of turning aside or state of being turned aside; a turning from a right line or proper course; a bending esp. downward; deviation.
The act of turning aside from any course occupation or object.
The act of turning or whirling as around a fixed center; a circular or spiral motion; motion about an axis; rotation; revolution.
The act of twirling; a rapid circular motion; a whirl or whirling; quick rotation.
The act of twitching; a pull with a jerk; a short sudden quick pull.
The act of undulating; a waving motion or vibration.
The act of uniting in a league; confederation.
The act of upheaving or the state of being upheaved; esp. an elevation of a portion of the earth's crust.
The act of using or adapting as an instrument; a series or combination of instruments; means; agency.
The act of uttering with articulation; the act of giving the proper sound and accent; utterance.
The act of uttering.
The act of valuing or of estimating value or worth; the act of setting a price; estimation; appraisement.

The act of venerating or the state of being venerated; the highest degree of respect and reverence; respect mingled with awe; a feeling or sentimental excited by the dignity wisdom or superiority of a person by sacredness of character by consecration to sacred services or by hallowed associations.
The act of ventilating or the state of being ventilated; the art or process of replacing foul air by that which is pure in any inclosed place as a house a church a mine etc.; free exposure to air.
The act of vibrating or the state of being vibrated or in vibratory motion; quick motion to and fro; oscillation as of a pendulum or musical string.
The act of violently forcing air out through the nasal passages while the cavity of the mouth is shut off from the pharynx by the approximation of the soft palate and the base of the tongue.
The act of visiting or the state of being visited; access for inspection or examination.
The act of wagging; a shake.
The act of waiving or not insisting on some right claim or privilege.
The act of waking or the state or period of being awake.
The act of wavering or of fluttering; flucuation; sudden and brief increase of brightness.
The act of wearing (clothes or ornaments).
The act of willing or choosing; the act of forming a purpose; the exercise of the will.
The act of wrecking or state of being wrecked.
The act or art of coloring; the state of being colored.
The act or art of foretelling the course and termination of a disease; also the outlook afforded by this act of judgment.
The act or art of one who carves.
The act or art of ornamenting or the state of being ornamented.

The act or art of producing upon hard material incised or raised patterns characters lines and the like; especially the art of producing such lines etc. in the surface of metal plates or blocks of wood. Engraving is used for the decoration of the surface itself; also for producing an original from which a pattern or design may be printed on paper.
The act or art of writing in secret characters; also secret characters or cipher.
The act or business of making or marking with letters as by cutting or painting.
The act or crime of a pirate.

The act or employment of grinding or passing through a mill; the process of fulling; the process of making a raised or intented edge upon coin etc.; the process of dressing surfaces of various shapes with rotary cutters.
The act or enlisting or the state of being enlisted; voluntary enrollment to serve as a soldier or a sailor.

The act or habit of arrogating or making undue claims in an overbearing manner; that species of pride which consists in exorbitant claims of rank dignity estimation or power or which exalts the worth or importance of the person to an undue degree; proud contempt of others; lordliness; haughtiness; self-assumption; presumption.
The act or manner of a swaggerer.
The act or manner of expressing in words; style of expression; phrasing.
The act or method of arranging in or by grade or of bringing as the surface of land or a road to the desired level or grade.
The act or method of weaving a cover for a ring rope end etc.
The act or occupation of one who sews.
The act or operation of clipping with shears or a shearing machine as the wool from sheep or the nap from cloth.
The act or operation of eroding or eating away.
The act or operation of giving a brown color as to gun barrels etc.
The act or operation of melting or rendering fluid by heat; the act of melting together.
The act or operation of that which streams; the act of that which sends forth or which runs in streams.
The act or power of recalling past experience; the state of being reminiscent; remembrance; memory.

The act or practice of a hypocrite; a feigning to be what one is not or to feel what one does not feel; a dissimulation or a concealment of one's real character disposition or motives; especially the assuming of false appearance of virtue or religion; a simulation of goodness.

The act or practice of abstaining; voluntary forbearance of any action especially the refraining from an indulgence of appetite or from customary gratifications of animal or sensual propensities. Specifically the practice of abstaining from intoxicating beverages -- called also total abstinence.
The act or practice of alluring or tempting.
The act or practice of flattering; the act of pleasing by artiful commendation or compliments; adulation; false insincere or excessive praise.
The act or practice of making jests; joking; pleasantry.
The act or practice of observing or noticing with attention; a heeding or keeping with care; performance; -- usually with a sense of strictness and fidelity.
The act or practice of one who is hospitable; reception and entertainment of strangers or guests without reward or with kind and generous liberality.
The act or practice of one who mimics; ludicrous imitation for sport or ridicule.
The act or practice of persecuting; especially the infliction of loss pain or death for adherence to a particular creed or mode of worship.
The act or practice of plagiarizing.
The act or practice of planting or setting in the earth for growth.
The act or practice of prostituting or offering the body to an indiscriminate intercourse with men; common lewdness of a woman.
The act or practice of recording anything by marks figures or characters.
The act or practice of rowing or sailing esp. as an amusement; carriage in boats.
The act or practice of trafficking by exchange of commodities; an exchange of goods.

The act or process by which living tissues or cells take up and convert into their own proper substance the nutritive material brought to them by the blood or by which they transform their cell protoplasm into simpler substances which are fitted either for excretion or for some special purpose as in the manufacture of the digestive ferments. Hence metabolism may be either constructive (anabolism) or destructive (katabolism).
The act or process by which anything is seasoned.
The act or process of absorbing or sucking in anything or of being absorbed and made to disappear.
The act or process of augmenting or making larger by addition expansion or dilation; increase.
The act or process of beating bruising or pounding; the state of being beaten or bruised.
The act or process of coercing.
The act or process of compiling or gathering together from various sources.
The act or process of computing; calculation; reckoning.
The act or process of conquering or acquiring by force; the act of overcoming or subduing opposition by force whether physical or moral; subjection; subjugation; victory.
The act or process of converting metal into money.
The act or process of conveying or transmitting.
The act or process of cooking in an oven or of drying and hardening by heat or cold.
The act or process of digesting; reduction to order; classification; thoughtful consideration.
The act or process of dividing into segments; specifically (Biol.) a self-division into segments as a result of growth; cell cleavage; cell multiplication; endogenous cell formation.

The act or process of evicting; or state of being evicted; the recovery of lands tenements etc. from another's possession by due course of law; dispossession by paramount title or claim of such title; ejectment; ouster.
The act or process of exhaling or sending forth in the form of steam or vapor; evaporation.
The act or process of filtering; the mechanical separation of a liquid from the undissolved particles floating in it.
The act or process of generating or bearing.
The act or process of haggling.
The act or process of handling or touching with the fingers.
The act or process of holding fast; that which serves to hold fast; a grip; a grasp; a clamp; a holdfast.
The act or process of implantating.
The act or process of inclosing in or covering with a case or thin substance as plaster boards etc.
The act or process of increasing; growth in bulk guantity number value or amount; augmentation; enlargement.
The act or process of inducting or bringing in; introduction; entrance; beginning; commencement.
The act or process of inferring by deduction or induction.
The act or process of inscribing.
The act or process of irrigating or the state of being irrigated; especially the operation of causing water to flow over lands for nourishing plants.
The act or process of laying a pavement or covering some place with a pavement.
The act or process of litigating; a suit at law; a judicial contest.
The act or process of making a pad or of inserting stuffing.
The act or process of making clear.
The act or process of making fixed.
The act or process of making nets or network or of forming meshes as for fancywork fishing nets etc.
The act or process of making or becoming white.
The act or process of making the grooves in a rifled cannon or gun barrel.
The act or process of multiplying or of increasing in number; the state of being multiplied.
The act or process of one who or that which binds.
The act or process of oxidizing or the state or result of being oxidized.
The act or process of perspiring.
The act or process of portraying; description; delineation.
The act or process of preparing liquors which are brewed as beer and ale.
The act or process of raising a nap as on cloth.
The act or process of reclaiming.

The act or process of refuting or disproving or the state of being refuted; proof of falsehood or error; the overthrowing of an argument opinion testimony doctrine or theory by argument or countervailing proof.
The act or process of relaxing or the state of being relaxed.
The act or process of rendering impervious to sound as a floor or wall; also the material with which the spaces are filled in this process; pugging.
The act or process of renovating; the state of being renovated or renewed.

The act or process of resolving the constituent parts of a compound body or substance into its elementary parts; separation into constituent part; analysis; the decay or dissolution consequent on the removal or alteration of some of the ingredients of a compound; disintegration.
The act or process of scattering or dispersing or the state of being scattered or separated.
The act or process of shipping.
The act or process of smoothing as clothes with hot flatirons.
The act or process of sucking; the act of drawing as fluids by exhausting the air.
The act or process of swindling; a cheat.
The act or process of transcribing or copying.
The act or process of using formulas sung or spoken with occult ceremonies for the purpose of raising spirits producing enchantment or affecting other magical results; enchantment.
The act or process of vegetating or growing as a plant does; vegetable growth.
The act or process of voiding urine; micturition.
The act or process of waning or decreasing.
The act or process of washing ores in a buddle.
The act or result of dispersing or scattering; dispersion.
The act or result of spraining; lameness caused by spraining.
The act or solemnity of crowning a sovereign; the act of investing a prince with the insignia of royalty on his succeeding to the sovereignty.
The act or state of bending downward; inclination.
The act or state of declining or sinking.
The act or state of inheriting.
The act or state of one who or that which heads; formation of a head.
The act or state of quivering; a tremor.
The act or state of separation into branches; division into branches; a division or branch.
The act or state of sticking together; close union.
The act or state of sustaining grasping or retaining.
The act or state of that which curls.
The act or the place of excavating.
The act or the power of foreseeing; prescience; foreknowledge.
The act or the result of betraying.
The act or the state of fitting badly.
The act or the state of going out.
The act or the state of intermitting; the state of being neglected or disused; disuse; discontinuance.
The act retrieving.
The action of a lever; mechanical advantage gained by the lever.
The action of causing to drop or of letting drop; falling.
The action of sticking; the state of being attached; intimate union.
The action or effect of corrosive agents or the process of corrosive change.
The acts arts or boastful pretensions of a quack; false pretensions to any art; empiricism.
The addition to the human body of some artificial part to replace one that is wanting as a log or an eye; -- called also prothesis.
The adult male of the red deer (Cervus elaphus) a large European species closely related to the American elk or wapiti.
The aforesaid thing; the same (as before). Often contracted to do. or to two turned commas () or small marks. Used in bills books of account tables of names etc. to save repetition.
The agency for another who acts through the agent; authority to act for another esp. to vote in a legislative or corporate capacity.
The agency of a cause; the action or power of a cause in producing its effect.
The American great marbled godwit (Limosa fedoa). Applied also to the red-breasted godwit (Limosa haematica).
The American reindeer especially the common or woodland species (Rangifer Caribou).
The American wood rabbit (Lepus sylvaticus); -- also called Molly cottontail.
The amphitheater of Vespasian at Rome the largest in the world.
The angel fish (Squatina angelus).
The angle formed by the parting of two legs or branches; a fork; the point where a trunk divides.
The anguish like gnawing pain excited by a sense of guilt; compunction of conscience for a crime committed or for the sins of one's past life.
The animals of any given area or epoch.
The answer of a god or some person reputed to be a god to an inquiry respecting some affair or future event as the success of an enterprise or battle.
The apartments or portion of the house allotted to females in Mohammedan families.
The application of the healing art to mental diseases.
The arched middle portion of the human foot next in front of the ankle joint.
The arched part of a structure.
The arctic circle.
The aromatic and edible spindle-shaped root of the cultivated form of the Pastinaca sativa a biennial umbelliferous plant which is very poisonous in its wild state; also the plant itself.
The art and practice of conducting negotiations between nations (particularly in securing treaties) including the methods and forms usually employed.
The art of building with bricks or of uniting them by cement or mortar into various forms; the act or occupation of laying bricks.
The art of calculating by nine figures and zero.
The art of casting and working in lead and applying it to building purposes; especially the business of furnishing fitting and repairing pipes for conducting water sewage etc.
The art of cutting framing and joining timber as in the construction of buildings.
The art of dissecting or artificially separating the different parts of any organized body to discover their situation structure and economy; dissection.
The art of dressing up; artifice; stratagem; fraud; imposture.
The art of forming or of cultivating forests; the management of growing timber.
The art of healing diseases; the science of medicine; the theory or practice of medicine.
The art of inducing an extraordinary or abnormal state of the nervous system in which the actor claims to control the actions and communicate directly with the mind of the recipient.
The art of making fireworks; the manufacture and use of fireworks; pyrotechny.
The art of making things of baked clay.
The art of occupation of laying out and cultivating gardens; horticulture.
The art of preparing preserving and mounting the skins of animals so as to represent their natural appearance as for cabinets.
The art of revealing future events by means of a pretended communication with the dead; the black art; hence magic in general; conjuration; enchantment.
The art of training by athletic exercises; the games and sports of athletes.
The art of training falcons or hawks to pursue and attack wild fowl or game.
The art or business of forming charts or maps.
The art or occupation of a mason.
The art or practice of attack and defense with the sword esp. with the smallsword.

The art or practice of preparing and preserving drugs and of compounding and dispensing medicines according to prescriptions of physicians; the occupation of an apothecary or a pharmaceutical chemist.
The art or process of converting skins into leather.

The art or process of covering anything with a plate or plates or with metal particularly of overlaying a base or dull metal with a thin plate of precious or bright metal as by mechanical means or by electro-magnetic deposition.
The art or profession of a dentist; dental surgery.
The art or science of flying.
The art or science of good eating; epicurism; the art of good cheer.
The art or trade of a jeweler.
The articles or goods supplied by upholsterers; the business or work of an upholsterer.
The articles usually sold by stationers as paper pens ink quills blank books etc.
The attribute or quality of being cruel; a disposition to give unnecessary pain or suffering to others; inhumanity; barbarity.
The aurochs or European bison.
The author of a dramatic composition; a writer of plays.
The back or top of the back; a crest.
The back and sides of a pig salted and smoked; formerly the flesh of a pig salted or fresh.
The back of a horse.
The back part of the neck.
The back part of the neck; the scruff.
The bag or pouch which contains the testicles; the cod.
The ball or globe of the eye.
The band of the sleeve of a shirt or other garment which covers the wrist.
The band which encompasses the waist; esp. one on the upper part of breeches trousers pantaloons skirts or the like.
The bank of a river.
The bare end of the nose between the nostrils; -- used esp. of ruminants.
The base or foot of a column statue vase lamp or the like; the part on which an upright work stands. It consists of three parts the base the die or dado and the cornice or surbase molding.
The basinlike opening or mouth of a volcano through which the chief eruption comes; similarly the mouth of a geyser about which a cone of silica is often built up.
The basis or foundation of a thing; especially a horizontal piece as a timber which forms the lower member of a frame or supports a structure.
The bed or stratum of earth which lies immediately beneath the surface soil.
The bed in which a person dies; hence the closing hours of life of one who dies by sickness or the like; the last sickness.

The belly or that part of the body between the thorax and the pelvis. Also the cavity of the belly which is lined by the peritoneum and contains the stomach bowels and other viscera. In man often restricted to the part between the diaphragm and the commencement of the pelvis the remainder being called the pelvic cavity.
The belly; the abdomen.

The berry of several species of Vaccinium an ericaceous genus differing from the American huckleberries in containing numerous minute seeds instead of ten nutlets. The commonest species are V. Pennsylvanicum and V. vacillans. V. corymbosum is the tall blueberry.

The berry of the pimento (Eugenia pimenta) a tree of the West Indies; a spice of a mildly pungent taste and agreeably aromatic; Jamaica pepper; pimento. It has been supposed to combine the flavor of cinnamon nutmegs and cloves; and hence the name. The name is also given to other aromatic shrubs.
The berry or fruit of any tree of the genus Morus; also the tree itself.
The bilge or protuberant part of a cask.
The bill or nib of a bird consisting of a horny sheath covering the jaws. The form varied much according to the food and habits of the bird and is largely used in the classification of birds.
The bitter alkaline viscid fluid found in the gall bladder beneath the liver. It consists of the secretion of the liver or bile mixed with that of the mucous membrane of the gall bladder.
The bittern.
The black howler of Central America (Mycetes villosus).
The black tern.
The blood necessary to life; vital blood.
The blubber of whales or other marine mammals; also the fat of the hippopotamus.
The blue-winged snow goose.
The board used in the game of chess having eight rows of alternate light and dark squares eight in each row.
The body of a ship or decked vessel of any kind; esp. the body of an old vessel laid by as unfit for service.
The body of men set apart by due ordination to the service of God in the Christian church in distinction from the laity; in England usually restricted to the ministers of the Established Church.
The bone of either jaw; a maxilla or a mandible.
The bone of the brachium or upper part of the arm or fore limb.
The bone of the breast; the sternum.
The bony and cartilaginous framework which supports the soft parts of a vertebrate animal.
The border edge or margin of a thing usually of something circular or curving.
The brain and spinal cord; the cerebro-spinal axis; myelencephalon.
The branch of science which treats of the nervous system.
The breaking in pieces or shattering of a ship or other vessel by being cast ashore or driven against rocks shoals etc. by the violence of the winds and waves.
The breast of a human being; the part between the arms to which anything is pressed when embraced by them.
The broken coat of the seed of wheat rye or other cereal grain separated from the flour or meal by sifting or bolting; the coarse chaffy part of ground grain.
The brow or hairy arch above the eye.
The bubbles caused in fluids or liquors by fermentation or agitation; spume; foam; esp. a spume of saliva caused by disease or nervous excitement.
The building and apparatus for refining or purifying esp. metals and sugar.
The building and works where distilling esp. of alcoholic liquors is carried on.
The burden of a song; a phrase or verse which recurs at the end of each of the separate stanzas or divisions of a poetic composition.
The burning or discoloration produced on the skin by the heat of the sun; tan.
The bush or shrub which bears roses.
The business of a bank or of a banker.
The business of a butcher.
The business of a cutler.
The business of a hosier.
The business of conveying goods on trucks.
The business of cutting or getting timber or logs from the forest for lumber.
The business of felling trees cutting them into logs and transporting the logs to sawmills or to market.
The business or employment of a broker.
The business or practice of catching fish; fishing.
The buttock.
The calcined ashes of seaweed -- formerly much used in the manufacture of glass now used in the manufacture of iodine.
The call of a hen to her chickens.
The canal by which the urine is conducted from the bladder and discharged.
The case in which a dead human body is inclosed for burial.
The case in which the blade of a sword dagger etc. is kept; a sheath.
The catch in a gunlock by which the hammer is held cocked or half cocked.
The cause of continued pain of body or mind as sickness losses etc.; an instance of grievous distress; a pain or grief.
The celebration of the hundredth anniversary of any event; a centenary.
The central or topmost stone of an arch. This in some styles is made different in size from the other voussoirs or projects or is decorated with carving.
The central part usually cylindrical of a wheel; the nave.
The ceremony or the state of marriage; matrimony.
The channel of a stream.
The character dignity or condition of a knight or of knights as a class; hence chivalry.
The character or practices o/ wizards; sorcery; magic.
The cheek; the jaw.
The chemical basis of ordinary connective tissue as of tendons or sinews and of bone. On being boiled in water it becomes gelatin or glue.
The chemistry of living organisms; the chemistry of the processes incidental to and characteristic of life.
The chief ecclesiastic in a national church; one who presides over other bishops in a province; an archbishop.
The chief officer of a regiment; an officer ranking next above a lieutenant colonel and next below a brigadier general.
The chief officer of a shire or county to whom is intrusted the execution of the laws the serving of judicial writs and processes and the preservation of the peace.
The chuck or call of a hen.
The circuit or extent of a bishop's jurisdiction; the district in which a bishop exercises his ecclesiastical authority.
The claw of a predaceous bird or animal especially the claw of a bird of prey.
The close of the day.
The closing of a factory or workshop by an employer usually in order to bring the workmen to satisfactory terms by a suspension of wages.
The clothes tents utensils and provisions of an army.
The clothing (esp. an outer wooden covering) as of a steam cylinder applied to prevent the radiation of heat; a covering of lags; -- called also deading and cleading.
The coagulated or thickened part of milk as distinguished from the whey or watery part. It is eaten as food especially when made into cheese.
The coarse harsh sound uttered by a frog or a raven or a like sound.
The coarse and broken part of flax or hemp separated from the finer part by the hatchel or swingle.
The coast of the sea; the land that lies adjacent to the sea or ocean.
The cob or axis on which the kernels of Indian corn grow.

The collar bone which is joined at one end to the scapula or shoulder blade and at the other to the sternum or breastbone. In man each clavicle is shaped like the letter / and is situated just above the first rib on either side of the neck. In birds the two clavicles are united ventrally forming the merrythought or wishbone.
The collection of attributes which make up the nature of a god; divinity; godhead.
The column of bones in the back which sustains and gives firmness to the frame; the spine; the vertebral or spinal column.
The coming into life or into the world; birth; also the circumstances attending birth as time place manner etc.
The common European cuttlefish.
The common guillemot.
The common people; the vulgar; the multitude -- comprehending all persons not distinguished by rank office education or profession.
The common title of civility in France in speaking to or of a man; Mr. or Sir.
The condition of a martyr; the death of a martyr; the suffering of death on account of adherence to the Christian faith or to any cause.
The condition of a nation or government which refrains from taking part directly or indirectly in a war between other powers.
The condition of being amazed; bewilderment [Obs.]; overwhelming wonder as from surprise sudden fear horror or admiration.
The condition of being barren; sterility; unproductiveness.
The condition of being exact; accuracy; nicety; precision; regularity.
The condition of being festive; social joy or exhilaration of spirits at an entertaintment; joyfulness; gayety.

The condition of being insolvent; the state or condition of a person who is insolvent; the condition of one who is unable to pay his debts as they fall due or in the usual course of trade and business.
The condition of being lonely; solitude; seclusion.
The condition of being mad; insanity; lunacy.
The condition of being naked.
The condition of being numb; that state of a living body in which it loses wholly or in part the power of feeling or motion.
The condition of being out of favor; loss of favor regard or respect.
The condition of being pure.
The condition of being stagnant; cessation of flowing or circulation as of a fluid; the state of being motionless.
The condition of enjoying anything; pleasure or satisfaction as in the possession or occupancy of anything; possession and use.
The condition or quality of being an idiot; absence or marked deficiency of sense and intelligence.
The condition or quality of being formal strictly ceremonious precise etc.
The condition or quality of being fragile; brittleness; frangibility.
The condition or quality of being idle (in the various senses of that word); uselessness; fruitlessness; triviality; inactivity; laziness.
The condition or quality of being imminent; a threatening as of something about to happen. The imminence of any danger or distress.
The condition or quality of being immobile; fixedness in place or state.
The condition or quality of being impure in any sense; defilement; foulness; adulteration.
The condition or quality of being insecure; want of safety; danger; hazard.
The condition or quality of being lame.
The condition or quality of being mortal; subjection to death or to the necessity of dying.
The condition or quality of being narrow.
The condition or quality of being quick or living; life.
The condition or quality of being regular.
The condition or quality of being sane; soundness of health of body or mind especially of the mind; saneness.
The condition quality of being frail physically mentally or morally frailness; infirmity; weakness of resolution; liableness to be deceived or seduced.
The conductir of a mule team; also a head shepherd.
The conductor of a musical band.
The contents of a sewer or drain; refuse liquids or matter carried off by sewers
The Cornus a genus of large shrubs or small trees the wood of which is exceedingly hard and serviceable for many purposes.
The country of one's ancestors; -- same as fatherland.
The cover of the eye; that portion of movable skin with which an animal covers or uncovers the eyeball at pleasure.
The creation of an artifical flood by the sudden letting in of a body of water; -- called also flushing.
The crime of cohabitation or sexual commerce between persons related within the degrees wherein marriage is prohibited by law.
The croup.
The crown of a king.
The cry of a horse; a whinny.
The cry of a wild goose.
The cry of a young chicken; a chirp.
The cry of the duck or a sound in imitation of it; a hoarse quacking noise.
The cultivation of a garden or orchard; the art of cultivating gardens or orchards.
The current of a stream.
The current that sets seaward near the bottom when waves are breaking upon the shore.
The curve which a body describes in space as a planet or comet in its orbit or stone thrown upward obliquely in the air.

The Cynara scolymus a plant somewhat resembling a thistle with a dilated imbricated and prickly involucre. The head (to which the name is also applied) is composed of numerous oval scales inclosing the florets sitting on a broad receptacle which with the fleshy base of the scales is much esteemed as an article of food.
The daughter of one's son or daughter.
The dead grass that remains on mowing land in winter and spring.
The decrease of the illuminated part of the moon to the eye of a spectator.
The deep threatening sound made by a surly dog; a grumbling sound.
The degree title or rank of a doctor.
The delicate membrane by which the back part of the globe of the eye is lined and in which the fibers of the optic nerve terminate.
The dense tissues which invest the teeth and cover the adjacent parts of the jaws.
The descent of a deity to earth and his incarnation as a man or an animal; -- chiefly associated with the incarnations of Vishnu.
The description of a particular place town manor parish or tract of land; especially the exact and scientific delineation and description in minute detail of any place or region.
The destruction or injury of a vessel by being cast on shore or on rocks or by being disabled or sunk by the force of winds or waves; shipwreck.
The dialect or dialects of English spoken by the people of Scotland.
The difference of the results obtained by observation and by computation from a formula.

The dignity and authority of sovereign power; quality or state which inspires awe or reverence; grandeur; exalted dignity whether proceeding from rank character or bearing; imposing loftiness; stateliness; -- usually applied to the rank and dignity of sovereigns.
The disbelief or denial of the existence of a God or supreme intelligent Being.
The disposal or relative arrangement of figures or objects as in drawing painting and sculpture or in ornamental design.
The disposition and tendency to preserve what is established; opposition to change; the habit of mind; or conduct of a conservative.
The disposition to do good; good will; charitableness; love of mankind accompanied with a desire to promote their happiness.
The disposition to favor and promote the interest of one person or family or of one class of men to the neglect of others having equal claims; partiality.

The distance through which one part of connected machinery as a wheel piston or screw can be moved without moving the connected parts resulting from looseness in fitting or from wear; also the jarring or reflex motion caused in badly fitting machinery by irregularities in velocity or a reverse of motion.
The district or territory of a town.
The doctrine of certain extreme adherents or disciples of Descartes and Johann Gottlieb Fichte which finds all the elements of knowledge in the ego and the relations which it implies or provides for.
The doctrine of terms; a theory of terms or appellations; a treatise on terms.
The doctrine of the Cynics; the quality of being cynical; the mental state opinions or conduct of a cynic; morose and contemptuous views and opinions.
The doctrine or practice of anarchists.
The doctrine or science of musical sounds.
The doctrine or science of sounds; especially those of the human voice; phonology.
The doctrine that all things are subject to fate or that they take place by inevitable necessity.
The drink of the gods (as ambrosia was their food); hence any delicious or inspiring beverage.
The duck mole.
The dung of birds.
The ear or its lobe.
The earliest age at which persons are capable of begetting or bearing children usually considered in temperate climates to be about fourteen years in males and twelve in females.
The East Indian name of the chick-pea (Cicer arietinum) and its seeds; also other similar seeds there used for food.
The edge margin or border of a steep place as of a precipice; a bank or edge as of a river or pit; a verge; a border.
The edges or lower borders of the roof of a building which overhang the walls and cast off the water that falls on the roof.
The edible fleshy roundish or somewhat conical root of a cruciferous plant (Brassica campestris var. Napus); also the plant itself.

The edible black or dark blue fruit of several species of the American genus Gaylussacia shrubs nearly related to the blueberries (Vaccinium) and formerly confused with them. The commonest huckelberry comes from G. resinosa.
The edible drupaceous fruit of the Prunus domestica and of several other species of Prunus; also the tree itself usually called plum tree.
The edible nut of a forest tree (Castanea vesca) of Europe and America. Commonly two or more of the nuts grow in a prickly bur.
The eighth day after a church festival the festival day being included; also the week following a church festival.
The end or tip of the toe.
The end of the backbone of an animal with the parts adjacent; the buttock or buttocks.
The endeavor to equal or to excel another in qualities or actions; an assiduous striving to equal or excel another; rivalry.
The English form of the Spanish word Caï¿½on.
The entire body or all.
The entire clothing of a bird.
The entire coat of wood that covers a sheep or other similar animal; also the quantity shorn from a sheep or animal at one time.
The entire horn or any branch of the horn of a cervine animal as of a stag.
The essential part of a seed; all that is within the seed walls; the edible substance contained in the shell of a nut; hence anything included in a shell husk or integument.
The European flounder.
The European widgeon.
The excrement of an animal.

The expanded upper end of the windpipe or trachea connected with the hyoid bone or cartilage. It contains the vocal cords which produce the voice by their vibrations when they are stretched and a current of air passes between them. The larynx is connected with the pharynx by an opening the glottis which in mammals is protected by a lidlike epiglottis.
The expected king and deliverer of the Hebrews; the Savior; Christ.
The expressed juice of apples. It is used as a beverage for making vinegar and for other purposes.
The expressed juice of the grape or other fruit before fermentation.
The external covering or coat as of flesh fruit trees etc.; skin; hide; bark; peel; shell.
The external covering or envelope of certain fruits or seeds; glume; hull; rind; in the United States especially applied to the covering of the ears of maize.
The external parts of the female genital organs; sometimes the opening between the projecting parts of the external organs.
The extraneous matter or impurities which rise to the surface of liquids in boiling or fermentation or which form on the surface by other means; also the scoria of metals in a molten state; dross.
The extreme part; the utmost limit; the farthest or remotest point or part.
The eyepiece of an optical instrument as of a telescope or microscope.
The faculty of acquiring wisdom by observation and experience or the wisdom so acquired; -- opposed to inwit.

The father and ruler of a family; one who governs his family or descendants by paternal right; -- usually applied to heads of families in ancient history especially in Biblical and Jewish history to those who lived before the time of Moses.
The feeling excited by that which is unworthy base or disgraceful; anger mingled with contempt disgust or abhorrence.
The female of the domestic fowl; also the female of grouse pheasants or any kind of birds.
The female of the red deer of which the male is the stag.
The female of the tiger.
The females of the human race; women collectively.
The feudal system; a system by which the holding of estates in land is made dependent upon an obligation to render military service to the kind or feudal superior; feudal principles and usages.
The figure statue or bust on the prow of a ship.

The figure of a star thus / used in printing and writing as a reference to a passage or note in the margin to supply the omission of letters or words or to mark a word or phrase as having a special character.
The finest of wool separated from the rest; combed wool; also fine yarn of wool.
The finger next to the thumb; the index.
The finish around a fireplace covering the chimney-breast in front and sometimes on both sides; especially a shelf above the fireplace and its supports.
The first antiphon of the vespers for the dead.
The first letter in the Greek alphabet answering to A and hence used to denote the beginning.
The first month after marriage.
The first or chief man
The first rudiments of an organism whether animal or plant
The flap or latchet of a shoe fastened with a string or a buckle.
The flesh of a calf when killed and used for food.
The flesh of swine fresh or salted used for food.
The fleshy or muscular part of the side of an animal between the ribs and the hip.
The fleshy pome or fruit of a rosaceous tree (Pyrus communis) cultivated in many varieties in temperate climates; also the tree which bears this fruit.
The fling of a horse or ordinary kicking back of his heels; a gambol.

The flour of a hard and small-grained wheat made into dough and forced through small cylinders or pipes till it takes a slender wormlike form whence the Italian name. When the paste is made in larger tubes it is called macaroni.
The flower of a plant or the essential organs of reproduction with their appendages; florescence; bloom; the flowers of a plant collectively.
The flower of a rose before it opens or when but partially open.

The foam or troth (top yeast) or the sediment (bottom yeast) of beer or other in fermentation which contains the yeast plant or its spores and under certain conditions produces fermentation in saccharine or farinaceous substances; a preparation used for raising dough for bread or cakes and making it light and puffy; barm; ferment.
The fold of skin which covers the glans of the penis; the prepuce.
The foot of a quadruped having claws as the lion dog cat etc.
The footless larva of any fly.
The forests or partly cleared grounds on the frontiers.
The forked bone in front of the breastbone in birds; -- called also merrythought and wishing bone.

The forms required by good breeding or prescribed by authority to be observed in social or official life; observance of the proprieties of rank and occasion; conventional decorum; ceremonial code of polite society.
The fourth part of a bushel; a dry measure of eight quarts.
The fourth part; a quarter; hence a region of the earth.
The fourth part; the quarter.
The fourth stomach of a ruminant; rennet.
The freezing or effect of a freezing of some part of the body as the ears or nose.
The French middle class particularly such as are concerned in or dependent on trade.
The fretting or dimpling of the surface as of running water; little curling waves.
The fringe of hair that edges the eyelid; -- usually in the pl.
The front compartment of a French diligence; also the front compartment (usually for three persons) of a car or carriage on British railways.
The front of a building; esp. the principal front having some architectural pretensions. Thus a church is said to have its facade unfinished though the interior may be in use.
The front of that part of the head which incloses the brain; that part of the face above the eyes; the brow.
The front part of an edifice or lot; extent of front.
The front; hence that which is in front; the future.
The fruit of a trailing leguminous plant (Arachis hypogaea); also the plant itself which is widely cultivated for its fruit.

The fruit of a tree (Artocarpus incisa) found in the islands of the Pacific esp. the South Sea islands. It is of a roundish form from four to six or seven inches in diameter and when baked somewhat resembles bread and is eaten as food whence the name.

The fruit of several species of bramble (Rubus); also the plant itself. Rubus fruticosus is the blackberry of England; R. villosus and R. Canadensis are the high blackberry and low blackberry of the United States. There are also other kinds.
The fruit of the almond tree.

The fruit of the mango tree. It is rather larger than an apple and of an ovoid shape. Some varieties are fleshy and luscious and others tough and tasting of turpentine. The green fruit is pickled for market.
The fruit of the oak being an oval nut growing in a woody cup or cupule.
The fruit of the oak and beech or other forest trees; nuts; acorns.

The fruit of the tree Punica Granatum; also the tree itself which is native in the Orient but is successfully cultivated in many warm countries and as a house plant in colder climates. The fruit is as large as an orange and has a hard rind containing many rather large seeds each one separately covered with crimson acid pulp.
The fruit or nut of any tree of the genus Juglans; also the tree and its timber. The seven or eight known species are all natives of the north temperate zone.
The garden of Eden in which Adam and Eve were placed after their creation.

The general and popular term for a firm upright insulated support for a superstructure; a pier column or post; also a column or shaft not supporting a superstructure as one erected for a monument or an ornament.
The giving of evidence on the part of a plaintiff to destroy the effect of evidence introduced by the defendant in the same suit.
The glandular organ in which milk is secreted and stored; -- popularly called the bag in cows and other quadrupeds.
The glede or kite.
The god of war and husbandry.
The goddess of retribution or vengeance; hence retributive justice personified; divine vengeance.
The goddess of the rainbow and swift-footed messenger of the gods.

The government or authority of a tyrant; a country governed by an absolute ruler; hence arbitrary or despotic exercise of power; exercise of power over subjects and others with a rigor not authorized by law or justice or not requisite for the purposes of government.
The governor of a country or province who rules in the name of the sovereign with regal authority as the king's substitute.
The grain left after harvest or gleaning; also nuts which have fallen to the ground.
The great artery which carries the blood from the heart to all parts of the body except the lungs; the main trunk of the arterial system.
The great extensor muscle of the knee divided above into four parts which unite in a single tendon at the knee.
The great hall or council chamber of demons or evil spirits.
The Grecian Archipelago or Aegean Sea separating Greece from Asia Minor. It is studded with a vast number of small islands.
The Greek letter / / or / (English S or s). It originally had the form of the English C.
The gross amount; the mass; the lump.
The ground adjoining a church in which the dead are buried; a cemetery.
The habit or act of lisping.
The hair that grows on the chin lips and adjacent parts of the human face chiefly of male adults.
The half of a circle; the part of a circle bounded by its diameter and half of its circumference.
The half-wild horse of the plains in Mexico California etc. It is small hardy and easily sustained.
The hand with the fingers doubled into the palm; the closed hand especially as clinched tightly for the purpose of striking a blow.

The hard white opaque fine-grained substance constituting the tusks of the elephant. It is a variety of dentine characterized by the minuteness and close arrangement of the tubes as also by their double flexure. It is used in manufacturing articles of ornament or utility.
The hard external coat or covering of anything; the hard exterior surface or outer shell; an incrustation.
The hard parts or skeleton of various Anthozoa and of a few Hydrozoa. Similar structures are also formed by some Bryozoa.
The having of a plurality of wives or husbands at the same time; usually the marriage of a man to more than one woman or the practice of having several wives at the same time; -- opposed to monogamy.
The head gear with which a horse is governed and restrained consisting of a headstall a bit and reins with other appendages.
The head of an Arab family or of a clan or a tribe; also the chief magistrate of an Arab village. The name is also applied to Mohammedan ecclesiastics of a high grade.
The head of an arrow.
The heat or utmost violence of an onset; the strength or greatest fury of any contention.
The helm or tiller of a vessel or boat; also the rudder.
The hide of a cow.
The hide or skin of a calf; or leather made of the skin.
The highest of the four principal parts in music; the part usually sung by boys or women; soprano.
The highest or chief.
The highest or covering course of masonry in a wall often with sloping edges to carry off water; -- sometimes called capping.
The highest order of mammals. It includes man together with the apes and monkeys. Cf. Pitheci.

The highly perfumed yellowish heartwood of an East Indian and Polynesian tree (Santalum album) and of several other trees of the same genus as the Hawaiian Santalum Freycinetianum and S. pyrularium the Australian S. latifolium etc. The name is extended to several other kinds of fragrant wood.
The hinder part posteriors or rump of a person or animal.
The hip; the projecting region of the lateral parts of the pelvis and the hip joint; the hind part.
The hole or loop in which a button is caught.
The hollow beneath the junction of the arm and shoulder; the axilla.
The home place; a home and the inclosure or ground immediately connected with it.
The hook on the end of an eccentric rod opposite the strap.
The hook with its eye or the joint on which a door gate lid etc. turns or swings; a flexible piece as a strip of leather which serves as a joint to turn on.
The horn of plenty from which fruits and flowers are represented as issuing. It is an emblem of abundance.
The horny substance or case that covers or terminates the feet of certain animals as horses oxen etc.
The human body as distinguished from the head and limbs; in sculpture the trunk of a statue mutilated of head and limbs.
The human race; man taken collectively.
The husband of one's mother by a subsequent marriage.
The hypothetical radical C2H3 regarded as the characteristic residue of ethylene and that related series of unsaturated hydrocarbons with which the allyl compounds are homologous.

The image likeness or representation of a person whether a full figure or a part; an imitative figure; -- commonly applied to sculptured likenesses as those on monuments or to those of the heads of princes on coins and medals sometimes applied to portraits.
The imaginary great circle on the earth's surface everywhere equally distant from the two poles and dividing the earth's surface into two hemispheres.
The imaginary land or abode of fairies.
The immersion of the body in water.
The imperative mood; also a verb in the imperative mood.
The imperfect tense; or the form of a verb denoting the imperfect tense.
The impression of the foot; a trace or footmark.
The income of a prince or a state; revenue; exhequer.
The increasing moon; the moon in her first quarter or when defined by a concave and a convex edge; also applied improperly to the old or decreasing moon in a like state.
The indicative mood.
The inmeats or edible viscera (heart gizzard liver etc.) of poultry.
The inner or preaxial and usually the larger of the two bones of the leg or hind limb below the knee.
The inner bark of the shoots of Cinnamomum Zeylanicum a tree growing in Ceylon. It is aromatic of a moderately pungent taste and is one of the best cordial carminative and restorative spices.
The inspissated juice of the Papaver somniferum or white poppy.
The interior or central region of a country; -- usually in the plural.
The internal parts of animal bodies; the bowels; the guts; viscera; intestines.
The itch.
The Jews'quarter in an Italian town or city.
The joint next above the hock and near the flank in the hind leg of the horse and allied animals; the joint corresponding to the knee in man; -- called also stifle joint.
The joint of a finger particularly when made prominent by the closing of the fingers.
The journey of a pilgrim; a long journey; especially a journey to a shrine or other sacred place. Fig. the journey of human life.
The juice of plants of any kind especially the ascending and descending juices or circulating fluid essential to nutrition.
The juice or other liquid matter that drips from flesh in cooking made into a dressing for the food when served up.
The juicy fruit of certain cucurbitaceous plants as the muskmelon watermelon and citron melon; also the plant that produces the fruit.
The jurisdiction of a patriarch; patriarchship.
The keeper of a jail or prison.
The kernel of the fruit of the nutmeg tree (Myristica fragrans) a native of the Molucca Islands but cultivated elsewhere in the tropics.
The killer; the man appointed to kill the bull in bullfights.
The killing of one human being by another.
The kitchen or cooking department.
The knave of trumps at gleek.
The kneepan.
The land belonging to a lord or nobleman or so much land as a lord or great personage kept in his own hands for the use and subsistence of his family.
The land bordering on or adjacent to the sea; the seashore. Also used adjectively.
The lapwing; the wipe; -- so called from its cry.
The large lobe of the hind brain in front of and above the medulla; the little brain. It controls combined muscular action.
The large stomach of ruminating animals when prepared for food.
The larva of an insect especially of a beetle; -- called also grubworm.
The larva of any one of numerous species of bombycid moths which spins a large amount of strong silk in constructing its cocoon before changing to a pupa.

The larval state of a butterfly or any lepidopterous insect; sometimes but less commonly the larval state of other insects as the sawflies which are also called false caterpillars. The true caterpillars have three pairs of true legs and several pairs of abdominal fleshy legs (prolegs) armed with hooks. Some are hairy others naked. They usually feed on leaves fruit and succulent vegetables being often very destructive Many of them are popularly called worms as the cutworm
The lash of a whip -- usually made of thongs of leather or of cords braided or twisted.
The last letter of the Greek alphabet.
The lateral movement of a ship to the leeward of her course; drift.
The leader of a circle of dancers; hence the leader of a number of persons acting together; the leader of a herd of animals.
The lens or combination of lenses at the eye end of a telescope or other optical instrument through which the image formed by the mirror or object glass is viewed.
The letters of a language arranged in the customary order; the series of letters or signs which form the elements of written language.
The light given by the stars.
The light of a candle.
The light of day as opposed to the darkness of night; the light of the sun as opposed to that of the moon or to artificial light.
The light of the moon.
The light of the moon.
The light of the sun or the place where it shines; the direct rays of the sun the place where they fall or the warmth and light which they give.
The light of the sun.

The light perceived before the rising and after the setting of the sun or when the sun is less than 18? below the horizon occasioned by the illumination of the earth's atmosphere by the direct rays of the sun and their reflection on the earth.
The light yielded by the combustion of illuminating gas.
The limit or exterior line encompassing a place; a boundary; a confine; limit of jurisdiction or authority; -- often in the plural.
The line that goes round or encompasses a circular figure; a periphery.

The loadstone; a species of iron ore (the ferrosoferric or magnetic ore Fe3O4) which has the property of attracting iron and some of its ores and when freely suspended of pointing to the poles; -- called also natural magnet.
The lock of hair that grows from the forepart of the head.
The long projecting nose of a beast as of swine.

The long round slender rod or pin in spinning wheels by which the thread is twisted and on which when twisted it is wound; also the pin on which the bobbin is held in a spinning machine or in the shuttle of a loom.
The long and heavy hair growing on the upper side of or about the neck of some quadrupedal animals as the horse the lion etc.
The loose black particles collected from combustion as on pots and kettles or in a chimney; soot; smut; also coloring matter which rubs off from cloth.

The loose outer garment worn by the ancient Romans consisting of a single broad piece of woolen cloth of a shape approaching a semicircle. It was of undyed wool except the border of the toga praetexta.
The lord or officer who defended the marches or borders of a territory.
The low murmuring sound made by a cat; pur.
The lower extremity of the face below the mouth; the point of the under jaw.
The lower of inferior world; the world which is under the heavens; the earth.
The lower or lowest side of anything.
The lower part of the body behind; the buttocks.
The lowing of a cow.
The lucern (Medicago sativa); -- so called in California Texas etc.
The luminous point or object from which light emanates; also a body radiating light brightly.
The machinery of a clock or machinery resembling that of a clock; machinery which produces regularity of movement.
The maiming of a person by depriving him of the use of any of his members which are necessary for defense or protection.
The making of small sharp cracks or reports frequently repeated.
The male ass; a donkey.
The male fecundating fluid; semen.
The male member or organ of generation.
The male of any pheasant of the genus Pavo of which at least two species are known native of Southern Asia and the East Indies.
The male of any species of cattle (Bovidae); hence the male of any large quadruped as the elephant; also the male of the whale.
The male of any species of goose.
The male of bees esp. of the honeybee. It gathers no honey.
The male of birds particularly of gallinaceous or domestic fowls.
The male of the domestic fowl; a cock.
The male of the duck kind.
The male of the sheep and allied animals. In some parts of England a ram is called a tup.
The male of the sparrow hawk.
The malicious burning of a dwelling house or outhouse of another man which by the common law is felony; the malicious and voluntary firing of a building or ship.
The man at the helm; a steersman.
The man who presides over and teaches a school; a male teacher of a school.
The manner in which one bears or conducts one's self; mien; behavior; carriage.
The mark or stamp of a post office on a letter giving the place and date of mailing or of arrival.
The mark aimed at in curling and in quoits.
The mark of the foot left on the earth; a track or footstep; a trace; a sign; hence a faint mark or visible sign left by something which is lost or has perished or is no longer present; remains.
The mark or impression of the foot; a track; hence visible sign of a course pursued; token; mark.
The mark or symptom by which one disease is known or distinguished from others.
The marking of the clothes with stripes or horizontal bands.
The marking or numbering of the pages of a book.
The mass of the people as distinguished from the titled classes or nobility; the commonalty; the common people.
The material of which belts for machinery are made; also belts taken collectively.
The matter which subsides to the bottom frrom water or any other liquid; settlings; lees; dregs.

The melted rock ejected by a volcano from its top or fissured sides. It flows out in streams sometimes miles in length. It also issues from fissures in the earth's surface and forms beds covering many square miles as in the Northwestern United States.

The melting of ice snow or other congealed matter; the resolution of ice or the like into the state of a fluid; liquefaction by heat of anything congealed by frost; also a warmth of weather sufficient to melt that which is congealed.
The middle of summer.
The middle of the way or distance; a middle way or course.
The middle of the week. Also used adjectively.
The middle part of the day; noon.
The milk that remains after the butter is separated from the cream.

The Milky Way; that luminous tract or belt which is seen at night stretching across the heavens and which is composed of innumerable stars so distant and blended as to be distinguishable only with the telescope. The term has recently been used for remote clusters of stars.
The mixture formed by brewing; that which is brewed.

The moral condition or the condition in other respects so far as it is affected by or dependent upon moral considerations such as zeal spirit hope and confidence; mental state as of a body of men an army and the like.
The morning star; Phosphor.
The most beautiful and beloved of the gods; the god of peace; the son of Odin and Freya.
The most that can be; the farthest limit; the greatest power degree or effort.
The mother and ruler of a family or of her descendants; a ruler by maternal right.
The mother city; the chief city of a kingdom state or country.
The mouth; hence idle prate; chatter; unmeaning talk; loquaciousness.
The name of several aromatic labiate plants mostly of the genus Mentha yielding odoriferous essential oils by distillation.
The name of several cereal and forage grasses which bear an abundance of small roundish grains. The common millets of Germany and Southern Europe are Panicum miliaceum and Setaria Italica.
The name of several cruciferous plants of the genus Brassica (formerly Sinapis) as white mustard (B. alba) black mustard (B. Nigra) wild mustard or charlock (B. Sinapistrum).
The name of several evergreen trees. The wood is remarkable for its durability and fragrant odor.
The name of several large perennial herbs of the genus Rheum and order Polygonaceae.
The name of several poisonous umbelliferous herbs having finely cut leaves and small white flowers as the Cicuta maculata bulbifera and virosa and the Conium maculatum.
The name of various instruments for passing along mucous canals esp. applied to a tubular instrument to be introduced into the bladder through the urethra to draw off the urine.
The narrow edge of a hammer head.
The natural color of flesh; rosy pink.
The natural constitution or physical structure of a person.
The natural height of an animal body; -- generally used of the human body.
