The reversal of what has been done.
The ridge between the shoulder bones of a horse at the base of the neck.

The right line drawn through the two points of contact of the two tangents drawn from a given point to a given conic section. The given point is called the pole of the line. If the given point lies within the curve so that the two tangents become imaginary there is still a real polar line which does not meet the curve but which possesses other properties of the polar. Thus the focus and directrix are pole and polar. There are also poles and polar curves to curves of higher degree than the second and poles and polar planes to surfaces of the second degree.
The rim border or upper edge of a cup dish or any hollow vessel used for holding anything.
The ringing of an evening bell originally a signal to the inhabitants to cover fires extinguish lights and retire to rest -- instituted by William the Conqueror; also the bell itself.
The rising light of the morning; the dawn of day; the redness of the sky just before the sun rises.
The rock dove.
The rod used in ramming home the charge in a muzzle-loading firearm.
The roes of the sturgeon prepared and salted; -- used as a relish esp. in Russia.
The roof of the mouth.
The rorqual.
The sale of commodities in small quantities or parcels; -- opposed to wholesale; sometimes the sale of commodities at second hand.
The scab or itch in cattle dogs and other beasts.
The scale.
The scarfskin or epidermis.
The scaup duck.

The science and art of disposing military and naval forces in order for battle and performing military and naval evolutions. It is divided into grand tactics or the tactics of battles and elementary tactics or the tactics of instruction.
The science of civil government.
The science of earthquakes.

The science of human duty; the body of rules of duty drawn from this science; a particular system of principles and rules concerting duty whether true or false; rules of practice in respect to a single class of human actions.
The science of sounds teaching their nature phenomena and laws.
The science of the structure and functions of the human body.

The science of the world or universe; or a treatise relating to the structure and parts of the system of creation the elements of bodies the modifications of material things the laws of motion and the order and course of nature.
The science or art of hurling missile weapons by the use of an engine.
The science which has to do with the collection and classification of certain facts respecting the condition of the people in a state.
The science which treats of diseases their nature causes progress symptoms etc.
The science which treats of measuring time by regular divisions or periods and which assigns to events or transactions their proper dates.
The science which treats of minerals and teaches how to describe distinguish and classify them.
The science which treats of myths; a treatise on myths.
The science which treats of poisons their effects antidotes and recognition; also a discourse or treatise on the science.
The science which treats of the atmosphere and its phenomena particularly of its variations of heat and moisture of its winds storms etc.
The science which treats of the phenomena of living organisms; the study of the processes incidental to and characteristic of life.

The science which treats of the principles of language; the study of forms of speech and their relations to one another; the art concerned with the right use aud application of the rules of a language in speaking or writing.
The science which treats of the skin its structure functions and diseases.

The science which treats: (a) Of the structure and mineral constitution of the globe; structural geology. (b) Of its history as regards rocks minerals rivers valleys mountains climates life etc.; historical geology. (c) Of the causes and methods by which its structure features changes and conditions have been produced; dynamical geology.
The Scotch shepherd dog. There are two breeds the rough-haired and smooth-haired. It is remarkable for its intelligence displayed especially in caring for flocks.
The scroll termination of any architectural member as of a step etc.
The seashore; seacoast.
The season of spring; springtide.
The second or true muscular stomach of birds in which the food is crushed and ground after being softened in the glandular stomach (crop) or lower part of the esophagus; the gigerium.
The secretion from the salivary glands.
The seed of plants.
The seeds of flax from which linseed oil is obtained.
The sense of touch; feeling.
The sense or act of feeling; touch.
The sentiment of attachment to a federal union especially to the federal union of the United States.
The serum or watery part of milk separated from the more thick or coagulable part esp. in the process of making cheese.
The set of apartments within which the cardinals of the Roman Catholic Church are continuously secluded while engaged in choosing a pope.
The setting of the sun; sunset.
The shafts or thills of a wagon or carriage.
The sharp broken noise made by a goose or by a hen that has laid an egg.
The shedding or spilling of blood; slaughter; the act of shedding human blood or taking life as in war riot or murder.
The shell or exterior covering of an egg. Also used figuratively for anything resembling an eggshell.
The shell or hard external covering in which the kernel of a nut is inclosed.
The shoot of a plant; a shoot from the seed from the stump or from the root or tuber of a plant or tree; more rarely a shoot from the stem of a plant or the end of a branch.
The shore or border of the land adjacent to the sea or ocean. Also used adjectively.
The short loud explosive sound uttered by a dog; a similar sound made by some other animals.
The show of an intention to inflict evil; a threat or threatening; indication of a probable evil or catastrophe to come.
The shutting up of a place by troops or ships with the purpose of preventing ingress or egress or the reception of supplies.
The side of a bed.
The side of a ship above the water line from the bow to the quarter.
The side of the way; the edge or border of a road or path.
The side or bank of a river.
The side or declivity of a hill.
The sin or crime of violating or profaning sacred things; the alienating to laymen or to common purposes what has been appropriated or consecrated to religious persons or uses.
The sixth part of a circle.
The skill of a good seaman; the art or skill in the art of working a ship.
The skin of a bear.
The skin of a beast with the hair on; a raw or undressed hide; a skin preserved with the hairy or woolly covering on it.
The skin of a buck.
The skin of a goat or leather made from it.
The skin of a lamb sheep goat young calf or other animal prepared for writing on.
The skin of a pig -- used chiefly for making saddles; hence a colloquial or slang term for a saddle.
The skin of a sheep; or leather prepared from it.
The skull of an animal; especially that part of the skull either cartilaginous or bony which immediately incloses the brain; the brain case or brainpan.
The slaying of a human being; destruction of men.
The slender smooth stem of an arrow; hence an arrow.
The slender styles of the pistillate flowers of maize; also called silk.
The sliding weight on a steelyard.
The slipping down of a mass of land from a mountain hill etc.
The slope or angle to which the cutting edge of a tool as a plane is ground.
The small troublesome tumors or swellings about the anus and lower part of the rectum which are technically called hemorrhoids.
The smallest firearm used intended to be fired from one hand -- now of many patterns and bearing a great variety of names.
The smooth and level extent of ice marked off for the game of curling.
The snout of a swine.
The sordid friar bird of Australia (Tropidorhynchus sordidus).
The sound made by a bullet in striking a solid object or in passing through the air.
The sound made by the sudden fall or blow of a heavy body as of a hammer or the like.
The sound of a beaten drum; drum music.
The sound of roaring.
The sound produced by anything that creaks; a creaking.
The sound which follows a flash of lightning; the report of a discharge of atmospheric electricity.
The southern regions or countries; the south.
The sovereign or supreme monarch of an empire; -- a title of dignity superior to that of king.
The space between the eye and bill in birds and the corresponding region in reptiles and fishes.
The space of fourteen days; two weeks.
The spirit or conduct of the Vandals; ferocious cruelty; hostility to the arts and literature or willful destruction or defacement of their monuments.
The spotted deer (Cervus axis or Axis maculata) of India where it is called hog deer and parrah (Moorish name).

The standard unit in the measure of electrical resistance being the resistance of a circuit in which a potential difference of one volt produces a current of one ampere. As defined by the International Electrical Congress in 1893 and by United States Statute it is a resistance substantially equal to 109 units of resistance of the C.G.S. system of electro-magnetic units and is represented by the resistance offered to an unvarying electric current by a column of mercury at the temperature of melting ice 14.4521 grams in mass of a constant cross-sectional area and of the length of 106.3 centimeters. As thus defined it is called the international ohm.
The state condition or quality of being great.
The state condition or quality of being late.
The state condition or quality of being light or not heavy; buoyancy; levity; fickleness; nimbleness; delicacy; grace.
The state condition or quality of being loose.
The state office or dignity of a king; royalty.
The state or condition of belonging to a definite place or of being contained within definite limits.
The state or quality of being legitimate or in conformity with law; hence the condition of having been lawfully begotten or born in wedlock.
The state quality or relation of being objective; character of the object or of the objective.
The state behind or past.
The state of a parent; the office or character of a parent.
The state of any compound substance which results from the mixture of various ingredients; due mixture of different qualities; just combination.
The state of being a boy; the time during which one is a boy.
The state of being a captive or a prisoner.
The state of being a father; the character or authority of a father; paternity.
The state of being a mother; the character or office of a mother.
The state of being a mother; the character or relation of a mother.
The state of being a saint; the condition of a saint.
The state of being a widow; the time during which a woman is widow; also rarely the state of being a widower.
The state of being a woman; the distinguishing character or qualities of a woman or of womankind.
The state of being abrupt or broken; craggedness; ruggedness; steepness.
The state of being actual; reality.
The state of being actually or legally bankrupt.
The state of being affected with psora.
The state of being an accomplice; participation in guilt.
The state of being an orphan; orphanhood; orphans collectively.
The state of being bad.

The state of being beside one's self or rapt out of one's self; a state in which the mind is elevated above the reach of ordinary impressions as when under the influence of overpowering emotion; an extraordinary elevation of the spirit as when the soul unconscious of sensible objects is supposed to contemplate heavenly mysteries.
The state of being blank.
The state of being bored or pestered; a state of ennui.
The state of being bound; condition of being under restraint; restraint of personal liberty by compulsion; involuntary servitude; slavery; captivity.
The state of being broken down or weakened.
The state of being brothers or a brother.
The state of being carnal; fleshly lust or the indulgence of lust; grossness of mind.
The state of being chaste; purity of body; freedom from unlawful sexual intercourse.
The state of being close.
The state of being cloudy.
The state of being competent; fitness; ability; adequacy; power.
The state of being complex; complexity.
the state of being continuous; uninterupted connection or succession; close union of parts; cohesion.
The state of being cool; a moderate degree of cold; a moderate degree or a want of passion; want of ardor zeal or affection; calmness.
The state of being damned; condemnation; openly expressed disapprobation.
The state of being dazed.
The state of being deformed; want of proper form or symmetry; any unnatural form or shape; distortion; irregularity of shape or features; ugliness.
The state of being depraved or corrupted; a vitiated state of moral character; general badness of character; wickedness of mind or heart; absence of religious feeling and principle.
The state of being divine; the nature or essence of God; deity; godhead.
The state of being dry.
The state of being dull; slowness; stupidity; heaviness; drowsiness; bluntness; obtuseness; dimness; want of luster; want of vividness or of brightness.
The state of being empty; absence of contents; void space; vacuum.
The state of being entire; completeness.
The state of being exuberant; an overflowing quantity; a copious or excessive production or supply; superabundance; richness.
The state of being faint; loss of strength or of consciousness and self-control.
The state of being fatal or proceeding from destiny; invincible necessity superior to and independent of free and rational control.
The state of being filthy.
The state of being final finished or complete; a final or conclusive arrangement; a settlement.
The state of being foolish; want of good sense; levity weakness or derangement of mind.
The state of being fresh.
The state of being full or of abounding; abundance; completeness.
The state of being general; the quality of including species or particulars.
The state of being grateful; warm and friendly feeling toward a benefactor; kindness awakened by a favor received; thankfulness.
The state of being happy; blessedness; blissfulness; enjoyment of good.
The state of being high; elevation; loftiness.
The state of being illegitimate.
The state of being illiterate or uneducated; want of learning or knowledge; ignorance; specifically inability to read and write.
The state of being impaired; injury.
The state of being insane; unsoundness or derangement of mind; madness; lunacy.
The state of being intimate; close familiarity or association; nearness in friendship.
The state of being itchy.
The state of being liable.
The state of being man as a human being or man as distinguished from a child or a woman.
The state of being monstrous or out of the common order of nature; that which is monstrous; a monster.
The state of being much known and talked of; exalted reputation derived from the extensive praise of great achievements or accomplishments; fame; celebrity; -- always in a good sense.
The state of being one; singleness in number; individuality; unity.
The state of being opaque; the quality of a body which renders it impervious to the rays of light; want of transparency; opaqueness.
The state of being pagan; pagan characteristics; esp. the worship of idols or false gods or the system of religious opinions and worship maintained by pagans; heathenism.
The state of being pleasing; a suiting.
The state of being plural or consisting of more than one; a number consisting of two or more of the same kind.
The state of being pure (in any sense of the adjective).
The state of being puzzled; perplexity.
The state of being queasy; nausea; qualmishness; squeamishness.
The state of being relative.
The state of being royal; the condition or quality of a royal person; kingship; kingly office; sovereignty.
The state of being savage; savageness; savagism.
The state of being supreme or in the highest station of power; highest or supreme authority or power.
The state of being sure; certainty; security.
The state of being the same; identity; absence of difference; near resemblance; correspondence; similarity.
The state of being unmarried; single life esp. that of a bachelor or of one bound by vows not to marry.
The state of burning.
The state of desponding; loss of hope and cessation of effort; discouragement; depression or dejection of the mind.
The state of mind of a bigot; obstinate and unreasoning attachment of one's own belief and opinions with narrow-minded intolerance of beliefs opposed to them.
The state of quality of being calm; quietness; tranquillity; self-repose.
The state of voluntary or compulsory subjection to a master; the condition of being bound to service; the condition of a slave; slavery; bondage; hence a state of slavish dependence.
The state or act of one who sits; the posture of one who occupies a seat.
The state or condition of being a lord; hence (with his or your) a title applied to a lord (except an archbishop or duke who is called Grace) or a judge (in Great Britain) etc.
The state or condition of being bald.
The state or condition of being delicate; agreeableness to the senses; delightfulness.
The state or condition of being easy; freedom from distress; rest.
The state or period of being an infant; the first part of life; early childhood.
The state or period of infancy.
The state or quality of being adequate proportionate or sufficient; a sufficiency for a particular purpose.
The state or quality of being arid or without moisture; dryness.
The state or quality of being bestial.
The state or quality of being big; largeness; size; bulk.
The state or quality of being bland.
The state or quality of being bold.
The state or quality of being clean.
The state or quality of being cold.
The state or quality of being constant or steadfast; freedom from change; stability; fixedness; immutability.
The state or quality of being crisp.
The state or quality of being deep profound mysterious secretive etc.; depth; profundity; -- opposed to shallowness.

The state or quality of being durable; the power of uninterrupted or long continuance in any condition; the power of resisting agents or influences which tend to cause changes decay or dissolution; lastingness.
The state or quality of being eager; ardent desire.
The state or quality of being fertile or fruitful; fruitfulness; productiveness; fecundity; richness; abundance of resources; fertile invention; quickness; readiness.
The state or quality of being firm.
The state or quality of being fraternal or brotherly; brotherhood.
The state or quality of being grand; vastness; greatness; splendor; magnificence; stateliness; sublimity; dignity; elevation of thought or expression; nobility of action.
The state or quality of being gross; thickness; corpulence; coarseness; shamefulness.
The state or quality of being heavy in its various senses; weight; sadness; sluggishness; oppression; thickness.
The state or quality of being hidden.
The state or quality of being holy; perfect moral integrity or purity; freedom from sin; sanctity; innocence.

The state or quality of being humble; freedom from pride and arrogance; lowliness of mind; a modest estimate of one's own worth; a sense of one's own unworthiness through imperfection and sinfulness; self-abasement; humbleness.
The state or quality of being immature or not fully developed; unripeness; incompleteness.
The state or quality of being immense; inlimited or immeasurable extension; infinity; vastness in extent or bulk; greatness.
The state or quality of being immoral; vice.
The state or quality of being inactive; inertness.
The state or quality of being innocent; freedom from that which is harmful or infurious; harmlessness.
The state or quality of being intricate or entangled; perplexity; involution; complication; complexity; that which is intricate or involved.
The state or quality of being kind in any of its various senses; manifestation of kind feeling or disposition beneficence.
The state or quality of being latent.
The state or quality of being lazy.
The state or quality of being legal; conformity to law.
The state or quality of being like; similitude; resemblance; similarity.
The state or quality of being liquid.
The state or quality of being little.
The state or quality of being lovely.
The state or quality of being malignant; extreme malevolence; bitter enmity; malice.
The state or quality of being mature; ripeness; full development.
The state or quality of being near; -- used in the various senses of the adjective.
The state or quality of being neat.
The state or quality of being needy; want; poverty; indigence.
The state or quality of being neutral; the condition of being unengaged in contests between others; state of taking no part on either side; indifference.
The state or quality of being ready; preparation; promptness; aptitude; willingness.
The state or quality of being ripe; maturity;; completeness; perfection.
The state or quality of being sacred or holy; holiness; saintliness; moral purity; godliness.
The state or quality of exceeding a measure or rule or of being immoderate monstrous or outrageous.
The state or relation of being a sister; the office or duty of a sister.
The state or relation of being or associate.
The stay extending from the foot of the foremast to the maintop.
The steam let out of a cylinder after it has done its work there.
The stem or body of a tree apart from its limbs and roots; the main stem without the branches; stock; stalk.
The stem or main axis of a plant.
The stock or handle of anything.
The stomach.
The stone or plank forming a step before an outer door.
The string of a musical instrument.
The stump of a tree; that part of a tree or plant which remains fixed in the earth when the stem is cut down; -- applied especially to the stump of a small tree or shrub.
The stumps of wheat rye barley oats or buckwheat left in the ground; the part of the stalk left by the scythe or sickle.

The substance which constitutes the essential part of the solid framework of plants of ordinary wood linen paper etc. It is also found to a slight extent in certain animals as the tunicates. It is a carbohydrate (C6H10O5)n isomeric with starch and is convertible into starches and sugars by the action of heat and acids. When pure it is a white amorphous mass.
The summit of an eminence.
The superior or presiding bishop of a country or province.
The surf duck.

The sweetbread a gland connected with the intestine of nearly all vertebrates. It is usually elongated and light-colored and its secretion called the pancreatic juice is discharged often together with the bile into the upper part of the intestines and is a powerful aid in digestion.
The swell of the sea which breaks upon the shore esp. upon a sloping beach.
The sympathetic affection of one mind by the thoughts feelings or emotions of another at a distance without communication through the ordinary channels of sensation.
The syntactical or structural form peculiar to any language; the genius or cast of a language.
The tail of a pig.
The tender branches or twigs of trees and shrubs fit for the food of cattle and other animals; green food.
The terminal part of the large intestine; -- so named because supposed by the old anatomists to be straight.
The territory jurisdiction or dignity of an elector as in the old German empire.
The theory or method of suggesting an effect or impression without elaboration of the details; -- a disignation of a recent fashion in painting and etching.

The thick brown or dark colored viscid uncrystallizable sirup which drains from sugar in the process of manufacture; any thick viscid sweet sirup made from vegetable juice or sap as of the sorghum or maple.
The thigh bone.
The thimble-shaped fruit of the Rubus Idaeus and other similar brambles.
The third letter (/ / = Eng. G) of the Greek alphabet.
The thong or braided cord of a whip with which the blow is given.
The threads that cross the warp in a woven fabric; the weft; the filling; the thread usually carried by the shuttle in weaving.
The threads which are extended lengthwise in the loom and crossed by the woof.
The throat; the gullet; the canal by which food passes to the stomach.
The throwing overboard of goods from necessity in order to lighten a vessel in danger of wreck.
The tie or obligation implied or expressed which a subject owes to his sovereign or government; the duty of fidelity to one's king government or state.
The time during which there is daylight as distinguished from the night.
The time from dusk to dawn; -- opposed to daytime.
The time of the first appearance of light in the morning.
The time of triumph and exultation; hence joy high spirits frolicsomeness; wildness.
The time to go to bed.
The time when the sun enters one of the equinoctial points that is about March 21 and September 22.
The tip top point or angular summit of anything.
The tissue which fills the cavities of most bones; the medulla. In the larger cavities it is commonly very fatty but in the smaller cavities it is much less fatty and red or reddish in color.
The title by which the shogun or former commander in chief of the Japanese army was known to foreigners.
The tonic or first tone of the scale in which a piece or passage is written; the fundamental tone of the chord to which all the modulations of the piece are referred; -- called also key tone.
The top or head of anything.
The town city or country where a person is born; place of origin or birth in its more general sense.
The trachea or windpipe.
The track of man or beast as followed by the scent.
The trade of a baker.
The transmission of a disease from one person to another by direct or indirect contact.
The transoms knees beams keelson and other chief timbers used for connecting and strengthening the parts of a vessel.
The transparent part of the coat of the eyeball which covers the iris and pupil and admits light to the interior.
The treble; the highest vocal register; the highest kind of female or boy's voice; the upper part in harmony for mixed voices.
The tuft of hair on a man's lower lip and chin; -- so called from the style of beard of Napoleon III.
The turtledove.
The tusk of an animal by which the prey is seized and held or torn; a long pointed tooth; esp. one of the usually erectile venomous teeth of serpents. Also one of the falcers of a spider.
The tympanum.
The uncastrated male of swine; specifically the wild hog.

The uneasiness or pain of mind which is produced by the loss of any good real or supposed or by diseappointment in the expectation of good; grief at having suffered or occasioned evil; regret; unhappiness; sadness.

The unfaithfulness of a married person to the marriage bed; sexual intercourse by a married man with another than his wife or voluntary sexual intercourse by a married woman with another than her husband.
The union of man and woman as husband and wife; the nuptial state; marriage; wedlock.
The union of three persons (the Father the Son and the Holy Ghost) in one Godhead so that all the three are one God as to substance but three persons as to individuality.

The unit of heat according to the French standard; the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one kilogram (sometimes one gram) of water one degree centigrade or from 0ï¿½ to 1ï¿½. Compare the English standard unit Foot pound.
The unit of value and account in Japan. Since Japan's adoption of the gold standard in 1897 the value of the yen has been about 50 cents. The yen is equal to 100 sen.
The universe or universality of created things; -- so called from the order and harmony displayed in it.
The unlawful taking and carrying away of things personal with intent to deprive the right owner of the same; theft. Cf. Embezzlement.
The upper hand; advantage; superiority; mastery.
The upper layer of soil; surface soil.
The upper part; the top.
The upper side; the part that is uppermost.
The use of many words without necessity or with little sense; a superabundance of words; verbosity; wordiness.
The use of the bow and arrows in battle hunting etc.; the art practice or skill of shooting with a bow and arrows.
The use of the microscope; investigation with the microscope.
The use of the pen in writing; the art of writing; style or manner of writing; chirography.
The usual time of eating a meal.
The utmost; the highest or greatest degree; the farthest extent.
The vascular appendage which connects the fetus with the parent and is cast off in parturition with the afterbirth.
The vernacular language; one's mother tongue; often the common forms of expression in a particular locality.

The very large ovoid or roundish fruit of a cucurbitaceous plant (Citrullus vulgaris) of many varieties; also the plant itself. The fruit sometimes weighs many pounds; its pulp is usually pink in color and full of a sweet watery juice. It is a native of tropical Africa but is now cultivated in many countries.
The vessel which carries the commanding officer of a fleet or squadron and flies his distinctive flag or pennant.
The vessels or ware made by potters; earthenware glazed and baked.
The Virginia deer.
The virus of vaccinia used in vaccination.
The viscid tenacious substance which gives adhesiveness to dough.
The vitreous coating of pottery or porcelain; anything used as a coating or color in glazing.
The waist or bodice of a lady's dress.

The washing out or away of earth etc. especially of a portion of the bed of a road or railroad by a fall of rain or a freshet; also a place especially in the bed of a road or railroad where the earth has been washed away.
The waste which overlies good stone in a quarry.
The water course of a street; a little canal or channel; a gutter; also a puddle.
The water which falls in drops from the eaves of a house.
The watery portion of certain animal fluids as blood milk etc.
The wax secreted by bees and of which their cells are constructed.
The way or fashion of people at any particular time; temporary mode custom or practice; popular reception for the time; -- used now generally in the phrase in vogue.
The weight by which precious stones and pearls are weighed.
The western region or countries; the west.
The white substance consisting of an aggregation of bubbles which is formed on the surface of liquids or in the mouth of an animal by violent agitation or fermentation; froth; spume; scum.
The whole region or extent of country which contributes to the supply of a river or lake.
The whole; all the parts taken together.
The wife of an earl in the British peerage or of a count in the Continental nobility; also a lady possessed of the same dignity in her own right.
The wife of one's father by a subsequent marriage.
The wife or widow of a duke; also a lady who has the sovereignty of a duchy in her own right.
The windpipe or trachea; the weasand.
The windpipe.
The winner in a contest; one who gets the better of another in any struggle; esp. one who defeats an enemy in battle; a vanquisher; a conqueror; -- often followed by art rarely by of.
The withholding of belief; doubt; incredulity; skepticism.
The womb.
The wood of the agalloch.
The work belonging to housekeeping; especially kitchen work sweeping scrubbing bed making and the like.
The work of a knitter; the network formed by knitting.
The wrinkling of the brows or face in frowing; the expression of displeasure sullenness or discontent in the countenance; an angry frown.
The yard or inclosure attached to a barn or the space inclosed by the farm buildings.
The year last past; last year.
The yellow part of an egg; the vitellus.
The yellowish white opaque creamy matter produced by the process of suppuration. It consists of innumerable white nucleated cells floating in a clear liquid.
The young either larva or pupa of the mosquito; -- called also wiggletail.

The young aquatic larva of any amphibian. In this stage it breathes by means of external or internal gills is at first destitute of legs and has a finlike tail. Called also polliwig polliwog porwiggle or purwiggy.
The young birds hatched at one time; a hatch.
The young of a canine animal esp. of the common dog; a whelp.
The young of any animal of the Horse family (Equidae); a colt; a filly.
The young of some birds as grouse; a young fowl.
The young of the cow or of the Bovine family of quadrupeds. Also the young of some other mammals as of the elephant rhinoceros hippopotamus and whale.
The young of the equine genus or horse kind of animals; -- sometimes distinctively applied to the male filly being the female. Cf. Foal.
The young of the sheep.
The younger of two brothers; a younger brother or son; the youngest son.
Them
Thick and spreading like a bush.
Thick set with bristles or with hairs resembling bristles; rough.
Thick with haze; somewhat obscured with haze; not clear or transparent.
Thick; viscous.
Thin or transfer paper.
Thin; slender; small; minute.
Things remarkable and worthy of remembrance or record; also the record of them.
Thinly scattered; set or planted here and there; not being dense or close together.
Thoroughly bruised or broken.
Thoughtful sober or sad; employed in serious reflection; given to or favorable to earnest or melancholy musing.
Threefold; triple.
Thronged; crowded; also much occupied; busy.
Throwing back images.
Thrown into disorder; deranged.
Thunder.
Ticklish; easily tickled.
Tight; stretched; not slack; -- said esp. of a rope that is tightly strained.
Time beyond or in excess of a limit; esp. extra working time.
Time for play or diversion.
Timid; fearful.
